<HEADLINE>Actress hits out over `cruelty' of crackdown</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974798849</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ACTRESS Janet Suzman yesterday claimed the Government was behaving like ``a
wicked fairy in a pantomime'' over plans for a crackdown on bogus asylum
seekers.
Ms Suzman joined former Middle East hostage John McCarthy at a protest against
the controversial Immigration and Asylum Bill, which aims to streamline the
applications procedure and tighten up benefit rules. Ministers have stressed
that genuine refugees have nothing to fear.
However, Ms Suzman said at the demonstration outside the Commons: ``It seems so
cruel, when we have such a huge street problem of the homeless and mentally ill
anyway, that suddenly, like a wicked fairy in a pantomime, the Government waves
its wand and deposits thousands of people on the streets, the day this Bill is
passed.''
Under the proposed legislation, income support payments will not be made to
those who have been refused asylum, even though they may be appealing.
Ms Suzman said: ``This is a moral issue and the Home Secretary, Michael Howard,
should be ashamed of himself, because his grandfather came over here from some
East European country years ago.''
As part of the protest, actress Billie Whitelaw and eight children from George
Mitchell School in London's Waltham Forest performed a short play about a
Kurdish boy forced to flee his homeland.
</TEXT>
