<HEADLINE>Murder inquiry police appeal for witnesses</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KEITH SINCLAIR</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974798850</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
DETECTIVES in Renfrewshire launched a murder inquiry yesterday following what
was described as a vicious and unprovoked attack on a man who later died in
hospital.
Mr John McGrorey, 39, of Rankine Street, Johnstone, was found lying in the
town's Canal Road suffering from a serious head injury at about 9pm on Monday.
Mr McGrorey, who lived alone and was unemployed, was taken by ambulance to the
Royal Alexandra Hospital, Paisley, and later transferred to the Southern
General Hospital, Glasgow, where he died at about 9.30am yesterday.
Detective Sergeant David Hay said yesterday: ``This was a vicious and
completely unprovoked attack on a man who seemed to keep himself to himself.''
Detectives, who say there is no evidence to suggest the attack was
drugs-related, have appealed for anyone who may have been in the area of
Thornbrae, Campbell Street, or Canal Road, at about 9pm on Monday.
They would particularly like to speak to two men seen walking in the area at
the time and have urged anyone with information to contact them.
</TEXT>
