<HEADLINE>Forsyth plan backed</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Stephen McGregor,  Political Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974798851</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTTISH Secretary Michael Forsyth's plan to expand the role of the Scottish
Grand Committee was approved by MPs last night without a vote.
One of the changes will enable the committee comprising all Scotland's MPs to
question senior UK Cabinet Ministers. The Prime Minister is expected to give
evidence next month.
However, Opposition MPs including Shadow Scottish Secretary George Robertson,
said the changes fell far short of providing Scotland with a domestic
parliament to take over the handling of Scottish business from Westminster.
Mr Archy Kirkwood, for the Liberal Democrats, said he welcomed the changes if
they would lead to further measures.
For the Scottish National Party, Mr Andrew Welsh predicted that the committee
would be ``widely ignored in Scotland''.
</TEXT>
