<DATE>951220</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Parents' illness baffles doctors</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974798852</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MEDICAL experts are mystified why the parents of a seven-week-old baby who died
from meningitis had themselves become ill.
The parents, who have not been identified, are ``improving'' in hospital in
Newcastle upon Tyne.
Doctors have confirmed that one has meningitis, while the other is ``possibly''
suffering from the disease.
Neither has left Newcastle General Hospital since taking their baby to casualty
last Thursday. The child died within hours.
Dr Nicol Black, consultant in communicable disease control for Newcastle health
authority, said: ``We are still trying to piece it all together. A family case
like this is extremely unusual.
``The chance of parents becoming infected from their children is something like
that of being struck by lightning or a meteor,'' he said.
q Borders Health Board last night confirmed that a 12-month-old boy had been
admitted to Borders General Hospital suffering from meningococcal septicaemia.
Earlier this month two women were admitted to the hospital with meningococcal
meningitis. Both have now been released. Borders Health Board said the baby is
responding well to treatment.
</TEXT>
