<HEADLINE>Labour claims that people in Britain will be `astonished' by Minister's stance Bottomley backs lottery chief</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974798853</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LOTTERY watchdog Peter Davis is to keep his job, the National Heritage
Secretary Virginia Bottomley announced last night, much to the amazement of
opposition MPs.
The move followed days of speculation that he could face the sack after
admitting accepting free flights with the American company GTECH, a key Camelot
stakeholder.
Mrs Bottomley told Mr Davis yesterday afternoon: ``You retain my
confidence.......there is not, and never has been, any doubt about your
integrity.''
In a letter to him after the pair met at the department, Mrs Bottomley said he
had given an assurance that, in future, if he was involved in situations that
could lead to a conflict of interest with his role as regulator, he would seek
guidance from the department.
She made it clear: ``I do not think your acceptance of the flights was wise in
the context of your role as regulator of the lottery.''
Her statement followed a weekend of fevered rumours over Mr Davis's dealings
with GTECH, which has a 22.5% stake in lottery operator Camelot.
Mr Davis, director-general of Oflot, became embroiled in a row after his
admission to the Commons Public Accounts Committee last week that he accepted
flights in helicopters and private jets belonging to GTECH.
He also stayed at the Long Island home of the firm's non-executive director
Carl Menges, a family friend for 20 years.
Then on Monday, after Mr Davis was summoned to the Heritage Department for a
two-hour meeting with Mrs Bottomley, he emerged and declared he was ``going
back to work''.
However, his statement appeared to fuel a major Commons row and Shadow Heritage
Secretary Jack Cunningham warned Mrs Bottomley over the Despatch Box that many
people across Britain would be ``astonished'' if Mr Davis was allowed to stay
in his job.
He called on her to publish a code of conduct for the regulator and said there
was a case for an independent investigation of ``this whole sorry episode''.
Last night, Mrs Bottomley praised Mr Davis for his role in launching the
``highly successful lottery''.
Mrs Bottomley went on: ``You are making a full report on your overseas travel
and hospitality arrangements to the Public Accounts Committee. You have assured
me that there are no other issues which may come to light subsequently which
could affect my decision in this matter.
``I have told you that I do not think your acceptance of the flights was wise
in the context of your role as regulator of the lottery.''
Mr Davis said in a statement: ``I am grateful to the Secretary of State for her
expression of confidence in me as the regulator of the National Lottery.
``I am looking forward to continuing my work of ensuring that the National
Lottery is run properly, that players' interests are protected, and that the
maximum funds are raised for the good causes.''
Dr Cunningham said: ``Mrs Bottomley's decision will be greeted with incredulity
throughout Britain.
``A public watchdog who has defied the advice of senior civil servants and
closely involved himself with a private company of which he has the
responsibility of regulating cannot command public confidence.
``Mr Davis' lack of judgment has in turn exposed a serious flaw in the judgment
of the Secretary of State.''
Liberal Democrat national heritage spokesman Robert Maclennan said: ``This move
scarcely smacks of firm government. When her own department guidelines have
been flagrantly disobeyed regarding accepting hospitality, Virginia Bottomley
is apparently willing to turn a blind eye.
``Mr Davis is not fit to regulate a million pound business if he cannot
regulate his own behaviour.''
A Camelot spokeswoman said: ``It's not really for us to comment. It's a
Government matter.''
</TEXT>
