<HEADLINE>Euro-rebels inflict humiliating defeat on Government over stance on Brussels policy Fishing blow to Tories cheered</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>STEPHEN McGREGOR, Parliamentary Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974798854</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AMID dramatic scenes in the Commons last night, the Government was defeated
over its approach to fisheries policy.
It lost the crucial vote on how it would tackle this weekend's negotiations on
the common fisheries policy by 299 votes to 297, an Opposition majority of two.
Two Tories - Mr Michael Carttiss (Great Yarmouth) and Mr Bill Cash (Stafford) -
voted against the Government and 25 failed to vote for a variety of reasons,
including it is thought, 11 deliberate abstentions.
Jubilant Opposition MPs waved their order papers as the vote was declared,
while Agriculture Minister Douglas Hogg said the Government had listened to the
points raised and would give due weight to what had been said.
He said that Fisheries Minister Tony Baldry would, as always, represent the
interests of the UK and UK fishermen. However, from the Labour benches,
Agriculture spokesman Gavin Strang said that Mr Hogg's statement was ``just not
good enough.''
The Government's fisheries policy had failed, and the Commons had taken a
historic decision. He said: ``The Government has been defeated. It is all very
well for the Minister (Mr Hogg) to say that Ministers will pay due attention,
but the fact is that the House has rejected the Government's position on
fisheries policy.''
In reaching their decision, MPs rejected pleas from both Scottish Secretary
Michael Forsyth and Mr Baldry, who argued that inside or outside the CFP the
Government would fight for Britain's interests.
They also rejected what was described as a last-minute bribe, under which
Ministers promised #15m in the form of grants towards harbour works and
marketing schemes over the next three years, some of which is destined for
Scotland.
The acrimonious debate was opened by Mr Forsyth, who said he was the first to
acknowledge the level of concern in fishing communities, but argued the
difficulties could best be resolved from within the CFP. He was constantly
interrupted by Euro-sceptic MPs, notably Mr John Townend (Bridlington) who told
Mr Forsyth he could not be blamed for the ``betrayal'' of fisheries policy by
the former Tory Prime Minister Sir Edward Heath.
Sir Edward, hitting back in a later contribution, described Mr Townend's
remarks as ``abusive'' and bluntly told the House: ``I am not a traitor to my
country, whatever the Honourable Gentleman may think.''
Mr Forsyth's main point was that Mr Baldry, would be fighting hard to get the
best deal possible for UK fishermen at the talks which begin in Brussels
tomorrow.
The Minister said: ``I am well aware that many fishermen do not believe they
have been well served by the CFP. Most of them recognise that the CFP has not
been successful in conserving fish stocks.
``They feel their fishing rights are increasingly insecure because they believe
that the CFP is founded on a principle of equal access by all community
fishermen to fish stocks throughout the Community's waters.
``I understand this fear but I think it is exaggerated. We should not
underestimate our success in maintaining relative stability, in limiting access
to our territorial waters, in applying effective controls on Spanish access and
fishing effort in western waters. These are successes we have achieved within
the Community and which cut across the principle of equal access.''
For Labour, Dr Strang strongly criticised the Government over its handling of
fisheries policies over the years, notably its signing up to an agreement
allowing Spanish vessels into the Irish Box and allowing increased access for
Spanish fishing vessels to the waters to the west of the United Kingdom, which
presented ``an unacceptable threat to the economic viability of fishing
communities in England, Northern Ireland, Wales and Scotland.''
He claimed the Government had not effectively represented in Europe the
interests of the UK fishing industry and had failed to implement at home a
fisheries policy which was in the interests of the domestic industry.
Dr Strang said: ``I have spoken today to fishermens' leaders from Plymouth to
Lerwick and they support Labour's amendment. It is utterly unacceptable that we
should be decommissioning UK boats to facilitate access to UK waters by one of
European partners -in this case Spain. The real issues and real problems remain
unaddressed.''
Mr David Harris (St Ives - Con.), who represents a large fishing community in
the South-west of England, said that he was torn between the need to support
the Government and the wishes of his constituents.
Mr Jim Wallace (Orkney and Shetland - Lib Dem.) said a 200-mile fishing limit
was no solution to the problems facing the fishing industry.
He insisted there was no majority in the House for Britain to renege on its
international obligations and withdraw from the CFP.
``What is required is a thoroughgoing reform of the CFP and for proper
enforcement.''
SNP leader Alex Salmond urged would-be Tory rebels not to be ``bought cheaply''
and to hold out for bigger Government concessions.
Condemning Government ``failures'' in tackling the problems of over-fishing, he
said: ``Time and time again we have had a strategy by the fishing industry to
the Government and time and time again it has been greeted with deaf ears.
``If the Government is defeated this evening, there will be rejoicing in every
fishing port the length and breadth of Britain.''
Former whipless Tory Euro-rebel Christopher Gill (Ludlow) said the CFP was
``failing to protect fishing stocks, encouraging short-term exploitation at the
expense of genuine conservation, making criminals of otherwise honest people,
alienating public opinion, and perpetuating the situation in which a vital
British interest is compromised by the process of qualified majority voting''.
Mr John Wilkinson (Ruislip-Northwood - Con.) told the House that Ministers
should be required to signal to European partners the intention to establish a
200-mile exclusion zone and to leave the CFP, with the decision to be endorsed
by voters in a general election.
``The CFP is a busted flush and we should have no further part of it.''
Tory former leadership challenger John Redwood (Wokingham), intervened to say:
``Do you recognise that there are a lot of good Conservatives here tonight who
do not wish to give any comfort to the Labour Party on their political stunt,
but who are deeply worried about the state of the fishing industry?
``Is there more you can say about the robust stance you will take at the
Council and, if necessary, British action you might take after the Council so
that we stand up for British fishermen and not for Spanish ones?''
Mr Baldry replied: ``You can rest assured that I see my primary duty to this
House is to represent and stand up for the interests of the British fishing
industry.''
The Labour amendment accusing Ministers of failing to implement fisheries
policy in interests of UK, was defeated by 305 votes to 297, a Government
majority of eight.
However, the Government was defeated by two votes on its motion voicing support
for Ministers' intention to ``negotiate the best possible fishing opportunities
for British fishermen consistent with scientific advice and the need to sustain
the stocks''. Voting was 299 to 297.
q The Tories who did note vote were: Rupert Allason (Torbay), David Atkinson
(Bournemouth East) Spencer Batiste (Elmet), Nicholas Budgen (Wolverhampton
South-West), Dr Michael Clark (Rochford), Sir Julian Critchley (Aldershot),
Hugh Dykes (Harrow East), Harold Elletson (Blackpool North), Sir Peter Fry
(Wellingborough). Christopher Gill (Ludlow), Teresa Gorman (Billericay), Harry
Greenway (Ealing North), Tony Marlow (Northampton North), Sir Michael Marshall
(Arundel), David Porter (Waveney), Richard Shepherd (Aldridge-Brownhills),
Michael Spicer (Worcestershire South), Walter Sweeney (Vale of Glamorgan), Sir
Peter Tapsell (Lindsey East), Sir Teddy Taylor (Southend East), Peter Thurnham
(Bolton North-East), John Wilkinson (Ruislip-Northwood), David Wilshire
(Spelthorne) and Ann Winterton (Congleton). Whipless Tory Sir Richard Body also
did not vote.
</TEXT>
