<HEADLINE>Capital sticks to its colours</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>FRANCES HORSBURGH Local Government Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974798855</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IN a surprise move, the Labour leaders of the new City of Edinburgh Council
opted yesterday to stick with the traditional city colours of black and white,
with a dash of dark red, for the authority's new logo.
There had been speculation that dark blue or even dark green might be favoured
colours but, in the end, tradition prevailed.
The new corporate identity consists of the word Edinburgh in capital letters,
with a Celtic E and a Latin V, and underneath it the words ``The City of
Edinburgh Council''. An in-house team from Lothian region and Edinburgh
district created the design.
Labour leader Keith Geddes told the council that the cost of beginning the
transfer to the new identity would be limited to #100,000 this year.
It would take until the end of the century for all Lothian region and Edinburgh
District Council signs to be changed.
A report explained that a figure of #400,000 for establishing a new logo, which
had caused a previous row, related to the amount required if a more complete
implementation of the new identity were to be undertaken.
</TEXT>
