<DOCNO>GH951220-000007</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951220-000007</DOCID>
<DATE>951220</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Dewar marshals troops to good effect</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>STUART TROTTER Political Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974798856</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LAST night's victory tasted sweet for Mr Donald Dewar, MP for Garscadden, and
Opposition Chief Whip since the beginning of the session.
One Scots Labour MP said: ``When I saw Donald wearing his Sunday School face I
knew we were going to win.'' The ``Sunday School face'' means Mr Dewar is
looking marginally less pessimistic than usual.
In a vote where victory was tantalisingly near with the Government majority
down to five and many discontented Tory MPs, Mr Dewar marshalled the Labour
vote aided by three Labour back benchers, Mr Dale Campbell-Savours
(Workington), Mr Martin Redmond (Don Valley), and Mr John Fraser (Norwood).
The latter was in a neck brace after breaking a back vertebrae after being
knocked down by a car. He struggled in, despite being very ill.
Without the Tory rebels the Opposition could not have done it, but Mr Dewar was
already winning high opinions from those who wondered if Mr Blair had blundered
in putting one of the party's best despatch box performers in a backroom job,
however important.
However the reality of victory, with the prospect of more, as the Government's
majority seems set to inexorably fall, has buoyed party morale at the end of a
year which has finished disastrously for the Government and with the prospect
for Labour that it may not have to wait as long as 1997 to find itself in
office.
Mr Dewar's appointment has also been seen as a reassurance to the Scottish
party that Labour will indeed deliver a Scottish parliament at long last. It is
becoming recognised that few men are better equipped to steer the Scotland Bill
through what could prove some rough passages in the Commons.
With an important input into policy making, Mr Dewar now ranks as one of the
small band around Mr Blair on whom the electoral success of the party rests.
</TEXT>
