<HEADLINE>Scot charged in US over  trade embargo to Libya</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974798857</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A SCOTTISH businessman was yesterday charged in a Boston court with violating
the US embargo against Libya by attempting to export more than $250,000
(#166,000) worth of computers and related equipment.
Mr David McKeeve, 36, from Glasgow, and the company for which he worked, McNeil
International of Edinburgh, are accused of submitting false information to
shipping agents and the US Customs Service.
McNeil International is unlisted in the Edinburgh phone book. Its telephone
number is ex-directory.
Mr McKeeve said the shipments were destined initially for Cyprus and later for
Ethiopia.
The court said his intended recipient was actually Libya, which was placed on
the US embargo list in 1986.
If convicted, Mr McKeeve faces up to 20 years in prison and a fine of $550,000
(#366,000).
In January 1986, the then President Ronald Reagan ordered the rupture of
economic and commercial relations with Libya and froze all Libyan assets in the
United States.
The move followed US accusations that Libya harboured and trained members of
the Abu Nidal group believed to be responsible for attacks at Rome and Vienna
airports.
Since the 1988 Lockerbie bombing, which killed 270 people, Washington has
sought a worldwide oil embargo against Libya to force Tripoli to hand over two
alleged Libyan agents sought in connection with the bombing.
</TEXT>
