<DATE>951220</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Tears as family ask for help to catch murderer We've got to find out, says father</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DAVID STEELE, KIRSTY SCOTT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974798858</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A FATHER shattered by grief at the savage killing of his teenage daughter
yesterday made an anguished plea for the public to help police track down her
murderer.
Mr Philip Julyan, his voice cracking with emotion and with tears welling,
called on anyone who might have seen his daughter, Mhairi, during the last
fateful minutes as she made her way home from a panto, to come forward.
The 16-year-old schoolgirl went missing on Saturday night after watching
Sleeping Beauty at Kilmarnock's Palace Theatre with friends. After an
intensive
police search her body was found in a bus depot just a few hundred yards from
her home in Samson Avenue.
The Julyan family - father Philip, mother Maureen, both 46, and sister Claire,
21, - yesterday took the brave step of subjecting themselves to the ordeal of
a
news conference to help police in the murder hunt.
As he hugged his wife and daughter, Mr Julyan, visibly distraught, said: ``I
make this appeal in the hope that someone may have seeen Mhairi on Saturday
night when she left the Palace Theatre on her way home. And even during
Saturday night or even Sunday to come forward to let the police know and even
if anyone knows anything at all.
``Just come forward and let the police know. We've got to find out. We must.
Thanks.''
Police have established that Mhairi left the Palace Theatre around 9.30pm and
set off in a happy frame of mind after an enjoyable evening out with her best
friend, Julie-Ann Holland, to make her way home. It was a journey which should
have taken 10 to 15 minutes, but one she did not complete.
Her worried parents phoned a friends and when she could not be traced police
were alerted. They began a series of searches of the area. The grim discovery
of her body lying in a floor well in the Stagecoach Western Scottish bus depot
in McKinlay Place was made on Sunday afternoon.
Julie-Ann Holland described yesterday how she went out searching for Mhairi
after Mrs Julyan called the Hollands to say she had not returned home.
``As soon as I found out she was missing, we went out. We went to the
nightclubs, because her mum thought she maybe had gone there, but I knew all
the time that she would not be there. We went to all the parks, me and the
rest
of her pals.''
Julie-Ann's mother, Mrs Jane Holland, said her daughter had started screaming
when she found out that Mhairi was missing. ``We knew straight away really,''
said Mrs Holland. ``She would not have spoken to a
stranger. I'm just really, really angry and I just want whoever has done it to
be caught.''
Julie-Ann and Mhairi had been friends since the age of six and had been
together at the pantomime on Saturday night. The Hollands had waved her off on
the steps of the theatre after she decided to walk home.
``She went away laughing and joking,'' said Julie-Ann. ``She had really got
into the swing of the pantomime, shouting out and all that. At times she was
the only one you could hear.''
Another friend, 15-year-old Louise, said Mhairi was often described as quiet,
but was a popular girl who would hang around with the other youngsters in the
parks and always had a good word for everyone. ``She was really nice, you
know.
And I know that she wanted a lot out of life.''
Prayers were said at Kilmarnock Academy yesterday for their dead schoolmate
and
staff and pupils observed a minute's silence in her memory. Many of Mhairi's
closest friends were not there. They have been unable to return to school
since
the tragedy and some are receiving counselling.
The Rev Tom Jarvie, the school chaplain, spoke of the deep sense of loss which
the school and the community at large was feeling.
Detective Chief Inspector Bob Lauder, the man leading the hunt, said yesterday
that the attack on Mhairi appeared to have been sexually motivated and had
been
``particularly brutal and savage''.
He was not prepared to discuss how she had died, but said his team were not
looking for a murder weapon.
Mr Lauder added: ``I do not wish to instil panic but it would be irresponsible
to ignore the fact that it could happen again. I would ask parents to have a
heightened awareness of where their children, even adolescents, are at this
time of year when there is so much going on.''
Mr Lauder has so far ruled out any connection with any other unsolved case,
including the murder of Miss Shona Stevens in Irvine in November 1994 which is
still being investigated by detectives under his command.
He added: ``It is absolutely vital that anyone who has even the slightest
shred
of information gets in touch. It may be that they saw Mhairi at some stage or
it may be that they saw something suspicious in the area on Saturday night or
Sunday morning.''
Mr Lauder said the killer may have been bloodstained and there was a ``very
real possibility'' that he may have had local knowledge. He urged anyone who
was unhappy or uncomfortable about someone's behaviour to contact him in
confidence.
Mhairi's likely route would have taken her along London Road, past the Jet
filling station, into Middlemass Drive then into McKinlay Crescent beside the
bus depot.
She was wearing a black, Hoi Polloi bomber jacket, dark trousers, a purple
flowery blouse and black boots. Her curly ginger hair may have been tied in a
clasp.
</TEXT>
