<HEADLINE>Fast reaction to finance investigation</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JOHN MacCALMAN Municipal Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974798859</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IT took Labour councillors less than 30 seconds to consider the results of a
10-month investigation of financial irregularity in a number of community
projects in Easterhouse in Glasgow.
The report, which has been passed to Strathclyde Police, reveals an
unacceptable absence of financial records and a failure to account properly for
at least #12,000 of public funds.
It further points out that disciplinary procedures have already been set in
train against two community volunteers, one of whom is an elected member of the
new City of Glasgow unitary authority.
Due to pressures of business and a bereavement, there were no opposition
members present at yesterday's meeting of the community action committee.
Town clerk Thomas Monaghan opened the meeting by saying there was one item on
the agenda. Convener Christine Devine then asked committee members if they
wished to accept the recommendations. They responded: ``Agreed!'' And it was
all over.
Last night, however, Militant Group leader Councillor Thomas Sheridan
threatened to expose the two community volunteers unless action was taken
against them.
The auditor's report examined the affairs of Cranhill Community Council,
Greater Easterhouse Theatre Company, Cranhill Youth Forum, and Healthy Cities
projects.
</TEXT>
