<HEADLINE>Rebels cast a `no' vote The Tories sink to defeat on fishing</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>GEOFFREY PARKHOUSE, STEPHEN McGREGOR</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974798861</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Government last night slumped to a humiliating Commons defeat as its
approach to fisheries policy was defeated by two votes.
It was the culmination of the anger of bankrupt British fishermen building up
over the past two years.
A combination of Tory MPs representing fishermen throughout the UK and
Euro-sceptics challenged the Prime Minister to deliver a better European Union
deal.
The Tories, supported by Ulster Unionists and others, defeated the Labour
Party's outright challenge by eight votes. However, the Government went down by
two votes, 299-297, on its own motion 48 hours before Fisheries Minister Tony
Baldry goes into negotiations in Brussels which will decide who is allowed to
fish where and on what quotas.
The Commons debate was on a technical motion and therefore has no impact on
legislation. However, when Agriculture Minister Douglas Hogg said the
Government would take ``due weight on what has happened tonight'' he was jeered.
It was a moral victory for UK fishermen against what they regard as a sell-out
to Europe on their fishing quotas and the challenge from Spanish and other
fleets in what they consider their home waters.
Tory Euro-sceptics intervened against the Government to emphasise their message
to Mr Major that they are still severely critical of his whole European policy.
The Tories would not support the Labour Party in what they regarded as a
cynical amendment to the fisheries debate and so, despite eight Scottish and
Welsh Nationalist votes, the Labour amendment was thrown out by eight votes.
However, when it came to the Government's motion which insists that
conservation is the key issue, all the pent-up frustration on the Tory back
benches was expressed.
The two-vote defeat does not change anything in UK and European legislation,
but it was a loud declaration the country is deeply dissatisfied by the laying
up of boats from Peterhead to Newlyn in Cornwall.
In the last Commons vote before Christmas, Government Ministers were hoping
they could slip through on a mere technical vote on conservation.
Euro-sceptic Michael Forsyth, the Scottish Secretary, was put up by the
Government in the debate instead of Cabinet colleague Douglas Hogg in order to
minimise Tory defections. In this, Mr Forsyth succeeded in confining the defeat
to merely two votes.
Opposition MPs waved their order papers as the result was declared, and Labour
leader Tony Blair said the Government was increasingly unable to govern.
A total of 13 Tory MPs failed to support the Government in the crucial vote,
which came at the end of an acrimonious debate. Mr William Cash (Stafford) and
Mr Michael Cartiss (Great Yarmouth) voted with Labour, 11 abstained, while
others were absent through illness or on overseas trips.
Both Mr Forsyth and Mr Baldry insisted they would fight for the best interests
of the fishing industry in the negotiations and said that, inside or outside
the Common Fisheries Policy, there would have to be a reduction in fishing
effort because there were too many boats chasing too few fish.
The Ministers even tried to buy off the rebellion by announcing at the last
minute a #15m plan to give grants to harbour works and marketing schemes, about
#2.5m of which would have come to Scotland. The concession, however, was not
enough.
Labour's agriculture spokesman, Mr Gavin Strang, said the Government's
fisheries policy had failed and that the Commons had taken ``a historic
decision''.
Mr Blair said: ``The Government is unravelling. It is unable to lead. It is
increasingly unable to represent Britain, it is increasingly unable to govern.
``The leadership election changed absolutely nothing and so we see the
parliamentary year ending as it began: incompetence, division, and chaos.
``The Tories' divisions over Europe now run so deep that they have reduced
Government policy to a state of virtual paralysis. Because he never stood up to
his rebels, the Prime Minister is unable to control them. Because he has never
made his own views clear, he allows both sides of the European divide to claim
him as their own.''
SNP leader Alex Salmond said: ``This is an important defeat for the Government
and an important victory for the fishing communities. It is all the more
damaging for the Government's credibility because the issue cuts across the
fault line of Europe in the Tory Party.
``The reaction in the fishing communities around Scotland will be one of
celebration that finally, after years of neglect and betrayal, the Government
fisheries Ministers have finally got their come-uppance.''
The Liberal Democrats' deputy leader, Mr Alan Beith, said: ``The House of
Commons has rightly insisted on a much tougher line in support of our fishermen
and the country will see this as a further demonstration that this Government
must go.''
Lib-Dem fisheries spokesman and Scottish leader Jim Wallace, the MP for Orkney
and Shetland, said: ``Tonight's vote shows conclusively that the Government has
lost the confidence of the people in its dealings with fishing policy. It was a
reflection of years of neglect of the fishing industry.''
</TEXT>
