<DOCNO>GH951220-000013</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951220-000013</DOCID>
<DATE>951220</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Libel case MP facing ruin</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974798862</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TORY MP David Ashby was last night surveying the ruins of his life as the
dramatic loss of a libel action effectively left him branded a homosexual,
liar, and hypocrite.
The Leicestershire North West MP broke down and sobbed after a High Court jury
dismissed his claim by a majority verdict, and left him facing a legal bill
estimated at up to #500,000.
However, the Sunday Times in-house lawyer Alastair Brett said he expected the
paper to ``show magnanimity'' in its victory.
Mr Ashby, 55, brushed aside an attempt by his wife Sylvana - who offered
damning evidence against him during the 20-day trial - to offer commiserations.
She crossed the court and kissed him on the back of his neck. But he pushed her
away as she attempted to put an arm around him and snapped: ``Just leave me
alone.''
The action arose from a damages claim against the Sunday Times over an article
which claimed Mr Ashby was having a homosexual affair with neighbour Dr Ciaran
Kilduff.
Mr Ashby claimed the article made him out to be not only a homosexual, but a
liar over his relationship with Dr Kilduff and a hypocrite for stressing the
importance of family values in his last election address to voters.
Two hours after the verdict, Mr Ashby astonished cheering colleagues by
appearing in the Commons.
</TEXT>
