<DATE>951220</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Christmas gift of liberty for jailed asylum seeker</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BRUCE McKAIN Law Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974798863</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A SCOTS bride broke down in tears yesterday after a judge gave her an early
Christmas present by allowing her to be reunited with her Nigerian husband.
Mr Peter Nwokoye is being detained in Saughton Prison, Edinburgh, pending a
judicial review of a decision by the immigration authorities to refuse to grant
him political asylum.
He fears political persecution if he is sent back to Ogoniland, a homeland he
shared with Nobel Peace Prize nominee Ken Saro-Wiwa, who was recently executed
by the Nigerian Government.
Lord Milligan decided yesterday that Mr Nwokoye could be released pending a
court hearing of his case, provided his wife Tracy lodged #1000 security with
the court.
Mr Nwokoye, 35, arrived in the UK in 1991 and was at first allowed to remain
for six months. That was later extended, and in June this year he applied for
political asylum.
That was refused in July this year and he is seeking a judicial review of that
decision. He has been detained in prison for the past six months.
Advocate Mungo Bovey appeared for Mr Nwokoye at the Court of Session yesterday
to ask for interim liberation for his client pending the judicial review.
He said that Mr Nwokoye feared persecution because of the current situation in
Ogoniland. His client claimed there had been a rebellion in his village against
the decision of the Government and Shell Oil to destroy houses and take over
the land to enable oil prospecting to take place.
Mr Nwokoye alleged that two of his brothers had been imprisoned because of
protests and his mother was in hospital because of injuries she had suffered
during riots.
He argued that he should be treated as a refugee and granted asylum in Britain
under the UN Convention.
Lord Milligan was told that on September 22 this year Mr Nwokoye married a
Scots bank clerk, Miss Tracy McPherson, 26, who was unwilling to go to Nigeria
to live in the present climate of fear.
Mr Bovey said that she visited her husband three times a week in prison.
Mr Nwokoye had already been detained for about six months and if he was not
granted interim liberation now he could be left in prison for another six
months before his judicial review could be heard.
Lord Milligan said he was willing to grant Mr Nwokoye his freedom, but there
had to be a sufficient deterrent for him not to abscond if he were released
from prison.
He imposed a condition that #1000 be lodged as security with the court and that
Mr Nwokoye should report to the police in Edinburgh three times a week.
Speaking from the couple's home in Downfield Place, Dalry, Edinburgh, after the
hearing Mrs Nwokoye said: ``I can't believe it. I'm never going to have another
Christmas present like this.''
She had left her home late yesterday afternoon to lodge the #1000 required to
secure her husband's liberty, but was disappointed to learn he would not be
released immediately.
``I'm disappointed, but I know he's definitely going to be released tomorrow.''
However, she said the battle to save her husband from deportation was not over.
``The fight is still going on. The real case is the deportation issue.
``Last week there was a Channel 4 documentary called Delta Force which had
pictures of my husband's village. It has been totally razed. I'm not going to
let him go back to that,'' she said.
</TEXT>
