<DATE>951220</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Army officer disciplined over 'copter golf trip</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974798866</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A LIEUTENANT-colonel who requisitioned an Army helicopter for a golf trip has
been disciplined and procedures tightened to prevent a recurrence of such an
incident, the Government announced last night.
The member of the Third Battalion, the Highland Regiment was one of two
officers taken by Gazelle helicopter to a tournament in May.
Armed Forces Minister Nicholas Soames said in a Commons written reply that
inquiries by the Royal Military Police in Edinburgh had been completed and
considered by the Army chain of command.
``A Gazelle helicopter deviated from its task to take two Army officers to a
golf tournament,'' he said.
``There was no dishonest intent on the part of the officer responsible. He did,
however, make an error of judgment and he has been subject to the appropriate
disciplinary action.
A MoD spokesman declined to specify what action had been taken, but confirmed
it had not involved demotion or court-martial.
He emphasised that no blame had attached to the pilot of the helicopter.
</TEXT>
