<DOCNO>GH951220-000018</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951220-000018</DOCID>
<DATE>951220</DATE>
<HEADLINE>New pill scare sparks requests for abortions</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974798867</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
NEARLY 30 women have asked for abortions in the past week after becoming
pregnant in the wake of the latest contraceptive pill scare, Britain's biggest
abortion charity reported yesterday.
It was a ``small but significant'' start to a period in which growing numbers
of women are expected to report unplanned pregnancies after stopping taking
their usual pill, according to the British Pregnancy Advisory Service.
``It is very early days yet and any surge in demand will be starting to show
from now,'' said chief executive Ian Jones.
BPAS, which carries out more than one in three abortions outside the NHS, was
monitoring the aftermath of the official warning two months ago that one and a
half million women should switch to safer brands of pill, he said.
Government scientists alerted doctors and pharmacists to findings that seven
brands carried twice the usual risk of causing blood clots in leg veins.
Their official letter recommended that women should finish their monthly course
before switching brands.
However, GPs and others, critical of the way the warning was made public,
immediately expressed concern that many unwanted pregnancies would result from
women dropping their regular pill before arranging to start a replacement.
That concern was now being borne out, said Mr Jones.
``We do expect an increase in the numbers giving the pill scare as the reason
for their pregnancy but it is too early to have much idea of the scale,'' added
Mr Jones.
The phenomenon was being monitored nationally by the seven BPAS clinics on a
computer-linked system, he said. It was hoped to link this with studies.
The research had to take into account the fact that one of the most common
reasons given by women for unwanted pregnancy was a switch in contraceptive
methods, usually because the pill they were taking did not suit them.
There was also a seasonal rise in demand for abortions in the post-Christmas
period, he said.
The biggest scare over the contraceptive pill, a decade ago, had led to an 8%
rise in demand for abortions, said Mr Jones. BPAS was currently carrying out
30,000 abortions a year.
</TEXT>
