<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951220-000019</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951220-000019</DOCID>
<DATE>951220</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Private prison adviser namedC</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JAMES FREEMAN, Home Affairs Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974798868</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE job of advising the Scottish Prison Service team on the operational
specification for Scotland's first private prison has been given to Mr Alec
Spencer, governor of Peterhead prison.
The 500-prisoner, category B jail will be built under the Private Finance
Initiative and run under a Scottish Prison Service contract by private
operators.
It is to be built on one of three sites, most probably close to the existing
Low Moss prison at Bishopbriggs.
Mr Spencer, 49, will be responsible for specifying such matters as security
standards, regimes, and medical and educational facilities at the jail which
private contractors would then have to meet.
His post at Peterhead is to be filled by the governor of Aberdeen prison, Mr
Bill Rattray, 43. In another move, Mr Bill McKinlay, governor in charge at HM
Young Offenders' Institution at Polmont, is to become governor of Shotts prison
when the current governor, Mr George Shearer, retires in May.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951220-000020</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951220-000020</DOCID>
<DATE>951220</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Private finance behind new road projects</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CHRIS HOLME</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974798869</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTTISH Secretary Michael Forsyth yesterday announced a major building
programme to improve Scotland's road network, with more than half the money
coming through the Private Finance Initiative.
A total of 17 schemes costing #450m will start over the next three years,
including long-awaited by-passes and three major motorway upgrades funded
through #257m from the PFI.
The announcement was welcomed warmly by industry and motoring organisations as
a significant success in strengthening the Scottish road network, but greeted
with dismay by some environmental groups, including Friends of the Earth.
The first PFI roads project will be the last 18-mile section of the A74 in
Scotland to motorway standard.
Under the scheme, which was used for the new Skye Bridge, private firms
undertake to design, build, finance and operate the project.
The advantage to the Government is that it does not have to find the huge
capital investment itself but it pays back over a period of time to the private
consortium. The Scottish Secretary remains the owner of the bridge or stretch
of road.
``It's a bit like buying something on hire purchase,'' said David Begg,
lecturer in transport economics at Napier University and also Lothian Regional
Council's transportation committee convener.
``It seems to be a short-term way out of the financial difficulties for the
Scottish Office. It could mean the taxpayer paying up to 20% more for a given
road improvement, compared to conventional financing.''
PFI will also be used for upgrading the M8 from Baillieston to Newhouse and the
M80 from Stepps to Cumbernauld.The latter is likely to be strongly opposed by
conservationists, eager to protect important habitats in the Kelvin Valley.
The remainder of the programme includes dualling of the A1 between Haddington
and Dunbar, a notorious stretch for accidents, improvements to the A75
Stranraer Euro-route, A9, and bypasses at Kintore and Dalkeith.
Mr Forsyth said: ``The trunk road network is of vital importance to the
continuing health of Scotland's economy. Our strategy is to give priority to
the key routes of major importance to the economy and my new plans will ensure
further rapid progress in that strategy."
Both the RAC and the AA said the announcement was a welcome recognition by the
Government of the importance of the road network to Scotland.
Mr Iain McMillan, director of CBI Scotland, said the schemes were good news for
business. ``We have lobbied long and hard to ensure a sound infrastructure for
Scotland. The completion of the M74 and of the Baillieston to Newhouse section
of the M8 are two key priorities,'' he added.
q Eight of the schemes approved yesterday are due to start during the next two
years: the A74 upgrade of the last 18-mile section in Scotland still not
motorway standard (PFI), M8 Newbridge underpass, M90 Halbeath interchange, A96
Kintore by-pass, A96 Blackburn bypass, A9 Logie Easter, A68 Dalkeith bypass.
and the A830 Loch Nan Uamh to Polnish bridge.
Nine are planned to start between April 1997 and March 1999: the M8 Baillieston
to Newhouse (PFI) including Newhouse to Shotts, junctions 5-6 (PFI), M80 Stepps
to Cumbernauld (PFI), M77 Fenwick to Floak, A1 Haddington to Dunbar, A830
Arisaig to Kinsadel, A828 Creagan Bridge, A75 The Glen and the A92 Balmedie to
Tipperty.
</TEXT>
