<DOCNO>GH951220-000021</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951220-000021</DOCID>
<DATE>951220</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Major's remark puzzles Brussels</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>MURRAY RITCHIE European Editor</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974798870</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Brussels
Prime Minister John Major's remark that a clause in the Maastricht treaty's
timetable for a single currency is ``no longer operative'' had the European
Commission in confusion yesterday.
Mr Major alarmed back-bench critics of the EU on Monday when he told Labour's
veteran Euro-sceptic, Mr Peter Shore, that sterling's membership of the
European exchange rate mechanism (ERM) was no longer a factor in monetary union.
Mr Shore had argued that Britain could not join the planned single currency in
1999 because Maastricht required entrants to have been in the ERM for at least
two years.
Mr Major has said Britain will not put the pound back into the ERM in the
present Parliament. He told the Commons that membership no longer applied as a
qualification for the single currency ``because the ERM that existed at the
time no longer exists''.
This met with a neutral reaction yesterday from the Commission, which normally
talks in spirited terms about the inevitability of monetary union and the
observance of Maastricht's convergence criteria for those wishing to join the
single currency.
Maastricht's wording is ambiguous, stating only that a member state must
respect the normal fluctuation margins in the ERM for two years without severe
tensions or voluntary devaluations if it is to join the single currency.
Many observers take the view that Mr Major is correct. The EU would be highly
unlikely to exclude any currency wishing to join in monetary union if it met
all the criteria without formal membership of the ERM.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951220-000022</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951220-000022</DOCID>
<DATE>951220</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Hearing told of death threat to refugee</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974798871</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A NIGERIAN political refugee seeking asylum in Britain would be targeted by
government death squads if he returned home, it was claimed yesterday. A former
Nigerian army chief told an immigration appeal hearing in Glasgow that the
country's military dictatorship would execute human rights campaigner Akin
Adegboye without a trial.
Colonel Tony Nyiam told Mr Mungo Deans, the special adjudicator hearing the
case, that Mr Adegboye's life was at risk because of his close links with
pro-democracy factions within the armed forces.
``It would be even more dangerous for Akin to go home than for me. If I am
caught, at least there would be some form of trial. They would just eliminate
him,'' he said.
Mr Adegboye, 36, of Wester Hailes, Edinburgh, and his Nigerian wife, Teju, are
appealing against deportation orders and are claiming political asylum because
they fear persecution and death if they return.
Mr Paul Seils, the Scottish Refugee Council lawyer representing Mr Adegboye,
said the Home Office's decision to refuse asylum to Mr Adegboye was because it
deemed his activities not to be serious enough.
``I don't think they had the right information, or they would not have said
that,'' Col Nyiam said.
The hearing is expected to finish today with a written decision due in January.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951220-000023</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951220-000023</DOCID>
<DATE>951220</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Seasonal greetings are on the chilly side</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Stuart Trotter</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>commons sketch</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974798872</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WHEN Santa Major wished him a ``Happy 1995'' last year, Ebenezer Blair snarled
back: ``Humbug. Bunkum.'' He knew what was coming and yesterday he told us.
The Prime Minister's year had ended as it had begun, he thundered, ``in
weakness, chaos and incompetence.'' Yes, dear reader, the Spirit of Christmas,
who had attempted an early entry to the Palace of Westminster on Budget Day to
be fobbed off with a cut-price bottle of Scotch, couldn't even get inside the
door for the last Prime Minister's Questions before Christmas.
The pantomime element of the season survived. Mr David Shaw (Dover - Con.) was
hissed even more than usual by Labour as he rose to ask his question. Appearing
to revel in his Demon King role he got his own back by making the question an
extremely long one including the festive accusation that the Opposition is soft
on drugs.
The Tory children then gave Mr Paddy Ashdown, whom they seem to dislike more
than any of Labour's star performers, an ever ruder reception. Like Mr Shaw, Mr
Ashdown seems to enjoy enraging his critics and regularly succeeds in winding
up the Prime Minister, normally a mild-mannered Clark Kent figure who mislaid
his Superman gear in 1992.
Mr Blair's scriptwriters had gone into overdrive for his last Commons
performance of the year and handed him a multi-layered soundbite which fitted
in railway privatisation, unhealthy prisons, Tory divisions on Europe and
failure to run the National Lottery right. And that wasn't Mr Major's year -
that was just this week.
The Leader of the Opposition has been soundbiting away at him all year and,
with most of the ammunition provided by HMG, one almost expects the Prime
Minister to come from behind the despatch box with his hands up saying ``I
surrender''.
But no. Despite this deluge of soundbites going into every television
set-owning home in the land, Clark Major refuses to give in. Each session ends
with him clinging to the despatch box by his fingertips ready to go another
round.
Mr Blair sneered at the #1bn to be spent in two years on promoting rail
privatisation. It would have been better spent on improving the services.
Mr Major replied that Railtrack was to invest #10bn in the infrastructure and
enquired where Labour would have found that kind of money from. Mr Blair said
it could make a start with the #1bn the Government had wasted which, as Mr
Major, a former Chancellor of the Exchequer, pointed out, left him #9bn short.
Supportive Labour barrackers roared, ``Where, where?'' when the Prime Minister
apparently incautiously announced that some services already were improving. He
let them go on until they were hooked and then told them that 100 extra trains
had been added to Rail Southwest's timetable.
Faced with this soundbite-blunting defence, Mr Blair fell back on demanding a
guarantee that the existing level of services would not be cut - a guarantee BR
was never able to deliver - and dragged in VAT increases from somewhere in the
wings, a signal that the soundbite assault had failed to roll over the
objective.
Because we were one day short of breaking up for Christmas, things were a bit
rowdier - the children get excited about this time - but Prime Minister's
Questions is a form of trench warfare and, as it was on the Western Front, will
be, let us hope, mitigated over the actual day by signs of goodwill among the
resting combatants.
</TEXT>
