<DOCNO>GH951220-000024</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951220-000024</DOCID>
<DATE>951220</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Sleeping-bag vigil pays off for MPs</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Stephen McGregor,   Political Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974798873</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FIVE Liberal Democrat MPs have won the right to present all five Ten Minute
Rule Bills for which time was allocated in the Commons next month - by camping
out in sleeping bags in a Commons attic corridor last week to come first in the
queue.
They did it partly to ensure that the five subjects they chose get an airing
and also to highlight what they regard as the absurd procedures for determining
who wins the right to present such a Bill and make a 10-minute speech in
support of it.
Mr Archy Kirkwood (Roxburgh and Berwickshire), Mr Chris Davies (Littleborough
and Saddleworth), Mr Simon Hughes (Southwark and Bermondsey), Mr David Rendel
(Newbury) and Mr Paul Tyler (North Cornwall) spent last Thursday night in
sleeping bags. They were sustained by regular supplies of food and drink by
supporters and slept as best they could through the nearby chimes of Big Ben.
THE Government aims to safeguard the interests of the British steel industry in
a row over EU aid for Irish Steel, the Prime Minister insisted yesterday. He
was responding in the Commons to Liberal Democrat leader Paddy Ashdown, who
called on the Prime Minister to say if he fully understood ``the damage that
could be done to British-Irish relations at a very crucial moment in the Irish
peace process''.
THE Prime Minister yesterday reaffirmed his Government's opposition to
legalising drugs, insisting he had ``no intention'' of lifting the ban on
cannabis.
Such a move was not the right way to proceed, he said
SPENDING by the Prime Minister's office has fallen, Mr Major disclosed last
night. The total cost in 1994-95, covering items including travel, telephones,
entertainment, staff and office refurbishment, was #7.67m, compared with #9.22m
the previous year, he said in a written reply.
</TEXT>
