<DOCNO>GH951220-000025</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951220-000025</DOCID>
<DATE>951220</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Assisted places `to stay'</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Stephen McGregor, Parliamentary Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974798874</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE schools' assisted places scheme is here to stay, Scottish Education
Minister Raymond Robertson said yesterday.
The issue was raised in a Commons committee the day after Scottish Secretary
Michael Forsyth announced plans for expanding the scheme in Scotland.
From the Labour Front Bench, Mrs Helen Liddell said that the scheme had risen
in cost from #800,000 in 1981-82 to #10.6m now.
She said: ``In government, we will phase out this scheme because we believe it
is inequitable and elitist and is an implied attack on the Scottish education
system.''
However, Mr Robertson said the case for the scheme was very strong and that the
Government was determined to continue it. It improved quality and standards,
widened the choice available to parents regardless of their income, expanded
opportunities for children and widened the social mix.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951220-000026</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951220-000026</DOCID>
<DATE>951220</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Ulster talks go on</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Geoffrey Parkhouse</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974798875</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Prime Minister and Irish Premier John Bruton plan to meet in Dublin
tomorrow to try to keep the peace momentum going.
Last night, Mr Major and the Ulster Unionist leader David Trimble spent an hour
at No. 10 discussing Ulster Unionist ideas for reinstating a Belfast assembly,
(writes Geoffrey Parkhouse).
The Ulster Unionists, who are now crucial to Mr Major's majority in the
Commons, are suggesting that a Belfast assembly could be the way forward to
allow them to talk to Sinn Fein in parallel with efforts now being made by the
independent commission headed by ex-US senator George Mitchell and his team -
who were in Dublin yesterday - to find a way to decommission IRA weapons.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951220-000027</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951220-000027</DOCID>
<DATE>951220</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Watson fails to vote</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>STUART TROTTER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974798876</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
GLASGOW Central MP Mike Watson was in hot water last night after failing to
vote in the crucial division while unpaired.
A Labour Whip, confirming to The Herald Mr Watson had not been paired, said:
``If you contact him before I do, tell him I want a word.''
Mr Watson returned on Monday from Barcelona,
where he went after his controversial selection last week as prospective
candidate for the Glasgow Govan constituency in which his opponent, Mr
Mohammed
Sarwar, contested the way the votes were counted.
When Mr Watson did not appear at Westminster yesterday Labour Whips began
frantic attempts to contact him before the vote but failed to do so.
He now faces a disciplinary meeting with Chief Whip Donald Dewar for failing
to
obey a three-line whip.
Last Thursday, Mr Watson was embroiled in a row after winning the nomination
for Glasgow Govan.
The manner of his victory and the size of his winning margin (one vote after a
count-back) led to demands for an appeal by supporters of Councillor Sarwar.
Labour's national executive committee will decide whether to investigate Mr
Sarwar's complaint when it meets on January 24.
Last night, inquiries to Mr Watson's home were being recorded on an answering
machine.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
