<DOCNO>GH951220-000028</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951220-000028</DOCID>
<DATE>951220</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Upgrading at Nigg yard may bring 800 jobs</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>GRAEME SMITH</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974798877</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AN #8m investment planned at the Nigg yard in Easter Ross could create 800 jobs
by enabling it to penetrate new markets.
The initiative by BARMAC, the Brown &amp; Root and J Ray McDermott joint venture
company, is part of its plan to meet the challenges of the changing offshore
construction market.
It will take the company into the next century as one of Europe's leading
providers of energy-related construction services.
The BARMAC 2000 strategy proposes the development of the Nigg graving dock to
serve the growing need for floating production systems (FPS) and other dry-dock
services for the North-west Continental Shelf.
The company is also planning to seek work decommissioning redundant offshore
structures.
The Highlands and Islands Enterprise network, through Ross and Cromarty
Enterprise (RACE), is to kick start the development and take forward a bid for
more than #3m of vital European cash.
The company employs 1400 personnel at their Nigg and Ardersier yards and they
estimate a further 800 jobs could be created by the opportunities the
developments will bring.
``This potential major infrastructure investment is a clear indication of the
confidence our parent companies have in our ability to win a significant share
of growing new markets, of our employees' ability to adapt in order to
capitalise on these markets, and of our determination to build a sustainable
future for the yards,'' said BARMAC general manager Don Wright.
Ardersier will concentrate on servicing the reduced requirement for traditional
structures and Nigg and its graving dock will form the focus for the new
business segments.
Because FPS - normally ship-shaped structures through which fields produce -
are more economical for developing marginal fields, fields in deep or exposed
waters, and fields with poor access to existing infrastructure, they are
increasingly popular.
A conservative estimate of 26 fields will be developed using FPS in the North
Sea over the next five years.
</TEXT>
