<DATE>951220</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Jessie King was shopped by her lover and went to the scaffold Children of the shadows</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Bryan Douglas</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974798878</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CASES of mass murder by women are, fortunately, rare. The Rosemary West trial
filled pages of most newspapers for weeks and various family survivors continue
to provide gory details for eager readers.
Myra Hindley, who has at last admitted to being corrupt, wicked and evil, has
at least one supporter to remind us of the horrors of the Moors murders, lest
we forget.
Apart from the antics of sportsmen, soap stars, politicans and the royal
family, nothing fascinates the public more than a ``good'' murder story.
But mass murders by women are by no means a confined to modern times. Just over
a century ago, in 1889, Jessie King was tried at the High Court in Edinburgh
for the murder of three babies. There were no complex medical or legal issues
and the evidence was clear.
The case held nothing of the mystery and intrigue of the Madeleine Smith trial
with its ingredients of clandestine romance, arsenic and a Frenchman, which may
explain why it has not achieved the same notoriety.
The trial of Jessie King ended with almost inevitable verdicts of guilty on two
of the charges of murder. The jury took only four minutes to reach a unanimous
verdict and King was sentenced to be hanged by the neck until dead.
The case gives us a glimpse of life in Victorian Edinburgh, particularly among
the lower classes.
The stigma and financial realities of illegitimacy were disastrous to girls who
``got themselves into trouble'' and none of the choices available was likely to
provide a happy solution.
The girl could return in shame to her parents if they would take her or she
could rely on the charity of the parish. Other options were infanticide,
illegal abortion with its great risks to health, trying to find the prospective
father and persuade him into marriage, having the child and trying to earn
money to support both mother and baby, often by  prostitution.
The other choice was to have the baby and arrange an adoption. Without the
advantage of social work departments this was usually a private arrangement and
it was not until 1930 that adoption was put on a formal basis as we now know it.
In a commercial transaction, a deal is easily struck if there is a willing
buyer and a desperate seller. Newspaper advertisements usually provided the
necessary link between the parties. For only a few pounds the girl could solve
her problem with only her conscience to trouble her.
We should bear in mind that antenatal care was probably non-existent in the
vast bulk of unwanted pregnancies and the risk of miscarriage was fairly high.
Many ``quacks'' were willing to provide a wide range of drugs in these
circumstances, with varying degrees of success. Professor Glaister's great
text-book Medical Jurisprudence and Toxicology refers to a considerable traffic
in abortifacient drugs under barely disguised names such as ``Female remedies
for obstruction''.
Others resorted to the unskilled use of instruments with the accompanying risks
of septicaemia.
The trade of ``baby-farming'' seems to have been more popular in England but
the profits to be made attracted the attention of Jessie King and her elderly
lover, Thomas Pearson. It is not clear how many babies died in their care but
the matter came to the attention of police when some boys playing in the
Stockbridge area of Edinburgh found the body of an infant wrapped in an old
coat.
Inquiries led to Jessie and her lover being charged with the murder of three
children. Jessie admitted the murder of two of the infants but Thomas denied
his guilt.
At the trial he was more anxious to speak up and gave evidence as a prosecution
witness, saving his own neck from the rope and ensuring Jessie's conviction.
The evidence was clear and the Solicitor-General withdrew the third charge,
which she had not admitted. He had an easy task to convince the jury that the
only appropriate verdict was guilty of murder.
Following the best traditions of the Scottish Bar, counsel for King made a
creditable effort to suggest reasonable doubt and to persuade the jury to
consider the role the lover had played.
The Lord Justice Clerk painted a far from pretty picture of life behind the
public image of Edinburgh and indicated that the parents of these wretched
children must bear at least some moral reponsibility. But he made it clear that
if the jury accepted the evidence, it was enough to convict.
While awaiting execution in Calton Jail, Jessie made unsuccessful attempts at
beating the hangman by trying to strangle herself. Her mental health was
investigated, but she was pronounced fit to hang and the sentence was carried
out on March 11, 1889.
Just as, earlier in the century, Burke might have walked free if Hare had not
given evidence for the Crown, Jessie King might have escaped if her ``gallant''
lover had not shopped her.
Even today, the Crown Office faces a difficult task in deciding whether to use
guilty people to give evidence against their criminal associates, thus
rendering themselves immune from prosecution. It is expedient, but is it
justice?
Although Jessie King's trial was not complex, the Crown took great care to
obtain the best possible forensic evidence. It would have been easy to jump to
conclusions in a case of suspected child murder and in the case of very poor
people some babies who died of natural causes were disposed of very casually to
avoid expense.
The case was notable for the eminence of the doctors involved - Dr Henry
Littlejohn and his son, Harvey, who succeeded him in the Chair of Forensic
Medicine at Edinburgh University, and Dr Joseph Bell, the ``original'' Sherlock
Holmes.
It was also the first trial attended by William Roughead W.S, the eminent
chronicler of crime, who covered every murder trial, bar one, at the High Court
in Edinburgh for the next 60 years. He missed one because he happened to be on
holiday in Arran at the date of the trial.
Just as in 1889, there are still many unwanted children around the world and a
final thought for 1995 can be found in the Gospel according to St Mark:
``Suffer the little children to come unto me and forbid them not.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951220-000030</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951220-000030</DOCID>
<DATE>951220</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Platform for left-wing clerics</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974798879</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Rev Andrew McLellan's hysterical reply (December 18) to Stewart Lamont's
article on the Asylum Bill is long on rhetoric and short on facts.
The point the article made, quite correctly, was that a large number of people
are abusing the system to gain entry to Britain unlawfully. I think that is a
perfectly legitimate comment to make.
Mr McLellan does not answer the allegation that Glasgow Presbytery was
railroaded into a motion opposing the Asylum Bill by two of his fellow
activists. Is that because it is true?
To long-suffering church members like myself it seems that the convenership of
the Church and Nation Committee has become a platform for clerics with a
leftward leaning who do not necessarily reflect the views of the body of the
Kirk.
Incidentally, since Stewart Lamont's article only appeared on Saturday Mr
McLellan must have friends in The Herald to have his letter published on a
Monday morning.
J M Anderson,
7 Victoria Park Gardens South,
Glasgow.
I WAS disappointed to read in The Herald (December 16 and 18) of two well-known
Church of Scotland ministers exchanging insults in this season of goodwill.
Without going into the rights and wrongs of the matter, what concerned me most
of all was the way in which the World Mission and Unity Committee dealt with
the situation at the meeting of Glasgow Presbytery on December 12.
In fact, their report was dealt with near the end of the meeting. There was
nothing in print before the Presbytery, so that an informed discussion could
take place.
I have reason to believe that the Presbytery Council were unaware that the
Mission and Unity Committee were to raise this important issue. If they had
known, I think it would have been placed nearer the top of the agenda, rather
than nearer the bottom.
The Presbytery's World Mission and Unity Committee ought to be rapped over the
knuckles!
Rev John Jolly,
10 Kensington Court,
20 Kensington Road,
Glasgow.
IN response to the letter by the Rev Maxwell Craig about the proposed
withdrawal of benefits from asylum seekers (December 12), I write to say that I
will not be writing to my MP as he requests. This, I trust, is not because I am
indifferent to the plight of the disadvantaged or to the unfairness of the law.
It is because I have no faith in his proposed method of putting the world to
rights.
The commission that Jesus gave to his church as I understand the New Testament,
was not to pressurise governments, but to preach the gospel.
Rev W J McMillan,
7 Leven Place,
Linburn,
Erskine.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951220-000031</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951220-000031</DOCID>
<DATE>951220</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Protest going beyond small group of zealots</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974798880</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Rev Stewart Lamont's article on asylum (December 16) does justice neither
to his subject nor to himself.
It is regrettable that he should stoop to question the integrity of those of us
within the Scottish churches who have challenged the proposals to withdraw
benefit from certain important categories of asylum seekers.
But it is more serious that he should give such a confused and confusing
account of the issue. Limits of space unfortunately mean it is possible to deal
with only some of the points where Mr Lamont goes wrong!
First, the issue of withdrawal of benefits, the subject of regulations due to
be debated and decided by Parliament this week and to come into force on
January 6, is totally separate, as Mr Lamont clearly fails to appreciate, from
the proposals (equally open to criticism, as it happens) in the Bill currently
before Parliament.
Secondly, this is not a protest orchestrated by a small group of zealots, as Mr
Lamont implies. The proposals have been criticised by a wide range of
charitable organisations and public bodies, including the official
representatives of all the main British churches.
Thirdly, Mr Lamont's suggestion that Britain's system is somehow being
exploited by a host of immigrant opportunists is unworthy. There is already
widespread concern at the low rate of Home Office acceptance of applications
for asylum. The withdrawal of benefits will cause much further suffering among
many innocent and vulnerable people.
The proposals will in effect remove the right of appeal against the refusal of
asylum and are arguably in breach of the UK's obligations under the 1951 UN
Convention on the Status of Refugees. It is entirely appropriate that those
concerned about justice and hospitality should speak out against them - and
particularly at this time of year.
Rev Norman Shanks,
Leader of the Iona Community,
Pearce Institute, 840 Govan Road,
Glasgow.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951220-000032</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951220-000032</DOCID>
<DATE>951220</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Glasgow- Berlin analogy</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974798881</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Glasgow-Berlin analogy
HOW can Michael Fry (December 13) still be sniggering at communists in 1995?
OK, so their big experiment behind the Iron Curtain didn't work, but you don't
have to look very far to see signs that our own, under the Iron Lady, hasn't
exactly been a runaway success. Perhaps we'll soon turn our back on failure too.
His analogy between Glasgow and Berlin could be stretched a little further.
Glasgow's so-called socialist administration seems pledged, amid the
triumphalism of its public-relations coups, to reproduce here the ``desperate
dilapidation and bold brutalism'' of post-war East Berlin, by failing to
address housing problems, continuing to demolish fine old buildings, and
bulldozing motorways into the heart of the city: what Mr Fry might call
``socialist planning'' run amok.
We would do well to turn our back on that failure too, and as Deyan Sudjic,
Glasgow's new ``1999'' director, says, treat our city with respect (December
12). and that includes Mr Pat Lally refraining from cheap remarks about Glasgow
becoming ``the Vienna of the north''.
Berlin, by the way, has a healthy tradition of voting communist: it elected a
communist mayor the same year that Hitler came to power. Why don't we follow
its example of bucking the national trend, by throwing out not only the failed
Tories at Westminster, but also tired old Labour in Glasgow?
Ian Cowan,
4 Striven Gardens,
Glasgow.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951220-000033</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951220-000033</DOCID>
<DATE>951220</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Bogus doctor cleared</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974798882</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MADRID: A bogus gynaecologist who treated more than 11,000 women was cleared by
a court in northern Spain yesterday of fraud, falsifying documents, and
illegally using a professional title.
The court at San Sebastian gave a three-year suspended sentence to imposter
Jose Luis Fernandez, 44, saying his practical knowledge and dedication made up
for his lack of formal training. He had practised for 14 years, four of them at
a leading hospital in Barcelona, before being exposed.
Crowd gassed
LAGOS: Nigerian police fired teargas yesterday to disperse a crowd that
gathered for a rally in the commercial capital Lagos to demand an immediate
return to democracy, witnesses said. In London, an action group of the
Commonwealth, which expelled Nigeria following the execution of nine human
rights activists, said fresh punitive steps might be needed.
Trial put off
TEL AVIV: An Israeli court put off the trial of Yitzhak Rabin's self-confessed
assassin, 25-year-old Yigal Amir, 25, until January 23 so that his lawyers
would have time to study the evidence.
Briton falls
TOKYO: A 37-year-old British businessman visiting Japan fell to his death from
a fourth-floor office window, police said. Geoffrey Till, a car-parts company
executive of Witney, Oxfordshire, was found on Monday outside the offices of a
Japanese firm where he was to have had a meeting. Police suspected suicide.
Patten backed
HONG KONG: Britain has dismissed a Chinese demand to exclude Hong Kong Governor
Chris Patten from the ceremonial handover of Hong Kong in 1997. Beijing has
demonstrated its dislike of the governor with a series of attacks, but Hugh
Davies, head of the British team responsible for the handover, said: ``Clearly
the governor is a major participant.''
q.A South Korean woman welcomed as Hong Kong's 10 millionth visitor for this
year won a ride in a Rolls-Royce, a night in a deluxe hotel suite, #650 in
travel cheques, and two air tickets to come back again.
Celluloid sales
NEW YORK: The green army uniform worn by Tom Hanks in the film Forrest Gump
sold for #11,215 at a sale in New York of film and television memorabilia.
Other big sellers were Greta Garbo's love letters to actor Gilbert Roland,
which went for more than #11,000, and a pair of boxing shorts worn by Sylvester
Stallone in the 1976 film Rocky, which fetched more than #7100, doubling
estimates.
Leader `critical'
ATHENS: Greek Prime Minister Andreas Papandreou, in hospital for a month, was
fighting off a new secondary infection and his condition had worsened. Hospital
sources were reported as saying his condition was critical.
All bets off
PARIS: A strike at the French equivalent of the Tote entered its sixth day
yesterday, depriving thousands of would-be punters of a flutter. A spokesman
for the state-run Pari Mutuel Urbain (PMU) said the strike, over salaries and
jobs, had affected the system's computer network.
Dini set to quit
ROME: An aide said Prime Minister Lamberto Dini would offer his resignation on
December 30, opening the way to a parliamentary debate in the New Year on
Italy's political future. Dini has led a technocrat government since the
collapse of media magnate     Silvio Berlusconi's coalition government last
January.
Belgians strike
BRUSSELS: Rail and air strikes plunged Belgian transport into chaos yesterday
Most of national airline Sabena's 280 flights were cancelled and at least half
the country had no trains. Eurostar trains to Paris and London were also
affected.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951220-000034</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951220-000034</DOCID>
<DATE>951220</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Phlegmatic view of BSE danger</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974798883</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
PROFESSOR J Hume Adams finds no cause for concern about possible transmission
of BSE to humans as CJD because he understands that there are now strict
controls in abattoirs dealing with the use of brain, spinal cord, and eye
tissues for beefburgers, etc (December 14).
The Government has admitted that recent spot checks in abattoirs have shown
that almost half of them were not complying with correct procedures, and that
in 17 cases breaches of regulations have allowed machanically recovered spinal
cord tissue to get into meat products for human consumption.
Professor Adams also assures us that ``a considerable amount'' of infectious
brain tissue is needed even to transmit BSE to another cow by ingestion - a
degree of imprecision that seems remarkable from a scientist.
The curiously phlegmatic attitude adopted by the authorities to this potential
danger contrasts markedly with the plethora of thou-shalt-nots we got at the
start of the Aids score.
Robin Dow,
9 Sycamore Close,
Audlem, Cheshire.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951220-000035</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951220-000035</DOCID>
<DATE>951220</DATE>
<HEADLINE>CIA chief warns of terror surge</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974798884</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Washington, Tuesday
CIA chief John Deutch today predicted a worldwide surge in terrorism in the
next decade and said he was shifting US spy resources to help meet the threat.
``I regret that I have come to the conclusion there is going to be tremendous
growth in terrorism over the next decade or so, not only directed towards
Americans but throughout the world,'' he told the House of Representatives
Intelligence Committee.
Deutch said the forecast rise in terrorism would have ``immense impact on how
we conduct our foreign policy, immense impact on how American businesses
operate abroad''.
Replying to a question about the threat, the head of the Central Intelligence
Agency did not discuss why he expected a surge nor pinpoint the possible
perpetrators.
However in his opening statement he said: ``It is my judgment that ideologies
and regimes inimical to democracy will continue to exist. Examples today are
Iran, Iraq, and North Korea.''
He also cited unspecified transnational groups involved in drug running,
organised crime, and terrorism.
Deutch said the CIA and its sister US intelligence agencies were shifting
resources to cope with the threat.
He called for a halt in criticism of the CIA's covert operations arm, derided
in recent years for bungled operations, from the discovery of a Moscow mole in
its midst to bribing bureaucrats for trade secrets in Paris.-Reuter.
</TEXT>
