<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951220-000036</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951220-000036</DOCID>
<DATE>951220</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Crippling cost of having your day in court</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Margaret Vaughan</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974798885</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MONEY is the universal solvent; everything can be turned into money that is
either a gain or a loss, remarked Lord Neaves in 1874.
For David Ashby it looks like being a vary large loss indeed. As the Tory MP
wept into his hands in the High Court yesterday, he had to start coming to
terms with two things. First, after a lurid 20-day courtroom battle which has
turned him from an undistinguished backbencher to a reluctant household name,
he had lost his libel action against the Sunday Times. The court had decided
that the ``family from Hell'' was an unkind but apparently not inaccurate
sobriquet. So no ``universal solvent'' for David Ashby. But there was worse to
come.
Ashby, a Lloyd's ``name'' who has admitted he has financial problems, now faces
a costs bill (his own, plus that of the newspaper) unofficially estimated at
#500,000.
Some astronomically large payouts in the English courts in recent years have
encouraged those who believe their reputations to have been impuned to seek
redress through a libel case. In 1989 a jury awarded former Tory party deputy
chairman Lord Aldington #1.5m over allegations by Count Nicolai Tolstoy, the
largest libel award ever.
Better known perhaps is the case brought by another former holder of that post,
Lord Archer, who won #500,000 over allegations in the Daily Star, then gave the
lot to charity. But the price of failure, and even the price of success, can be
enormous. Not only has the individual had to tolerate the wide circulation of
minute details of their private lives, but they are likely to be landed with a
crippling bill for the legal costs. Bill Roache, Coronation Street's Ken
Barlow, won #50,000 damages because the Sun claimed he was boring in real life
as well as in his role, but was then confronted with a legal bill for #120,000
because he failed to win costs.
The operation of the law on defamation is another instance in which it is hard
for the Scots not to sound smug, though slighted individuals may not agree.
While the English system is sympathetic to the fragile ego, Scots law takes a
more robust view of defamation. Martin Smith, one of the few lawyers in
Scotland with extensive experience in libel cases says: ``In Scotland you get
next to nothing for having your reputation damaged. This is because you have to
prove loss, and that isn't easy. Jeffrey Archer would have got very little up
here.''
Also, while all cases in England have to go through the High Court, in Scotland
most go through the Sheriff Court. For the Scots client, this has the advantage
of making the costs considerably less but the likely payout is also likely to
be less. In Scotland, only about one defamation case a year is heard in the
Court of Session (the Scottish equivalent of the High Court).
The second big difference is that while the English system often uses juries to
decide both the merits of the case and the level of damages, in Scotland the
use of a jury for a libel hearing, even in Court of Session cases, is
relatively rare. Juries are likely to award considerably higher damages.
In Scotland the record for libel damages is #50,000. It is held by Lillian
Winter, who had sued News Scotland Ltd for an article in the Sun alleging that
she had been caught having sex with an inmate at Glenochil prison, where she
was employed as a prison officer. Significantly, this case was heard by a jury.
Before the Winter case, the highest personal payout for defamation had been
#7500 to seamen's union leader Sam McCluskie for allegations made in a series
of letters by one of his members.
The combination of low damages awards and facing the legal costs, for which
there is no legal aid, mean that only about 5% of Scots defamation cases ever
make it to court.
Smith says a typical cost of taking a case to court is #5000 but if you lose
you can get landed with the defender's costs, so you can double that.
A libel action has been described as a toy that allows the rich to sue the rich
with the proceeds being trousered by the legal profession. Even in Scotland,
that's not too wide of the mark.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951220-000037</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951220-000037</DOCID>
<DATE>951220</DATE>
<HEADLINE>No Headline Present</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Ian Bell</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974798886</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IT IS a rare occasion when this column gets itself accused of culture. We are
neither noticeably Doric nor Ionic, after all, more a sort of long streak
propping up the far side of the page with a pediment that leaves something to
be desired. But if the Scottish Arts Council is to be believed we are, in our
own modest way, one small pillar in the mighty edifice that is Scotland's
cultural industry.
According to a report issued by the council earlier this week, the country is
pediculous with folk earning their bread from the arts and culture. There are
more of us dancing, singing, painting, acting, scribbling, and generally
creating than there are primary teachers, shipbuilders, or whisky workers.
Indeed, in some sectors cultural activity is more intense in Scotland than it
is in any part of Britain outside London. And two cheers for that.
Purists among you might wonder, certainly after wading through this week's
assault on the frontiers of syntax, what journalists are doing among the
cultural and cultured. The problem of definition aside - what else would you
call us that wasn't merely obscene? - it might seem odd that those paid to pick
over the culture are themselves described as cultural producers.
But there it is: the SAC says so and the SAC, we must presume, knows whereof it
speaks.
That aside, however, its report seems to support the claim, long advertised but
never proven, that Scotland has enjoyed something of a cultural renaissance in
recent decades. Long ago MacDiarmid argued that cultural nationalism might be
the prerequisite for political nationalism, rather than vice versa, and here we
are with what appears to be a boom in (broadly speaking) the arts.
Does this mean that political self-determination will inevitably follow? The
Irish experience seems to suggest as much, though as Ireland has shown,
cultural resurgences seem to lose much of their puff once independence has been
achieved. Nevertheless, it is tempting to believe that self-confidence in the
arts and media, never mind employment, will one day be rewarded with a free
state to accompany its free spirit.
FOR that reason, perhaps, the SAC's findings for those sectors in which
Scotland does not outperform the rest of the UK are doubly interesting. Authors
and artists (even journalists) may flourish: what are we to make of the
broadcasters? According to the SAC, culling its information from the 1991
Census, Scotland's share of employment in the radio, television, and theatre
sector amounts to only 5% of the UK total. True, the figures for the film and
book trades amount to only 4% and 2% respectively, but these industries are not
governed by legislation to the same extent as broadcasting.
Equally, the BBC has a ``federated'' structure designed explicitly, so we are
told, to recognise Scotland's distinctiveness as a ``national region'', while
the regional structure of ITV (Channel Four always excepted) is meant to ensure
that the Scottish stations get their share of the revenue cake, if not the work.
Yet plainly, in terms of employment and production, the gravitational pull of
London remains stronger than any politician's good intentions. At the very
least our share of the jobs should match our share of the population, but it
does not. In film, meanwhile, Scotland's manifold attractions as a location
have done little to revive the local industry.
The parallels are tempting. BBC federalism and ITV's periodic efforts at
devolution have yet to produce the sort of results generally claimed for their
political equivalents. As other cultural activities show, Scotland has the
human resources but, in broadcasting, few of the rewards.
It is the culture's equivalent to North Sea oil, an export trade in ideas,
people, and skills.
Other areas of the UK could make the same claims, of course, but that is hardly
the point. The SAC's report indicates unusual signs of cultural activity in
Scotland at a time when, politically, the pot is beginning to bubble again. Yet
in broadcasting, where the idea of Britain remains strong (where else do you
hear of the ``national'', meaning British, news?), even federal structures have
failed to ameliorate the problem.
There may just be a lesson in this. After all, the substance at issue is the
same whether the debate is about politics or culture: power is the key. You can
have it granted by London, or even by a distant ``network centre'', or you can
achieve it for yourself. And sometimes the only way to do that is by toppling a
few old, familiar pillars.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951220-000038</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951220-000038</DOCID>
<DATE>951220</DATE>
<HEADLINE>In the doghouse over puppy love</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CHRIS HOLME</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>Devils Advocate</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974798887</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AND they called it puppy love. A youth appeared recently at a sheriff court
(let's just say somewhere in central Scotland) on the bizarre charge of having
sex with a neighbour's dog, and was ordered to be detained.
Apparently, before the hearing his mother arrived at court and spotted her
offspring across the room. She enquired as to why he was there and expressed
outrage when she learned the nature of the charge. ``The neighbour's dog!'' she
exclaimed. ``That's ridiculous. We've got a dug of oor ain.'' The unfortunate
youth then lodged a bail appeal, later withdrawn with the explanation that he
felt safer if he wasn't allowed to return home because his father was a boxer.
Life's a bitch
AT the risk of causing more offence to true dog lovers and descending further
into the depths of depravity, we could also record the activities of Monty,
erstwhile fox terrier owned by my distinguished colleague Robbie Dinwoodie, The
Herald's first Devil's Advocate.
Monty's concupiscent attentions extended beyond canine targets to another
family pet, the neutered cat, sometimes al fresco and often in flagrante in
front of the neighbours or dinner party guests.
Even intelligent humans, so-called sentient beings from a higher evolutionary
order, can take coupling activities beyond the pale. Students of one Scottish
academic, noted for his freelance frolics with all and sundry, once defined the
limits he would go to in search of sexual gratification. ``Anything with a
pulse,'' they said.
Spot the
difference
AN Asian shopkeeper was giving evidence at the High Court in Edinburgh after an
incident at his premises involving a number of young men. The men in the dock
were white and the shopkeeper was asked to look round the court to see whether
he could recognise anyone who had entered his shop at the relevant time.
He was having obvious difficulty in picking anyone out and explained: ``It is
like you get in China. All the people look the same.''
Barking
IN another case in the same court, a witness conceded that his regular drug
habit had perhaps caused a slowing down of his thought processes. ``Do you
remember August 5,'' he was asked. ``I don't remember August,'' he responded.
Dog's dinner
ONE thing's for sure if the SNP ever delivers its independent Scotland:
there'll be no shortage of work for lawyers. The proposed Bill of Rights alone
has enough guarantees to sustain a million working lunches and countless
careers: free health care, housing, benefits, trade unions, and fair and decent
renumeration for work and conditions that respect the dignity of the person.
There's also a tilt to yoof power: the voting age shifts down to 16 and even
leisure is liberated. The Bill would guarantee access to go roamin' in the
gloamin' anywhere in Scotland and to swear back at any obstructive landowner in
Gaelic, broad Scots or Urdu.
Even the miserable likes of the Diary get protection with freedom of the press,
which presumably means that in the world of news hounds, dog can still eat dog.
Hair of the......
AS this is the last Devil's Advocate before the festive season, we would like
to wish all our contributors and readers a very Merry Christmas, subject to the
usual rubric of contentment before capacity when addressing the sherry or
whisky bottle. That way you should avoid feeling rough, rough the next day. The
Diary's New Year resolution will be to let sleeping four-legged friends lie. No
more shaggy dog stories in 1996. Promise.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951220-000039</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951220-000039</DOCID>
<DATE>951220</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Dounreay verdict</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974798888</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE recent Caithness referendum and Scottish opinion poll have decisively shown
local and national opposition to nuclear reprocessing at Dounreay.
Mr John Baxter, director of Dounreay, arrogantly sought to dismiss such views
as being rushed, and ``not the way to judge whether the community understands
what we do and is content with it''.
Yet the Dounreay management were prepared to rush into a contract for the
reprocessing with no consultation whatever, and furthermore withheld (again)
information about contamination and problems at the plant.
FoE Scotland has been calling for the same extensive consultation process to be
conducted in Scotland as in the US.
We are confident that such consultation would show, as the referendum and poll
have done, how out of touch with Scottish opinion Mr Baxter is. It is time for
the people of Scotland to be listened to.
Kevin Dunion,
Director,
Friends of the Earth Scotland,
72 Newhaven Road,
Edinburgh.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951220-000040</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951220-000040</DOCID>
<DATE>951220</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Dupplin Cross</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974798889</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
YOUR report on the public inquiry over the fate of the Dupplin Cross near
Forteviot amazes me (December 13).
In the first place the matter does not appear to have been aired nationally on
any previous occasion. That having been said, your report states, ``Villagers
and experts are agreed that the cross should be removed.......'' This beggars
understanding.
Putting aside the avarice of the National Museum in Edinburgh, is there no
person or organisation left in our beleaguered country capable of fostering the
concept that our ancient monuments in their original settings inspire informed
visitors, who tend to return, to explore Scotland beyond the dubious delights
of Edinburgh, Scott Country, Alloway, and the Whisky Trail?
Move the Dupplin Cross? Whatever for? Put a weatherproof glazed cage round and
over it as was done with Sueno's Stone in Forres.
Such a scheme would cost a great deal less than #56,000 and a plastic replica,
and might even attract a portion of the money wasted on the National Lottery.
Tam Glen,
Glencurr, Mid Curr,
Dulnain Bridge,
Inverness-shire.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951220-000041</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951220-000041</DOCID>
<DATE>951220</DATE>
<HEADLINE>For whom the tills tell. Consumers hold key to economy</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Leader</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974798890</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Chancellor of the Exchequer may enjoy the way in which the OECD has
endorsed the direction of his projections for the UK economy in the next two
years, but the Paris-based organisation is somewhat less optimistic as to the
precise figures. It suggests somewhat less growth and somewhat more inflation,
but it does notice how the British economy has become less prone to inflation
these past few years - and more than the Chancellor will be gratified by that
observation. Both sets of forecasts do note how the build-up of stocks could
affect eventual outcomes. For both sets, therefore, the behaviour of consumers
is vital.
Economies aren't by nature dynamic and all forecasts have to be hedged. The
Chancellor's are widely recognised as being optimistic - they reflect his
personality as well as the data - but the OECD's were arrived at before the
latest interest-rate reduction. Modest though that was, it does reinforce Mr
Clarke's case, which will be further strengthened if, as is likely, more
reductions follow in the spring. Such changes could be enough to bridge most of
the gap between the two lots of figures, though both are really dependent on
movements in the international economy. Britain's dependence on exports makes
what happens in the United States and Germany, two very important customers,
extremely significant for us, though there are few ways in which any British
chancellor can directly influence American or German decisions.
Long before the next two years have passed local events will endorse one or
other of these projections. An early example would be the Christmas retail
figures and the extent to which their spending is financed by credit. These
will be known by January, but people who can ``feel'' economic trends will have
formed an opinion before Ne'erday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951220-000042</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951220-000042</DOCID>
<DATE>951220</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Here's to our own plums and turkeys next year</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Alex Salmond</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974798891</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
``Eight-Hundred Films Reviewed and Rated: Barry Norman's Plums and Turkeys''
announces the cover of the festive Radio Times.
Yet within the amazing variety of films listed there are only three that could
even vaguely be described as Scottish. One is the international movie
Highlander with Sean Connery, and two are wonderful comedies with Scottish
subjects - Whisky Galore &amp; The Maggie - but comedies whose genesis is
definitely from south of the Border.
Next year is the year of the centenary of cinema, and follows probably the best
yet for Scottish film with two international block busters - Rob Roy and
Braveheart - an Oscar (for Peter Capaldi's Franz Kafka, which was produced in
the BBC-supported Tartan Shorts series) and a highly successful low-budget
movie, Shallow Grave. But if our industry is only capable of providing less
than half of one per cent of movies that television chooses to show at the most
intensively viewed part of the year, then we are still going nowhere.
There is probably more optimism in the Scottish film community now than there
has been for a generation. Even Michael Forsyth's experience of being booed in
and booed out of the Braveheart premiers in his own constituency has not turned
the Secretary of State away from ordering a major study into Scottish film to
be published next year. But while Michael Forsyth is good at listening - it
seems to have been his big idea of 1995 - like the rest of the Tories he has
been pretty poor about doing anything with what he hears.
A case in point is a decision waiting on his desk regarding the future of the
Scottish film institutions. In the first half of this year the Scottish Office
reviewed the role of the Scottish Film Council and it was anticipated that the
results of this review would be published this autumn.
Nothing has happened, although the report is believed to have been in draft
form as early as August.
Among the speculation is that the review confirms the view of many in Scotland
that what we need is a new agency, provisionally entitled Scottish Screen.
Scottish Screen would draw together the diverse bodies that now exist - the
film council, the Production Fund, the Training Trust, and Scottish Screen
Locations - into a single ``super authority'' to develop policy and implement
it.
So far so good. Scotland does not need a single body, but that body needs power
and resources. It cannot be just a makeover of the Scottish Film Council, which
is on a promising new path but which has a remit that is largely cultural and
educational.
Scottish Screen needs to be able to tackle some of the structural problems that
exist - and these are primarily commercial issues. A weak physical
infrastructure (specifically the lack of a full sound stage), lack of expertise
in marketing and distribution, and a stronger ability to attract investment are
some of the areas that need urgent action. And despite the excellent work of
the Scottish Film Production Fund and the Glasgow Development Agency (which has
lead public policy in the absence of interest from Scottish Enterprise at a
national level) there needs to be more money made available for project
development.
Most of all Scotland needs to establish a ``film-friendly'' environment, and
this needs management and promotion by one agency. The context should be set by
politicians - particularly the tax context, where Scotland is crying out for an
initiative like the Irish ``Section 35'' which allows tax write-offs for
investment. The practical steps that come after have to be taken by film
professionals.
The need for that film-friendly environment can be seen clearly in the
Braveheart experience. The Section 35 money was only the final incentive that
tipped the balance. Ireland's inspired film minister, Michael D Higgins, was
able to offer Mel Gibson co-operation at every level of Irish life - from the
use of the Army for battle scenes (suitably scaled up by the wonders of
computer graphics) down to access to the Irish countryside. Despite the hard
work and enthusiasm of Scotland's film administrators, our country could not
match that commitment.
A real Scottish Screen would be a body established from the media industries,
involving professionals from television and film. There is no need for it to be
yet another quango - it can be created by federating existing organisations on
an equal basis and supplementing them with other small commercially orientated
bodies, keenly targeted towards specific developmental tasks. It would be
motivated by the vision of a sustainable, competitive Scottish film industry
and sustained by the tax incentives that will encourage production.
Such an initiative will need money, political will, and freedom from
interference from south of the Border, where the Department of National
Heritage jealously guards the right and privileges of the studio-based London
film industry.
Next year could be the year of the real revival - the long-term revival - of
the Scottish film industry. All it will take is the courage and vision to make
it happen.
Then we can get the world watching our plums and turkeys at Christmas, and reap
the benefit of them every day of the year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951220-000043</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951220-000043</DOCID>
<DATE>951220</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Galileo's orbits</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974798892</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A report from your Los Angeles correspondent concerning the space probe Galileo
stated that the giant planet Jupiter is 318 times larger than Earth (December
11).
Jupiter's volume is more than 1300 times that of our world which may explain
why Galileo's proposed 11 orbits of the planet will take all of two years.
Norman McDonald,
62 Riverside Road,
Waterfoot, Glasgow.
</TEXT>
