<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951220-000044</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951220-000044</DOCID>
<DATE>951220</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Hooked on hock and pork haggis</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Michael Fry</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974798893</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THIS is being written the morning after The Herald's editorial Christmas party,
I am afraid. So I do not feel quite up to contemplating, as is my wont, one of
the great issues of our time. Instead, let me give you a question for your
games of Trivial Pursuit over the festive weekend: who, beside the Scots, are
the only haggis-eating people on earth?
I shall supply the answer straightaway, since I would guess that not one in a
million could have the remotest inkling of it. The answer is the people of the
Rhineland Palatinate, one of the smallest and surely the sleepiest of the
German Lnder.
In its sleepiness it is, and this is why I like it, decidedly unGerman. I have
got to know it quite well because a friend of mine lives there with his family,
and I visited them again a couple of weeks ago. When I first met him, sharing
digs at Hamburg University, Wolfgang was a workaholic Prussian, though with a
substratum of humanity which might be brought out if only he could be persuaded
to get drunk. He was also - how shall we put this? - just a wee bit right wing.
His parents had been expelled from Silesia by the Poles at the end of the
Second World War, and neither they nor he had ever forgiven it. At least it
provided the stuff of discussion far into the night.
He grew up into a nuclear physicist, but the problem for nuclear physicists is
that after the age of 40 they become a trifle superannuated: the theoretical
flair is gone, the mathematical imagination fades, all the really creative work
is being done by younger brains. Wolfgang has become not only superannuated but
also, to coin a phrase, palatinated.
One reason why the Palatinate is so sleepy is that on a good many days a good
many of its citizens are coping with a hangover. It is wine-growing country, a
fact of which they take full advantage. As soon as I arrived, late on a Friday
night after a hellish journey from snowbound Berlin, bottles of rather peculiar
red champagne were opened: one for me, one for Wolfgang.
At breakfast we refreshed ourselves with copious draughts of what used to be
Oscar Wilde's favourite tipple, hock-and-seltzer, now ultra-trendy in this
country under the name of Spritzer and known to the Germans as Scholle. The
copious draughts continued through the morning, and by lunchtime I was feeling
a little woozy. At this point Wolfgang insisted on our jumping into his car.
Freezing fog lay thick over the Rhine Valley but he drives, as all Germans do,
like a thing possessed. Within 10 minutes we were, doubtless thanks to my
prayers, at his favourite vintner's.
The scene there was much like a Glasgow pub on a Friday night.
A crowd of locals, bright-eyed and red-cheeked in the fug, had obviously been
at it for some time. Vintners provide a room for the tasting of their product,
and they are generous. At least two dozen bottles were set out, with more
available when any was empty. You could drink as much as you liked for free.
Obviously there was an expectation that a case of something would be bought
before leaving, but no pressure on that point. As I said, it is all decidedly
unGerman.
Why are the people of the Palatinate like this? Probably because they live on a
frontier, or on three to be precise. Down the centuries they have had armies
trampling all over them, so have decided there are better things to do than
worry about the great issues of the time. The culture is resolutely
proletarian. As far as I can discover this land, almost uniquely, contains no
opera house; it prefers karaoke and country and western. The local daily, Die
Rheinpfalz, makes the Aberdeen Press and Journal look cosmopolitan. Each Monday
it carries eight pages of reports on junior football. And everyone is
fanatically devoted to Kaiserslautern, the Raith Rovers of Germany.
If all this has a familiar ring, it may be worth pointing out that the
Palatinate is traditionally Calvinist too. In fact the Reformation can be said
to have started here, in the town of Worms, where Martin Luther was arraigned
before the Imperial Diet and said: ``Here I stand. I can do no other.''
In principle it was no doubt a good thing to possess the true religion, but in
practice it had, in the centre of Europe, certain disadvantages, by attracting
the attention of the trampling armies. The trouble started in 1620 when the
Elector Palatine, Frederick V, tried to claim the Crown of Bohemia and set off
the Thirty Years' War. In his own country, two centuries of devastation
followed.
It is interesting that Frederick was married to a Scots lassie, Elizabeth,
daughter of James VI. Hence, perhaps, the haggis. As the evening of our boozy
Saturday drew on, I said to Wolfgang that I would like to taste some
specialities of the region. With his wife at the wheel this time, we drove to a
restaurant in the charming village of Freinsheim.
The starter on the set menu was Schmalz, bread and dripping, and very toothsome
too: did I not say that the culture was resolutely proletarian? A salad of
lamb's lettuce followed, a bit twee by British standards but as common as
cabbage in the Palatinate. Then came its culinary pride and joy, Saumagen. This
translates as sow's stomach. It is indeed a pork haggis, but on just the same
formula as any made from a sheep: the innards are chopped up and stuffed inside
the bag to be cooked. The result is tastier than our version, and amply
testifies to the sterling qualities of the people who invented it.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951220-000045</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951220-000045</DOCID>
<DATE>951220</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Workers' dream, employers' nightmare</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Alan Masson</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>Business Matters</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974798894</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MANY part-time workers can now no longer be treated as conveniently expendable
employees, open to instant dismissal without compensation when business is
having a hard time. This year, the UK Government has given them the protection
to which they are entitled by European Community Law.
The importance of part-time employment on Britain's commerce and industry has
grown significantly over the past decade and the supposedly caring 90s have
seen a steady drift away from full-time employment, with more and more jobs
being filled by part-time workers.
To some extent that may be because, until relatively recently, part-time
employees working more than eight but less than 16 hours per week were required
to work for five years before qualifying for the protection afforded after two
years' service to their full-time colleagues.
Those working less than eight hours per week never could enjoy that protection,
which may have made them attractive to an employer seeking to retain
flexibility without the risk of incurring liabilities when a downturn in trade
might force redundancies.
However, a sea change in the fortunes of part-time workers has occurred in the
past 18 months, following a decision of the House of Lords in March last year.
They held that the provisions of the Employment Protection Consolidation Act
1978 governing eligibility for redundancy payments were incompatible with the
provisions of Article 119 of the Treaty of Rome and European Community Equality
Law.
They also found that those provisions of the Act subjecting employees with less
than 16 hours service per week to different conditions for compensation for
unfair dismissal were also incompatible with EU equality law.
The Government subsequently took steps to rectify the position by issuing the
Employment Protection (Part-time Employees) Regulations 1995, effective from
February 6 this year. They repeated various provisions of the 1978 Act so that
part-time service, regardless of the number of hours worked per week, now
counts in computing an employee's continuous employment, both for the purposes
of unfair dismissal protection and in establishing the right to a redundancy
payment.
This is a somewhat radical change in the law relating to part-time workers and
it is clear that not all employers have yet got the message. The lack of
protection, which existed until the introduction of the new regulations, had
engendered a casual approach to the treatment of such employees and there was,
to some extent, a general feeling that when times were hard they were
expendable.
Equally, in a disciplinary situation, whereas a full-time worker, with more
than two years service would have to be treated fairly and reasonably, the
employer could, generally speaking, still afford to be somewhat cavalier in
regard to part-time personnel, who either had not yet qualified for protection
or never could.
All that has changed. Today, all employees have the same rights, whether they
work one or 50 hours a week. That is something which employers must now grasp.
The extension of the rights of part-time workers does not stop there. Those
same qualifying thresholds used also to apply to maternity rights, but changes
introduced by the Trade Union Reform and Employment Rights Act 1993 conferred
significant rights on all women expecting a baby on or after October 16, 1994.
Since that date, all women, no matter whether they are full-time or part-time
employees, what hours they work each week, or how long they have been employed,
have the right to 14 weeks' maternity leave. Under the 1995 regulations, the
qualifying limits for extended maternity leave have also been harmonised and,
accordingly, all women employees with more than two years service are entitled
to extended maternity absence, delaying their return to work for up to 29 weeks
from the beginning of the week in which their baby is born.
Another right enjoyed by part-time workers is the right to protection from
dismissal on the grounds of pregnancy, for which all women employees now
qualify regardless of their hours of work or length of employment. It is also
automatically unfair to dismiss any employee, regardless of hours worked,
length of service or age, if the reason, or principal reason, for dismissal is
that he or she has sought to rely on certain of their statutory rights.
There have also been changes to the rules on Health and Safety, which apply
equally to part-time employees, and the 1995 Finance Act introduced changes to
make part-time employees equally eligible to participate in profit-related pay
and profit-sharing schemes, employee share-ownership trusts, share option
schemes, and savings-related share-option schemes.
To add to the employer's nightmare, the two-year qualifying threshold itself
has come under attack of late with a recent decision of the English Court of
Appeal questioning its justification.
That case is currently on appeal to the House of Lords but it leaves the law in
a somewhat confused state. If it is decided that the unfair dismissal
compensation is to be deemed ``pay'' under Article 119 of the Treaty of Rome,
employees with less than two years service would probably have the right to
make unfair dismissal claims. That right may already be said to extend to some
employees in the public sector, due to the ``direct effect'' of the EU Equal
Treatment Directive.
Taken together, this all adds up to the fact that, no matter how long an
employee has been employed or how many hours each week he or she works, any
decisions taken affecting them must be arrived at very carefully against a
background of up-to-date advice. Employment law, particularly that relating to
part-time workers, is in a fluid state and represents a real danger to any
employer who chooses to ignore these new-found rights.
n-Alan Masson is an associate with Dorman Jeffrey &amp; Co.
</TEXT>
