<HEADLINE>Listeria risk</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974798895</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ACCORDING to your recent reports the misinformed public are unwilling to
consume good Scotch beef due to an unjustifiable fear of BSE and yet they are
willing to eat cheese made from unpasteurised (raw) milk which contains
listeria monocytogenes.
Once I had to sign a death certificate for a new-born baby dead of listeria
monocytogenes meningitis, passed on from the mother who had almost certainly
consumed listeria.
As some will know, pregnant women are routinely instructed to avoid certain
cheeses until after delivery because of this risk.
Large outbreaks of salmonellosis due to unpasteurised milk encouraged the
decision to make it illegal to sell unpasteurised milk in Scotland
Now, because of the greater risk of infection, it is time to make it illegal to
sell cheese made from such milk.
For these reasons there are those who will sympathise with Clydesdale District
Council and it is unhelpful for Arthur Bell to pursue them for doing their duty.
But again, maybe he is just another misinformed member of the public.
Dr Donald J C Cameron,
7 Duncan Avenue,
Fochabers.
</TEXT>
