<HEADLINE>Doing MP's job</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974798896</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
EPLORE your cheap attack on Bob Maclennan (December 15). In defending Dounreay
he has been doing what every MP should do. That is defend, when necessary and
as far as possible, the major employers of his constituents.
You imply that it is inappropriate to reprocess American nuclear ``muck'' at
Dounreay. All the nuclear ``muck'' from Scotland's hospitals and nuclear power
stations is processed in England. Would it not follow that this is
inappropriate?
You mention the leadership of a farmer in this campaign to undermine one of
Caithness's major employers. Would it not be more appropriate for a Caithness
farmer to direct his efforts to assisting Bob Maclennan in defending Caithness
beef farmers from fellow scaremongers?
Terry Jones,
3 Bridge of Westfield,
Thurso.
THE sneers in your editorial on December 15 were unworthy both of your
newspaper and of the target, Robert Maclennan, MP for Caithness and Sutherland.
He is respected across the party political spectrum as a very able and
thoughtful individual.
It is only the local recognition of his basic integrity and of his hard work on
behalf of his constituents that has ensured his re-election as MP for Caithness
and Sutherland in every General Election since 1966, regardless of national
party trends or negative press comment.
Rev Iain Murdoch,
22 Coronation Street,
Wishaw.
</TEXT>
