<DATE>951220</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Hospital failures. Regime `demeans patients'</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Leader</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974798897</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CONDITIONS at the Royal Edinburgh Psychiatric Hospital are clearly
unacceptable. For the Scottish Health Advisory Service to have identified 50
points of criticism is dispiriting for the doctors, nurses, and ancillary staff
who quite obviously struggle in a difficult situation. Worse, it implies a
demeaning regime for patients who are among the most vulnerable people cared
for by the National Health Service. The main points of criticism assembled by
the SHAS indicate clearly enough the most obvious areas of concern. There is no
excuse for inadequate cleaning in any hospital; this suggests either that the
cleaners are incompetent or that too little money is being spent on hygiene.
Either way it should be capable of remedy. Other matters are more difficult and
appear to indicate a management which cannot or will not lead and an overall
framework which is simply not capable of meeting the needs of psychiatric care.
We fear that the last two points are nearest the core of what ails the Royal
Edinburgh. The report on the hospital comments on a distinct lack of
involvement by junior medical staff, and whether or not the staff themselves
should carry some blame for this it is surely the duty of management to involve
junior staff and to give them leadership. The inadequacy of nursing provision
is another area in which management must surely have failed, although in this
respect the amount of resources made available to the hospital is obviously
relevant.
Yet whatever went wrong inside the Royal Edinburgh cannot be taken in isolation
from the more general question of care for psychiatric patients, both in
hospitals and as they are moved into the community. The report expresses
concern that patients are being discharged too quickly and that this leads to
problems when these inadaquate preparations lead to a breakdown of care when
patients go into the community. As we have said on previous occasions, there is
nothing wrong with the theory of care in the community, but if patients are not
prepared for this with sensitivity and an understanding that they must not be
pressured, and if care is not continued adequately once they are in the
community, what is a sensible policy becomes a nightmare. There are good points
about the Royal Edinburgh but the problems must be addressed immediately.
</TEXT>
