<DOCNO>GH951220-000049</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951220-000049</DOCID>
<DATE>951220</DATE>
<HEADLINE>This murder is the head of the monster but its tail is always flicking</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Kirsty Scott</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974798898</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THERE'S a colourful Christmas star on the steeple of Henderson Parish Church in
Kilmarnock, but within its walls the minister is grappling with issues, dark
and terrible, which have dimmed the brightest notions of the festive season.
The Rev David Lacy is angry. Angry and weary, and sick to his heart. In some
cold clinical setting, 16-year-old Mhairi Julyan, the daughter of one of his
parishioners, lies dead, her life violated and extinguished just minutes from
the church doors.
And in that one act of evil, Mr Lacy sees a thick layer of moral apathy
stretching from our own front rooms to the broader reaches of society, to
inadequate policing and even to the church itself.
``There is shock about this but with it comes a weariness. It's difficult to
put it into words that you can make sense of. It's a feeling of just how much
we tolerate. From the little things like kids dropping litter in the streets.
We just allow it to happen.
``The only time when the community arises, rises as one and says no, is when
something patently awful and evil happens, but by then it's too late. Some
person out there has all through his life believed he can do what he likes and
now he stops and thinks, I can even take a human life if it suits me.''
David Lacy is 43, a big, bluff man with a son in the same class as Mhairi, a
daughter he can't let out alone at night, and a community searching desperately
for answers or explanation. He thinks we should start by looking closely at
ourselves.
``We are horrified because this is so bad,'' he said. ``But we know all the
other things that happen. This murder, this is the head of the monster but the
tail is always there and it's flicking. Every time it hits at home, it grabs
you by the guts. But it's been happening for too long. This thing is now far
more possible today than it ever was before.
``I'm not angry at anyone. I'm angry at evil and we, the church, are as much to
blame. It's not been popular to talk about evil and sin. We want to tickle
their ears with something a wee bit more palatable and popular. It's the
feel-good factor. We don't tell them how it is. That there is evil and that it
must be fought.''
To win that fight, he said, we need a ``willingness to face up to this in the
political sense''. That means more police for a start. ``It's not the police's
fault, but officers are being drafted in from Kilbirnie for this case. There
aren't enough of them, but it's not their fault. It's our fault and mainly
because if we put up taxes to help the police force people would object, I
would object. Society says we will just get by.
``No; what we need is for everyone, every family, every parent, every school
teacher, when they see something wrong it should be stood up to and society
should support them in that stance. The law should support the victim, not the
aggressor. The policing should support them in their fight against whatever
evil it is.
``Why are we so careful and so precious in our attitudes to the wrongdoer? We
are not supportive enough of the victim until suddenly an innocent victim is
sacrificed.''
Mr Lacy is angry and the rest of Kilmarnock is just as disturbed. This town's
collective heart is breaking, not for innocence lost but for this confirmation
that they, too, live in an often brutal and senseless world.
In the main shopping precinct the talk was mainly of Mhairi's murder, all
thoughts of Christmas vanished under a growing sense of unease and panic. The
grim-faced warnings by the police that parents should keep an eye on their
offspring were almost redundant. Mothers and fathers, tight-lipped and pale,
had made a mental note when Mhairi's body was found on Sunday.
``There's evil all around, isn't there?'' said Margaret Findlay, a mother of
two, aged 12 and 14. ``Even on Thursday night, my daughter walked home at 10pm.
Then there was a school disco last night and when I went to pick her up, every
body was there to pick up their kids, everyone had turned out.''
Up at Kilmarnock Academy, where Mhairi was a pupil, the receptionist is calming
a caller who is apparently making arrangements to collect a child. ``I know,
it's such a worry,'' she said. ``It just brings it all home.''
Along the corridor, past the hall where the school band is rehearsing
half-heartedly for a Christmas concert, headmaster Frank Donnelly has been busy
issuing warnings to parents about the concert and a senior prom, offering
school assistance to make sure the children get home safely. ``I think the mood
here is much more sombre than I can ever remember it,'' he said grimly.
Outside, maybe five minutes walk away, at the bus depot where Mhairi's body was
found, someone has propped two small bunches of flowers against the wall, next
to the police incident room. To one side, an elderly passerby is shaking his
head, eyes bright with tears. ``It's just appalling, awful,'' he said. ``But
then no-one is safe to walk the streets these days.''
Yet while those in the town who had never known Mhairi drew lessons for their
own lives from her death, those who knew her best could do nothing more
yesterday than grieve for a lost companion and a bright, uncomplicated life cut
so brutally short.
Julie-Ann Holland was her best friend. They had known each other since she was
six and it was Julie-Ann who waved her off on the steps of the Palace Theatre
on Saturday night. She was put under sedation after the murder, but spoke to
The Herald yesterday.
``She was walking backwards, with a big cheesy grin on her face, just saying,
I'll see you later, bye now. She went away laughing and joking. She had really
got into the swing of the pantomime, shouting out and all of that. At times she
was the only one you could hear.
``She was so nice, you could tell her anything. She wanted to be a nurse, you
know. To help people.''
Julie-Ann is aware of the strength of feeling about the murder, but the
collective sense of outrage, from Mr Lacy to the man on the street, has done
little to ease her own pain.
``I always tried to protect her, you know, look out for her,'' she said, eyes
creasing tight and the tears finally coming. ``I always tried to protect her
all the way. She was just wonderful.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
