<DOCID>GH951220-000050</DOCID>
<DATE>951220</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Into valley of the shadow for Nato's big battalions</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Ian Bruce, Defence Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974798899</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
GENERAL Sir Michael Walker is the man cast centre-stage in Europe's latest
version of mission impossible. As commander of Nato's 60,000-strong ground
forces in Bosnia, he is about to become the military equivalent of a fairground
Aunt Sally.
Tomorrow he faces his first major challenge in a face-to-face meeting with the
warring parties in Bosnia. His key task is domination of the psychological high
ground. He has the firepower to back his remit. But the major hurdle is
convincing the Serbs that he is prepared to wield the big stick.
Sir Michael, aged 51, must become all things to all men in a land where
duplicity is a way of life. Bosnian Serb leader Radovan Karadzic is Olympic
class when it comes to mendacity. Walker will have to learn to read the small
print between the lines of the sub-text.
In Bosnia, nothing is as it seems. The only recognised law, to paraphrase Mao
Tse Tung, comes from the barrel of a gun. To that end, General Walker has
sought the assurance of big guns. Key components of the British contingent are
a regiment of Challenger tanks backed by infantry in armoured fighting vehicles
and self-propelled heavy artillery.
While the objective remains the peaceful and orderly disengagement of the
opposing armies, Walker, with political backing, has already made it plain that
Nato policy will be robust. Anyone reluctant to comply with pull-back tables
will be, as they say, shown the road.
The British are in the process of shifting 7000 tons of ammunition and 7500
vehicles into their assigned sector. Most of it lies in Serb territory,
including the important military and transport centre of Banja Luka. Before
Yugoslavia disintegrated, the city was an army corps headquarters.
About two-fifths of the 13,100-man contingent is in place. Their immediate job
is changing berets from UN blue and painting their vehicles in the colours of
the trade, camouflage green and black.
The immediate job is ensuring the release of prisoners of war and the
establishment of a demilitarised zone between the opposing forces. Patrolling
that zone and guaranteeing freedom of passage will constitute the first
potential stumbling block on the way to peace.
Previous UN commanders in the area were forever frustrated by the lack of
recognisable chains of command among the Serbs, Croats and Muslims. Deals
struck with one local warlord were not recognised by the next tinpot general 10
kilometers down the track. Negotiation became a morass and the UN effort
drowned in it.
Another part of the initial process is the disarming of civilians. Given that
most of the local forces were militia, that is a daunting order. Yugoslavia
once had the fourth-largest conventional military apparatus in Europe. Everyone
had to complete basic military training. The country was a huge, armed camp.
During the siege of Vukovar in Croatia, whose shattered ruins became a symbol
of the conflict, the Serbs fired more shells than Britain had in its entire
Nato inventory.
General Walker says he will patrol behind Serb lines, brooking no interference.
The intransigence of petty tyrants at roadblocks, the scourge of UN relief
convoys and Protection Force teams for more than three years, has had its day.
From early next month, patrols will roll through unhindered or roll over the
debris of anything standing in their way. God is on the side of the big
battalions.
Backing them up at sea is the aircraft carrier HMS Illustrious with its strike
force of six Sea Harrier jets, two frigates, HMS Brazen and HMS Beaver, and the
destroyer HMS London.
Twenty minutes flying time across the Adriatic at Italian airbases are 12 more
Harriers and eight Tornados, supported by early-warning aircraft and airborne
tankers.
The punch they represent is a powerful one. Being bombed to the conference
table was a salutary lesson for the Serbs.
On paper, Walker's approach and the vast array of weaponry and manpower
available should be guarantors of stable transition from war. But it must never
be forgotten that Nato is dealing with people whose reactions to threat and the
prospect of defeat are not logical.
Two days ago, a poll conducted in Serbia confirmed Ratko Mladic, the ``butcher
of Bosnia'', as the second most popular man in the country. He brought victory,
however fleeting. He gave the Serbs a renewed sense of national identity. The
fact that he has been indicted for war crimes and would, given the chance, lead
them to extinction in a blaze of glory is irrelevant.
Nato's job, and General Walker's reputation as a tough and business-like
soldier, may hang on the Serbs' national whim. The Western alliance is treading
in the valley of the shadow. Peace may yet be a long and bloody way down the
line.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951220-000051</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951220-000051</DOCID>
<DATE>951220</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Cravings of a potty mad trauma victim</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Sara Villiers</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974798900</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
NASTY big pomanders stinking of lavendar and festooned with lime green ribbons;
thick acrylic white socks decorated with bog-eyed reindeer with lolling
tongues; Pocahontas bubble bath; leather-bound desk tidies; wicker baskets all
wrapped up in cellophane full of titchy bottles containing about five drops of
weird smelly stuff which no-one will ever open, let alone use; horrificly
expensive sets of miniature crystal golf clubs and plush toys of any size,
price or description but especially Garfields.
Who buys this cack? I'll tell you who. Women with PMT buy it, that's who.
That's premenstrual tension, or potty mad trauma in layman's terms. Women with
PMT should not be allowed out of doors. They should stay tucked up on the sofa
working off their hormonal hysteria by shrieking insults at The Montel Williams
Show. They should be allowed to take a sickie so they don't pollute the
workplace with their mania. They should not be allowed near blunt objects,
sharp knives, or boxes of matches. Small children, furry animals, and errant
husbands should be locked out of their reach.
But most important of all, they should not be allowed to shop. If department
stores were really sharing, caring places they'd have PMT detectors on their
doors. When the alarm went off the security staff could gently remove the
woman, easily spotted due to that mad-eyed, fixed grin, unaccessorised look
which the PMT sufferer favours, pack her in a taxi, and send her home with the
urgent counsel ``do not shop''.
Of course, as we all know, department stores are not caring, sharing places.
They are places which need to entice PMT'ers through their doors so they can
get rid of the revolting goods which some woman in merchandising designed last
year while in the throes of a particularly evil bout of PMT herself. And,
unfortunately, although the last thing a PMT victim should attempt is a
shopping expedition, it's the very thing which she craves most.
She will shop with the zealous air of one with an assured sense of purpose,
although in fact she won't have the foggiest idea what she's looking for. She's
in search of the consumer equivalent of the Holy Grail, looking for a
mysterious purchase which will give her a sense of warmth and wellbeing and
stop her snarling at Big Issue vendors.
Eventually her eyes will light upon a bright orange and pink reversible hooded
anorak, the kind of clothing which can only be reasonably worn by
three-year-old infants with no road sense who might benefit from its
traffic-stopping abilities.
``If I buy this jacket,'' she will think, ``all will be right with the world
and the buzzing noise in my brain might subside. I could cease shopping, go
home, and watch The Montel Williams Show.''
I know this is how the PMT'er thinks. I am that woman. I have that jacket. It
hangs in my hall as a terrible lesson to me, a potential reminder of the folly
of dashing out to the shops at that certain time of the month. But do I pay
heed? Do I heck. Every four weeks it catches my eye and before I know it I've
shrugged it on and I'm rushing headlong out to the city centre in a frenzied
fit.
I mean, I have wine-coloured tights in my lingerie drawer. How could the woman
at Marks and Spencer have allowed me to buy them? Why didn't she take me aside
and say ``Dearie. No.'' And who were the evil vixens responsible for putting
them out on display in the first place?
Not only did I fail to come to my senses about the wine-coloured tights when I
got home, I actually put them on and went out to a nightclub wearing them. With
a short skirt. They were displayed in all their frightful glory. My friends
gasped in horror and, quite rightly, shunned me. Girls in the toilet queue gave
me pitying glances and kept a slight distance in case my bad taste disease was
infectious. I cared not. I thought I looked fabulous.
The moment I menstruated the very memory of it had me sobbing in shame. A
friend has just sent me a Purple Ronnie card. The verse on the front says it
all. ``Some folks are brilliant at telling good stories/And Being all clever
and funny/But some are just splendid at shopping all day/And spending great
sackloads of money.'' It's entitled ``A poem about a crazy shopper''. When it
comes to crazy shopping I'm right up there in the ranks of the truly barking.
Woof! Woof!
The worst aspect of this PMT shopping affliction is that it invariably grips me
the week before pay day. Not only do I go out spending sackloads of money on
cack I don't need or want, I'm spending great sackloads of money I can't
afford, pitching me straight into overdraft.
I'm trying to pluck up the courage to present a PMT plea to my bank manager.
Well, if it can be accepted in British law courts as a justifiable defence for
murder surely it can excuse a few financial indiscretions.
That said, I'm at least grateful that my PMT ailment only really manifests
itself in shopping insanity these days. Over the past two years my hormones
have settled down and my PMT has subsided from psychotic slagging matches with
innocent bystanders, like dry cleaners apologising for a slight delay in
delivery. These days the murderous impulses have diminished and the symptoms
are more or less manageable; my clumsiness increases in direct proportion to my
grip on rational thought decreasing. I have to avoid thin-stemmed glasses and
important decisions, like whether or not to buy orange and pink anoraks.
BUT at the moment I'm in a state of terror. A glance at the calendar confirms a
scheduled bout of PMT hitting me in the face at the exact time I need to do my
Christmas shopping. I just know that I'm about to buy nonsense presents, like
executive desk toys for friends who work outdoors and a bumper pack of Baywatch
Barbie dolls for everyone else, including my mate's mum.
So that's the reason why we chicks sometimes buy inappropriate prezzies. What's
your excuse boys? Incidentally, if anyone gives me a ``bouquet of wooden
kitchen utensils'' as some unquestionably PMT-afflicted person at Marie Claire
helpfully suggested in their Christmas gift pages, I will have no qualms about
poking the sender in the eye with the pointiest of said utensils.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951220-000052</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951220-000052</DOCID>
<DATE>951220</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Referendum cop-out. Arguing endangers economic interest</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Leader</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974798901</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Prime Minister is undoubtedly pleased with himself. By virtually promising
a referendum on the issue of a single currency he has eased some of the
pressure from the Euro-sceptics on his back benches. It is his way of appeasing
their whining attempts to influence the party manifesto for the next election
and to bend it to a Euro-sceptic line. Now this might constitute excellent
politics for the Tory party but it is not a satisfactory way in which to
conduct the governance of the nation. Those in favour of a referendum will
argue that an issue as important as the single currency must be subjected to
open public debate to be followed by a vote in which the considered and
informed opinion of the nation will be gauged.
Pigs might fly. If past experience of the single-currency affair is to be
repeated we will be in for an unending exchange of furious rhetoric which will
enlighten nobody. Don't take our word for it alone. The Confederation of
British Industry was so irritated by the political debate on Europe that it
warned of a danger that the nation's economic interests were in danger of being
undermined. Does Mr Major really want to condemn us to more of the same? It is
worth repeating the comments of CBI president Sir Bryan Nicholson at greater
length because they constitute a precise description of at least part of what
will take place in a referendum competition. He says that there is no support
for what has already taken place, characterising it as a shrill, xenophobic,
nationalistic debate which does not deal with the real business issues. Here is
the nub. The banner of national sovereignty is waved over the Emu battlefield
by the sceptics at every opportunity, but the loss of sovereignty is arguable
whereas the loss of economic advantage to a Britain which is sidelined from
monetary union would be clear and damaging.
This should not be taken as blind acceptance of Emu. On balance we agree with
the CBI's preference for open options on the matter and a full consideration of
the advantages and disadvantages as they unfold, but all of this should be
undertaken with proper information and a positive attitude towards the
potential benefits. None of it is possible if the threat of a referendum hangs
over the whole affair. Referendums are not necessarily bad but, as we have
indicated already, the sterility of the rhetoric which would flow from a
referendum campaign on a single currency is truly frightening. We have elected
representatives to form mature judgments on this and they have notably failed
to do so. This does not mean that we must seize the task from them. The manner
in which politicians of all parties conduct themselves on this issue in coming
months is an important part of the way in which we will judge them at the
General Election. That is the vote which matters. Talk of a referendum is just
another way for Mr Major and his confused colleagues to avoid yet another
essential duty of government. It will not do.
</TEXT>
