<HEADLINE>Message of hope</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974798902</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ON the morning of Thursday October 26, I left home literally convinced I was in
perfect health and walked up to a mobile medical unit in the Kidston Hall
car-park.
Shortly afterwards my certainty of wellbeing was shattered. On December 12 I
returned home after surgery and six days in hospital.
The mobile unit belonged to the West of Scotland Breast Screening Service - for
the first time my age had brought me within its scope. I was among the one in
100 women whose initial X-rays need clarification.
I am so grateful to the service, and to the surgical team and nurses at the
Western Infirmary for the excellent treatment I am receiving.
My purpose in writing is to urge all women who are invited to screening
sessions to go. Don't tear the letter up or, as I did, foolishly delay
appointments later on.
Christine McGeoch,
30 Whitelea Court,
Kilmacolm.
Message of hope
</TEXT>
