<HEADLINE>Where everything glitters but nothing is gold</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Tom Shields</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>diary</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974798903</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WE are all under stress at this time of year but we feel that Glasgow design
guru Janice Kirkpatrick may be suffering more than most. As evidence we
reproduce part of an article which she contributed to Design Week magazine on
the theme of Christmas colours:
``Then there are the metallics. Never trust a whore, never watch Hearts of
Gold. At Christmas, everything glitters and nothing is gold, Pantone 872 is
only ink on paper. Glittery things induce madness, Versace, and inspire some
very bad seasonal dressing. Silver balls inspire some very bad seasonal dancing.
``Tinseltown was a song by Blue Nile. A Glasgow band with a sensible colour in
their name. They obviously understood how bad things could get at this time of
year.
``Thankfully, Glasgow's streets are not paved with gold. London must be
lathered up and talking in tongues by now.
``In the words of that old song by Billy Ocean, red light spells danger . . .
you have been warned.''
Merry Christmas, Janice, and pass the mulled wine.
Pun of the Week
MR Brent Lockie, depute fiscal, prosecuting three Aberdeen students for the
heinous crime of growing a bit of cannabis in their flat, described it as ``a
joint venture''. Which is worth at least 180 hours' community service in its
own right.
No excuses
THE BBC television programme Only an Excuse has put together a comic
compilation of football parody and pastiche for our delectation on Hogmanay.
Jonathon Watson brings to our screens a flute-playing Gazza, a Graeme Souness
who admits that all that nice violence in the film Midnight Express was his
inspiration for becoming a football manager in Turkey, and a Jim White who asks
on Scotsport ``Did playing those European ties on a Thursday night cost Celtic
valuable league points? Let's hope so.''
The addition of tall, thin, angular actor Alastair MacGowan to the Only an
Excuse team allows the programme to impersonate tall, thin, angular people such
as Alan Hansen, Jurgen Klinsmann, and David Ginola.
But, for the Diary, the best part of the preview we saw was a devastatingly
literate and profound analysis of the game of football as it might have been
seen through the eyes of the MacIlvanney brothers, William and Hugh. In fact we
have taken the liberty of ripping off a great chunk of the dialogue, which
should be read in suitably gravelly and deeply meaningful MacIlvanneyesque
tones:
Hugh: Football is, was, and ever should have been the ballet of the working
classes, the poetry of the po-faced, the concerto of the criminally insane.
William: In our day, when you were talking football, you were talking millions
of mad, mental maniacs. The people's punters, pontificating, pissed, packed
like pilchards on the hallowed slopes of Hampden Park, the nation's national
cowshed.
Hugh: Watching with awesome awe some of the most skilfully accurate men on
earth. I tell you, in those conditions it wasn't easy to pee into a beer can.
William: Of coure this is now and that was then, when you could stand on the
terraces and just soak up the atmosphere through your shoes.
To compensate for this literary stuff, we have the Jim White character talking
about the UEFA three-foreigners rule. ``Or, as we call it in Scotland, the
three diddies rule.''
Wise guys
WE are nearing the end of our quest to name the Fourth Wise Person and say what
gift he or she might bring. Late arrivals at the stable in Bethlehem include:
q Former Scottish Office Minister Allan Stewart who would turn up with an array
of gifts and ask the baby Jesus to take his pick. (Stewart Hunter, Oban.)
q A salesperson from Herod Life, Palestine's biggest insurance company, with a
sales pitch which ends: ``In fact, the only thing you're not covered for is
mass infanticide.'' (Anon.)
q A Palestinian traffic policeman to tell Joseph that his donkey has just been
towed away and a daud of that gold will come in handy if he wants it back. (Jim
Paterson, Larkhall).
But Stuart Lindsday of Erskine shines brightliest today with his suggestion
that the fourth Wise Man would be Brandon Lee, schoolboy of the year, who would
bustle up to the manger with the words: ``Let me through, I'm a doctor.''
Time is running out for readers who wish to win a bottle of Langs Supreme
whisky or a Langs whisky first-footing kit. Closing date for entries, to the
usual address, is tomorrow.
Festive plug
WHAT with there only being four shopping days left before That Day, bathroom
furnishings giant Armitage Shanks has entered the ``what do you buy for a
person who has got everything'' arena.
Never mind your aftershave or under-arm stuff, the company says. Buy your loved
one a bath. It will ``last for years despite being used every day, provide
hundreds of hours of fun and relaxation for all the family, and doesn't require
batteries to make it work!''
Mr Shanks suggests the ``County'' bath, which ``accommodates two people in
comfort''.
For those of generous, even Santa, proportions Armitage Shanks recommends the
``Leander'' - a tub that is both ``generous in size'' and ``one of the
strongest baths available which can withstand great weight and the perfect
companion after a night on the tiles''.
For those whose stature more resembles that of one of Santa's little helpers,
Shanks offers the ``extra-short showertub''. In case you were worrying about
how to wrap up these unusual presents, Armitage Shanks is offering free festive
paper with every bath.
</TEXT>
