<HEADLINE>Clouds on the holiday horizon</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Margaret Vaughan</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974798905</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THERE is a tendency to yawn when the travel trade describes its grim state,
bleats on about this being the most distressing year it has ever suffered and
warns, peevishly, that this time it plans to do something about it. The
industry's cry wolf syndrome has led us to cock a knowing eyebrow and wait,
smirking, for the price-cut banners to appear in travel agents' windows.
This year, though, no amount of hype can disguise the dismal state of the
package holiday business. Yesterday First Choice Holidays, one of the big three
tour operators, announced a major slump in profits to #1.3m. They followed
rival Airtours which last week reported a 22% drop in profits to #59m. Thomson
Holidays are more than 50% down.
The travel industry blames everyone but itself. Yet the evidence is that they
are to blame for the bind in which they now find themselves, although it is the
public who will, literally and figuratively, pay the price.
This year, the major operators are cutting back substantially on the numbers of
holidays available. There will be between 10% and 30% fewer packages available.
A T Mays, the travel agent chain, said yesterday there would be 1.5 million
fewer holidays for sale next year. While bookings have plunged by 30%, brochure
prices have risen by 10%.
The objective, according to one leisure analyst, is to make sure a lot of
people cannot get the package holiday they want, cannot get the hotel or
destination they would like, if they leave booking until early summer. The
operators are aiming to break the cycle of last-minute booking.
Last year 45% of package holidays were booked late - between April and October
- compared with an annual average of 30%. Yet total sales of package holidays
were similar to the previous year. There were 10 million packages on offer last
year. But about 20% of the holidays were so deeply discounted that operators
saw their profits take a dive.
But the late-booking culture is the industry's fault. In the race to lure more
holidaymakers and gain ever more market share, the operators piled on capacity.
More hotels, more resorts, more destinations than any other operators, they
trilled. Now they yelp that they were forced to discount holiday prices to sell
off excess capacity.
Yesterday, in explaining the slump in profits for last year, the chairman of
First Choice, Michael Julien, said the industry had been forced into
significant discounting in June, July and August to sell excess capacity
created - he claimed - by unexpectedly weak consumer demand, partly the result
of the exceptionally hot UK summer. In other words, he blames the feel-bad
factor and, to borrow a phrase from another travel operator, the wrong kind of
weather.
Yet there was no whacking reduction in the numbers flying abroad on package
tours last year. Quite the reverse. What seems to have happened is that the
punters just got smart and waited for the discounts to start before booking.
By increasing brochure prices and reducing the choice of holidays available,
the major operators hope to reverse a trend that has become ever more marked in
the cut-throat package holiday trade.
``The major operators have been unable over the past few years to resist trying
to steal a march on their rivals, and in their greed to grab market share they
have been unable to control capacity,'' said an industry insider.
The enormous collapse of profits is forcing the major companies to address the
difficulties created by their previous strategy, according to John Boyle, who
co-founded the independent Scottish-based travel company Direct Holidays.
``The holidaymaker has had a bonanza for the past year or two. What's happened
now is that the big operators have decided that they can make more money by
reducing capacity.''
Direct Holidays, which as its name implies sells direct to the public, cutting
out travel agents, will announce substantially increased profits this year,
making it probably the only UK operator to make serious money.
The colossal losses, says Mr Boyle, have given the big operators a fright. The
evidence of capacity reduction is clear from the numbers of aircraft charters
scheduled for next summer by the big companies. For example, First Choice is
known to have reduced its fleet by two, sending one to operate out of Dublin
and another to New Zealand; Thomson Holidays have cancelled two 757s they were
due to charter from May, and Airtours have reduced flights also.
</TEXT>
