<HEADLINE>One in eight at risk from alcohol abuse</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By CRAIG WATSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974798906</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ALCOHOL abuse has reached ``staggering'' levels in parts of the west of
Scotland, says Argyll and Clyde Health Board.
The annual report of public health director Dr Lesley Wilkie found that 52,000
people aged 16 or over in the health board area, or one in eight of the
population, were running some degree of risk of damage to their health through
alcohol abuse.
Many of those could be within the Government's new recommended limit for
``safe'' drinking, 28 units in total a week for men and 21 for women.
The report's figures, based on the previous upper limit of 21 units for men and
14 for women, show that most problem drinkers consumed a maximum of
approximately six-and-a-half pints of beer more than the old limit.
The board spends #12m every year on hospital treatment for patients with
alcohol-related illnesses. That amounts to almost #30 for everyone in the board
area, which covers the districts of Argyll and Bute, Dumbarton, Inverclyde, and
Renfrew.
The report said:
q.Deaths from alcoholic liver disease and cirrhosis were 42% above the Scottish
average between 1981 and 1993.
q.The death rate for all alcohol-attributable diseases was increasing and had
outstripped the Scottish rate in recent years (up to 12 deaths per 100,000
compared to the national average of less than nine per 100,000).
Dr Wilkie spoke of the ``truly staggering toll of disease, disability, and
death caused by the misuse of alcohol''.
She said there was particular concern that alcohol-related problems were
affecting more young people and women and added that more research would be
done into ``safe'' drinking levels.
Mr Douglas Allsop, director of the Scottish Council on Alcohol, said: ``This
reinforces the fact that alcohol is a bigger problem than drugs. Rural areas
have specific problems with heavy drinking without the resources to tackle
them.''
Dr Wilkie added that there had been positive findings, such as the success of
exercise and health promotion campaigns.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
