<HEADLINE>Five survive on doomed charter flight from Zaire Plane crashes in Angola killing 139</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Kinshasa, Tuesday</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974798907</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A ZAIREAN passenger plane on a charter flight crashed in northern Angola last
night killing 139 people.
``There were 139 people on board, plus five crew. There were only five
survivors,'' said Zairean Transport Minister Alexis Thambwe Mwamba.
A Ministry official said most of the dead were Angolans.
Hospital staff said five survivors were flown to the Zaire capital Kinshasa
today and four were in intensive care.
``They have been badly burned and their condition is serious. At this stage
they are unable to talk,'' a doctor said.
The fifth survivor, the co-pilot, had been taken away by his family. Five
corpses were also brought back from Angola. Officials there said the plane, a
Lockheed-built Electra operated by the private Trans Service Airlift, had
crashed at Kahengula in Angola's remote Lunda Norte province.
Diamonds produced in the Lunda Norte and Lunda Sul regions are smuggled out via
Zaire and many Zaireans regularly travel to eastern Angola to dig for diamonds
or to buy them.
MADRID: Forty-three passengers on a Venezuelan airliner were taken to hospital
with broken bones or shock in the Canary Islands today after their plane
plunged 3000ft in turbulence over the Atlantic.
``Everything was an inferno,'' said Italian Lorena Rizzo, 24, after the plane,
on a flight from Caracas to Rome, landed in Las Palmas in the Canary Islands.
The VIASA (Venezolana de Aviacion) DC-10 airliner carrying 154 people flew into
a clear-air zone around 2am, according to passengers, and the plane nose-dived,
sending passengers and luggage hurtling around the cabin.
``We were all quiet and suddenly, we entered an air vacuum, and that's all,''
said Italian Carmela Mulas, 66, in hospital with a crushed backbone.
She said that after the drop the captain told passengers through the intercom
that the plane had fallen 1000m and added: ``Thank God, we are alive.''
He then asked for permission to make an emergency landing at Las Palmas, two
hours' flight away, so passengers with spinal injury, broken bones, cuts,
bruises, and shock could be treated.
A number of people refused to get back on the plane and it resumed its journey
to Rome with 24 fewer people on board, said an airport spokesman.
Spanish television showed passengers being driven back to the airport in neck
braces and arm slings. One was sitting in a wheelchair. Five people were kept
in hospital on the Canary Islands.
Local media listed among the injuries a fractured pubis, fractured ribs, broken
vertebrae, a broken sternum, and collar and jaw-bone fractures. -Reuter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
