<DATE>951220</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Family tensions still apparent in court after verdict brands Ashby a homosexual and a hypocrite Tory MP puts a brave face on disgrace</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By JAMES McKILLOP</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974798908</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TORY MP David Ashby last night was determined not to give the impression he is
a broken man after losing a libel action against the Sunday Times and the
newapaper's former editor Andrew Neil.
He took his seat as normal in the House of Commons at question time after a
jury had delivered a devastating verdict against him.
The majority decision at the High Court in London branded the Member of
Parliament for North West Leicestershire as a homosexual, and a hypocrite.
Nevertheless, within a couple of hours he was in his usual place in the House
of Commons.
In court, he sat sobbing with his head in his hands after the jury delivered
their verdict. His estranged wife, Silvana, who had given evidence for the
other side, crossed the courtroom and attempted to console him.
The 55-year-old MP pushed her away after she had put her arms around him and
kissed him on the back of the neck.
``Just leave me,'' was all the MP, newly disgraced by the jury's verdict, could
utter.
He remained in court until two policemen escorted him towards the sanctuary of
his lawyers' chambers in the nearby Temple Inn.
Prior to the case, the MP had lost vast sums by investing with Lloyd's. The
bill for pursuing the libel action, said by the Sunday Times to have been
misguided and illogical, will cost him an additional #500,000.
Mr Ashby, who before yesterday's verdict already had three mortgages to pay,
told the court that he was considering applying for legal aid to finance
matrimonial proceedings.
The MP may have finances to meet his latest legal bill. Nevertheless, it must
have crossed his mind that if he were to be declared bankrupt, he could no
longer carry on as a Member of Parliament. There was no suggestion that was the
case last night.
The scenes in the courtroom yesterday were extraordinary.
Spurned by her husband, Mrs Ashby returned to her seat and buried her head in
her arms. Yet she had spoken out loudly against him from the witness box.
For the Sunday Times, there were mixed emotions. Naturally its legal
representatives were delighted that the newspaper and former editor had been
exonerated. At the same time, there appeared to be some regret that it had come
to this.
``We will have to show magnanimity in our victory,'' said in-house lawyer
Alastair Brett. He anticipated that the current editor of the Sunday Times
would regard the case as a tragic family problem and would be sensible about
what further steps might be taken.
Despite these remarks, his employers soon after issued a statement declaring:
``We are sorry that Mr Ashby decided to take us to court and that he now faces
a substantial legal bill. But it was his choice.''
The statement continued: ``His case and ours could not have been more fully
aired in the High Court and in the end the jury decided in our favour.''
Mrs Ashby told reporters: ``It gives me no pleasure to see my husband lose an
expensive libel action.''
In an extraordinary twist that demonstrated the nature of their love-hate
relationship, she later said: ``I love my husband very much and will always be
behind him.''
She denied being ``obsessively jealous'' or showing, as her husband alleged,
``extreme hatred or violence'' towards him or anyone else.
She added: ``I have no idea what the future holds for me. I hope and trust that
relations with my daughter will return to normal as quickly as possible.''
Before the jury retired, she had heard the judge tell them: ``You have
witnessed a family exposing its misery in the full glare of publicity.''
Yesterday, Mrs Ashby continued: ``I hope it will not have a terrible effect on
him.
``On numerous occasions, I asked him to think twice before continuing with the
litigation.''
Mr Ashby's solicitor, libel action specialist Peter Carter-Ruck, issued a
statement on the MP's behalf. It read: ``I am deeply disappointed by the
decision of the court today. I am very grateful for the kind support of my
constituents during what has been a most traumatic ordeal.''
Against all the odds, Mr Ashby made an immediate appearance in the House of
Commons.
His presence at question time underlined his determination to hold on to his
seat.
Another man might well have applied for the Chiltern Hundreds but a by-election
could prove disastrous for an adminstration that is rapidly running out of a
majority.
While many Conservatives may have worried that the court decision could make a
General Election come sooner rather than later, it was clear last night that Mr
Ashby intends to battle on.
That is his style. The bustling, round-faced, workaday lawyer is the Whips'
idea of a perfect MP.
He rarely said anything out of place. Indeed, he has hardly said much at all in
the House of Commons. Obediently he has paraded through the division lobbies,
always on the Government's side.
Clearly, Mr Ashby's private life is in turmoil and it is almost certain that
the Tory Whips knew all about that.
That they can deal with. In fact, it is something they can use to their
advantage. They will pressurise Mr Ashby to carry on, despite the jury.
For their part, they will welcome his vote every time a division is called.
But many now believe Mr Ashby's political future hangs in the balance.
Officers in his constituency association, who have so far been supportive, said
they would be consulting him in advance of the next executive meeting in the
New Year.
Chairman Clifford McKee said: ``I expect to see him in about a week's time. I
can't comment on any action that may arise from this case until we have had
time to see David and speak to the association executive.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
