<HEADLINE>More emergencies put `bed managers' under pressure</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By ALAN MacDERMID Medical Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974798910</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
HOSPITALS are having to appoint ``bed managers'' to cope with a steady increase
in emergency admissions, according to a report published today.
The rise - 15% in four years in Scotland, 13% in England - is putting many
hospitals under considerable pressure, say the National Association of Health
Authorities and Trusts and the British Association of Medical Managers, who
produced the report.
The appointment of managerial bed-jugglers comes at a time when the NHS is also
under pressure to reduce administrative costs by 5%.
Hospital trusts are also having to set up emergency admission wards and provide
high-dependency units to take the pressure off intensive care.
Nor is the increase a short-term blip in the statistics. The report points out
that in Scotland - where the data has been collected more comprehensively - an
increase of 42% can be traced between 1981 and 1993.
The report says: ``The hospitals affected are experiencing problems in coping
with the relentless flow of emergency admissions at the same time as keeping
pace with the queue for planned care.
``Hospital managers are having to continually juggle beds to accommodate the
influx of patients. Some hospitals have had to cancel operations, often at the
last minute, to find spare beds. Some hospitals have had to close to emergency
admissions - sending the problem elsewhere - for one or two days at a time.''
While the maximum manageable bed occupancy level was said to be 80 to 85%, some
hospitals were running with up to 100% of beds occupied.
Mr Philip Hunt, director of Nahat, said yesterday: ``Trusts and health
authorities are already tackling the problem with some success but we must find
a long-term solution to this new phenomenon so that emergency admissions are
catered for more effectively in the normal day-to-day activities of our
hospitals.''
The report looks to a study by Mr Steve Kendrick, of the information and
statistics division of the NHS in Scotland, for an analysis of the causes. He
found that the 12-year increase spanned all ages and diagnoses, that the number
of people having repeated admissions had increased by 70%, and that 12% of the
increase involved people being re-admitted within 28 days.
The biggest increases occurred in the catch-all group of symptoms including
chest or abdominal pain and swelling, and in poisonings - particularly
paracetamol. Mr Kendrick also suggests that the increase in people living alone
or in small households, without families who can look after them, may play a
part.
Other possible factors cited in the report are rising expectations and
referrals by GPs already overburdened by other work and playing safe for fear
of being sued.
The Scottish Ambulance Service, which is introducing a prioritised system for
responding to emergency calls, has generated increased traffic in recent years
as a result of a promotion urging people to dial 999 immediately if they suffer
chest pains or other possible heart-attack symptoms, because of the benefits of
early intervention.
Although it is seen as a largely inner-city problem, the recently-opened Lorne
and Isles Hospital in Oban this year had a 32.6% increase in emergency
admissions between April and October, compared with the same period last year
in the old hospital group it replaced.
</TEXT>
