<HEADLINE>Skye Bridge protesters challenge toll legality</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID ROSS Highland Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974798911</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
EXCLUSIVE
OPPONENTS of the Skye bridge are still questioning the legal authority of the
operators Skye Bridge Ltd to collect tolls and island councillors are to ask
the new Highland Council to prepare for court action.
At issue is whether the Government followed the proper legal procedures before
the bridge opened on October 16. One particular point is whether they
advertised the identity of the warranted concessionaire, the party licensed to
stop traffic and collect tolls, under the terms of the New Roads and Street
Works Act 1991.
According to the protesters, the Act makes it clear that the certificate of the
warranted concessionaire must be advertised in the legal paper, the Edinburgh
Gazette, and whichever paper the Secretary of State believes best informs the
community most affected by road or street work.
A spokesman for the Scottish Office told The Herald this week: ``That part of
the Act does not apply to the Skye bridge because it is effectively a new road.
It only applies to existing roads.''
Skye and Kyle Against the Tolls (Skat) campaigner Robbie (the Pict) Robertson
does not accept the offical explanation: ``Clearly, the purpose is to ensure
that the travelling public is made aware who the licensed concessionaire is,
who can stop traffic and collect tolls on the A87 using powers orginally given
to the Secretary of State.''
Skye councillor Gavin Scott-Moncrieff, also a Skat member, said yesterday he
would now be asking the Highland Council, which is committed to a campaign to
abolish the present toll regime on the bridge, to seek further legal advice
with a view to applying for interim interdict.
``It is all very well to say the bridge is up now so let's get on with it but
there are many people in Skye who are suffering because of the imposition of
the tolls.
``There are now hundreds of people who have refused to pay their tolls as a
protest and sometime they will have to appear in court. It would appear they
may have no case to answer if the toll collection was not lawful in the first
place.''
</TEXT>
