<DATE>951220</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Princess to miss son's debut</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<FLAG>news digest</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974798912</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
PRINCESS Anne will not be among the crowd to see her son Peter win his first
schools rugby cap for Scotland, it was revealed last night. Her decision was
welcomed by Mr Tom Robertson, president of the Scottish Schools Union, who
said: ``There will be enough pressure on the lad as it is without it turning
into a real circus.''
Peter Phillips, 18, a pupil at Gordonstoun, makes his international debut
against the French Schools at Goldenacre, Edinburgh, on Friday afternoon. He
will become the first member of the royal family to play international rugby at
any level. He escaped injury after being involved in a car accident at the
weekend.
Bucking trend
THE engineering industry is set for continued growth next year despite a recent
slowdown in orders, according to a new report yesterday. The Engineering
Employers' Federation suggested that the United Kingdom market did not grow at
all over the last month but capital expenditure by firms and employment
increased and the industry is confident about the new year.
Shipyard deal
THE 1300 workers at the Kvaerner Govan shipyard on the Clyde yesterday accepted
a new pay deal which will cover them for the next two years. Following a
ballot, they agreed to an increase of 3.27% from January 1 with a further
increase of 2.8% in 1997, depending on the Retail Price Index. The yard also
confirmed a #60m contract for the construction of a ship to be used in the
launching of commercial satellites.
Shops anger
PLANS to extend a major shopping complex in Glasgow have been criticised by
council officials in Clydebank who fear that its own Clyde Shopping Centre will
suffer from the expansion. Details of the latest proposals for the former
Goodyear tyre factory site in Drumchapel were disclosed by Glasgow District
Council in a consultation document.
Theatre plan
THE Denny Civic Theatre in Dumbarton is to receive an #80,000 refurbishment
grant from the Scottish Arts Council Lottery Fund. Restoration work during the
five-year project will include an upgraded foyer area, new box office and bar,
and a small visual arts gallery.
Golf raid plea
POLICE in Renfrew yesterday appealed for witnesses after a man was injured
during a robbery at Erskine Golf Club, Bishopton. Mr James Allan, 63, a club
committee member, was hit on the head with a wooden baton as he chased three
armed men, who earlier had stolen a small amount of money from the club. He was
treated in hospital and later released.
</TEXT>
