<HEADLINE>Row over fuel rods bound for Dounreay</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974798913</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A ROW flared last night after it was revealed that Dounreay is set to receive
cargoes of almost 1000 bomb grade nuclear fuel rods from Belgium.
The highly-radioactive elements will be recycled at the D.1204 reprocessing
plant.
A total of 995 rods containing highly-enriched uranium will be shipped to the
Caithness facility by research organisation SCP, which operates the BR.2
reactor at Mol, near Antwerp.
The deal was revealed yesterday by Greenpeace and later confirmed by the
Belgian Ministry of Economic Affairs.
Yesterday, the UK Atomic Energy Authority, which operates the Dounreay site,
would neither confirm nor deny the shipments.
The deal was criticised yesterday by Greenpeace and by anti-nuclear activist
Rose Young, of the Northern European Nuclear Information Group, which is based
in Lerwick.
Mr Jan van de Putte, of Greenpeace Belgium, said the deal was illegal because
the Belgian Government had passed a resolution against transporting the
material.
He said: ``There is a major threat of A-bomb grade material getting into the
wrong hands, such as terrorist groups or `rogue' governments, who could use it
to make crude nuclear weapons.
``It goes against the wishes of the Belgian parliament and that of the Scottish
people.''
Ms Young said: ``Once again Dounreay is to be used as the world's nuclear waste
dump. The transport is dangerous, the reprocessing is dangerous and the storage
of such nuclear fuel is lethal.''
She added: ``We now face the prospect of fuel from Australia, Germany, India,
Britain, Belgium, and possibly the United States, coming to Dounreay, against
the wishes of the local people.''
Dounreay will not disclose the value of the new contract, but it is believed to
be in the region of #20m.
The D.1204 plant, the only facility in the Western world available for
recycling fuel from research reactors, has been mothballed for the past year,
but is set to re-open next month.
Yesterday, Mr Ian Shepherd, spokesman for Dounreay, said: ``We never discuss
specific contracts for reasons of commercial confidentiality.'' But he stressed
that Dounreay operated its reprocessing activities in accordance with tough,
internationally-agreed guidelines.
Last week, in a poll organised by Caithness Against Nuclear Dumping, voters in
Caithness voted two-to-one against Dounreay's plans to import foreign
atomic-fuel for reprocessing.
</TEXT>
