<HEADLINE>Lottery cash aids home for festival</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By KEITH BRUCE Arts Editor</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974798915</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Edinburgh Festival Society became the recipient of the largest Scottish
award yet to an arts organisation from the proceeds of the National Lottery.
Of the #4.2m of grants announced yesterday, #3m goes to the society towards its
plans to convert the Highland Tolbooth Church at the top of the Royal Mile into
a home for the festival.
The #7.3m plan will see the building, which was built as the Church of
Scotland's Assembly Hall in the mid nineteenth-century, converted into
exhibition space, a performance and rehearsal hall, box office, cafe, bar, and
offices. The announcement of support from the Scottish Art Council through its
National Lottery committee will pave the way for other public bodies to support
the project.
The festival's Mr Nick Dodds said indications of support had already been
received from Edinburgh District Council, Lothian Regional Council, and Lothian
and Edinburgh Enterprise Limited.
It is planned to open the centre in 1998.
The second largest grant announced yesterday was for a mobile cinema for the
Highlands. The award to Hi-Arts is for the construction and running of a lorry
trailer-based cinema modelled on the French Cinemobile which has visited
Scotland.
Exceptionally, the lottery committee granted #50,000 to the project to assist
with initial running costs, in addition to its #330,317 capital grant. The
construction of the vehicle will be commissioned in March, with the aim of
having the 100-seat cinema on the road in September.
Another arts vehicle on the road next year will be the Book Bus which has been
part of a campaign to promote books and reading. A #30,000 grant will enable a
new company, Readiscovery Touring Ltd, to buy the bus to continue the work.
</TEXT>
