<DATE>951220</DATE>
<HEADLINE>`Family from hell' living lives of Greek tragedy</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974798917</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE ``family from hell'' was an unkind but not an inaccurate sobriquet coined
by observers of Tory MP David Ashby's libel action. This was not the usual
hurly-burly of suburban ups and downs but an altogether more dramatically
dysfunctional set-up, reminiscent of an American soap or even a Greek tragedy.
Mr Ashby's 52-year-old wife Silvana claimed he threatened to kill her. He
pointed a knife at her chest, put a lighter to her skirt, and a pillow over her
face, she said. But she adored him even now, she told the jury.
In the MP's version, Silvana Ashby was a Latin Jekyll and Hyde with a vicious
vocabulary who once attacked him in the rockery, and fought with everyone - but
especially builders.
Their bizarre mutual tenderness even found expression outside court each
morning as, before the next bout of mud-slinging, they would kiss each other
continental-style on both cheeks.
In the midst of this emotional quagmire their only child, Alexandra - who lives
abroad - claimed to love them equally, but sat next to her father and bitterly
denounced her mother's possessiveness.
Silvana Ashby remains close to her 83-year-old mother and sister, who still
live in Italy.
But Mr Ashby has a tortured relationship with his sister Lynne, exacerbated, he
claimed, by Lynne Ashby and his wife being sworn enemies.
It was Lynne Ashby, dubbed the ``malevolent sister'' by the judge, who went to
the press with stories about the MP and Dr Kilduff. ``She hates me,'' said Mr
Ashby. ``She was determined to get me. She was coming in for the kill.'' She
even drew doodles of him hanging from a gibbet.
Bobby Sheridan, the homosexual partner of the MP's late brother, Brian, branded
Lynne Ashby ``cuckoo'' and claimed she was bent on destroying all her brothers
so she could have the business.
Whatever the truth of life in the ``crazy house'', as the MP described it,
there was abundant evidence during the case that the Ashby family lavished more
care on its four elderly, incontinent dogs than on each other.
Ironic from an MP whose last election address read that he was ``married with a
family and therefore understands the needs of families''.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951220-000069</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951220-000069</DOCID>
<DATE>951220</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Holbrooke to take on challenge of Cyprus</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>From PATRICK BROGAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974798918</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Washington, Tuesday
RICHARD HOLBROOKE, the man who negotiated the Bosnia peace treaty, is to leave
the government next year, after one last effort to resolve the Cyprus dispute.
He will return to Wall Street, where he used to be an investment banker,
holding himself in readiness to become secretary of state if the job is offered
him in 1997.
Mr Holbrooke is assistant secretary for European affairs. He was always a
staunch advocate of taking a firm line on the Balkans, but until last summer,
his advice was ignored. President Clinton and Secretary Warren Christopher
preferred the soft, European line and the war continued.
After the fiasco of the first Nato air-strike and the taking of UN hostages,
then the capture of Srebrenica and the massacre of its inhabitants, Mr
Holbrooke was at last allowed to apply the full force of American power and
diplomacy.
The result, after four months of shuttle diplomacy, was the reversal of the
situation on the ground and the Dayton peace agreement. Mr Holbrooke has many
enemies in Washington, but his success makes him the obvious candidate to
succeed Mr Christopher if the president is re-elected.
Mr Holbrooke will probably leave in February. Before that, he will conduct a
round of shuttle diplomacy in a new attempt to break the long stalemate over
Cyprus. A Turkish army has occupied the northern part of the island since 1974
and repeated efforts to reach an agreement between Greece, Turkey, and the two
sides in Cyprus itself have all failed.
Mr Holbrooke told the Washington Post: ``We intend to make 1996 the year of the
big push on Cyprus.''
</TEXT>
