<DATE>951220</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Former Minister awarded #40,000 for slur</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974798920</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TORY MP Peter Bottomley was yesterday awarded #40,000 damages by a High Court
jury which found by a majority that he had been libelled by a Sunday Express
article.
Mr Justin Walford, legal adviser to Express Newspapers, which was also ordered
to pay the estimated #250,000 costs of the eight-day trial, said the company
was considering an appeal because of the questions raised over press freedom.
Mr Bottomley, husband of Heritage Secretary Virginia Bottomley, was accused in
the article of betraying jailed paratrooper Private Lee Clegg by appearing at a
meeting with Sinn Fein leader Martin McGuinness.
The former Northern Ireland Minister said after the hearing: ``I don't mind
robust criticism or even vulgar criticism but this stopped me doing what I have
devoted my life to - ending the violence in Northern Ireland.''
Mr Thomas Shields QC, who represented the MP, had told the hearing that Mr
Bottomley had been ``shocked and horrified'' when he read the article last
January which linked his sharing a platform with Mr McGuinness and the failure
to free Private Clegg who at that time was in jail for murdering a joyrider in
Northern Ireland.
The 51-year-old MP for Eltham had told the court he was prepared to talk to two
Sunday Express journalists at his Surrey home and had explained he did not see
any link with his decision to appear at the meeting and the failure of the
House of Lords action to free Private Clegg.
However, the article which appeared the following day did not contain one
reference to his remarks to the journalists.
Mr Justice Blofeld, advising the jury on damages, had told them that any award
should take into account damage to political reputation.
He also indicated to them how much could be awarded in cases of personal injury
under new guidelines set by the Court of Appeal last week.
Mr Walford said after the hearing: ``We are disappointed with the result and we
shall be looking very closely at mounting an appeal.''
q.Two Metropolitan policemen who sued the BBC over a Panorama programme which
they claimed painted them as racists yesterday won a total of #16,500 libel
damages.
In a unanimous verdict, a High Court jury awarded Constables Christopher Wright
#12,500 and Peter Callaghan #4000.
The BBC was also ordered to pay the costs of the case, unofficially estimated
at #200,000.
The BBC denied libel and pleaded fair comment. It argued that the officers were
not identifiable from the programme - which dealt with a crisis of confidence
in the police among East End Asians - and that it did not accuse them of being
racist.
</TEXT>
