<DATE>951220</DATE>
<HEADLINE>On the fringe of lunacy</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KEN SMITH</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974798921</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
What's in a name? Usually a pun if you're a hairdresser, finds KEN SMITH, as he
combs the country
Hairdressing salon names would make you just want to Curl Up and Dye with
embarrassment. Other businesses can happily get by with the simple name of the
owner above the door. Malcolm Campbell's is a fine enough name to sell an apple
or two without resorting to calling it What A Pear or Gnaw Your Onions.
If it's not the owner's name, then a simple description of the services on
offer will suffice. What could be simpler than The Bank of Scotland? No need
there to have a chain of banks called the Cash Inn or Cheque It Out.
But hairdressers. They reach for the Book of Puns quicker than for a can of
lacquer as soon as they get the keys to a salon. Some were probably thought to
be quite smart the first time they were used. Cut Above for example, or Blow
Your Top, or Streaks Ahead. Unfortunately crimpers keep most of their
imagination for their hairstyles. Any novelty these names once had was soon
dissipated by the fact they have been reproduced the length of the country.
Others though turn to thoughts of their spare time, and in hairdressers' cases
that means keeping fit or foreign holidays. Thus in Glasgow we have the Hair
Port, Haircraft, Hair 2000, and Hairobics salons. Those interested in a night
out at a show have dreamed up, would you believe, Dyes 'n' Dolls as well as
Beyond the Fringe. Or perhaps there was a romantic filmgoer who chose Perfect
Endings.
These are all scissor-wielders in Glasgow. Outside in the country though things
begin to be a shade more weird. It may attract Aberdeen fans, but The Shearing
Shed in Dunoon sounds just a tad rough and ready. Ayrshire is just as bad with
Shear Magic in Dalry and The Head Gardener in Prestwick. We all know people who
look like they've been done over by a sheep-shearer, we just didn't think
salons would boast about it.
Only in Lanarkshire would a salon have the honesty to call itself Nutters. But
it doesn't say whether that's the staff or the clients.
Some do, of course, use their name, in a straight-up way such as Betty's in
Coatbridge or Janette's in Partick. Others try to be a bit more fanciful such
as Deb 'n' Hair. In Glasgow's Candleriggs, actor John Comerford runs a salon
and just calls it, well, John Comerford. So why the puns elsewhere John?
``Straight up, hairdressers don't have the imagination to think of anything
else. Although I do like the salon I saw called Michaelangus. I mean, is it
just run by two guys called Michael and Angus who ran their names together to
make it sound like Michelangelo? I'd hate to go in and ask them though, in case
they say they've never heard of Michelangelo. Mind you, I've never heard of a
hairdresser called Angus either.
``I'm sure there must be a Short 'n' Curlies out there somewhere, and there's a
Public Hair in Nottingham, I think, which is just waiting for someone to muck
about with the sign. I think some hairdressers should be a bit more honest
though and call what they do Cut and Run.''
Others are a bit more obscure. I mean, I may only have got an O-grade in
French, but does A Sans Cheveux not mean without hair? And the Tin Tin Hair
Studio. Who would want a haircut like a Belgian cartoon character? Then there
is Pele Hairdressing in Glasgow.
I don't recall the Brazilian footballer having a flowing mane or nipping into
Glasgow for a quick cut and blow-dry. Co-owner Fraser Stroak at Pele's
explained: ``Well there's three of us in the partnership and all three of us
would have argued over the name for ever. But all three of us are football
daft, so we finally settled on Pele. It's short, easy to remember, and he's
well known.''
Certainly makes more sense than calling it after Bobby Charlton.
Nor is it just a West of Scotland thing, this constant punning. Bristol, for
example, can offer you Friendly Wave, or perhaps the more unfriendly nineties'
names of Parting Company, Cutting Comments, and Head Case.
So why did John Comerford stick with just his name? ``My dad's name is John,''
he recalled, ``and the day before I opened it, he came to see it, and he was so
proud of me. And the tragedy was he died suddenly the next day, so I've really
named it in memory of him.'' He choked back a sob.
That's such a sad story. ``Yes,'' he added. ``And not a word of it is true you
gullible fool.''
See hairdressers? They can be so cutting at times.
</TEXT>
