<DATE>951220</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Nato force confident of mission</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>From KURT SCHORK</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974798922</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Sarajevo, Tuesday
NATO began a final countdown today to its biggest operation in 50 years,
confident that it has the men and political muscle to bring Bosnia the peace
its UN predecessor failed to deliver for 3!s years.
``I do not underestimate the challenge but Ifor (Implementation Force) has been
given the tools to do the job,'' said Britain's General Sir Michael Walker,
commander of Nato ground forces in Bosnia, on arrival in Sarajevo today.
``We offer the chance for something everybody wants - peace,'' he told
reporters as scattered units of the multi-national force grouped for
deployment.
Bosnia was ripped apart in ethnic crossfire during Europe's worst conflict
since the Second World War, which killed 200,000 people and displaced between
two and three million.
D-Day for the Nato-led peace enforcers, eventually to number 60,000, starts
around 11am tomorrow, when they formally take over from the United Nations in
Bosnia.
Nato officials said the first test could come within days of the Implementation
Force (Ifor) succeeding the blighted United Nations Protection Force (Unprofor)
when new commanders order Serbs and Muslims to quit front lines in the Bosnian
capital, Sarajevo.
French troops patrolling Sarajevo have earmarked several sites they want
vacated. Walker is to meet leaders of the warring parties on Thursday to say
what he wants.
``Sarajevo is the key, it is first chronologically and politically and will set
the tone for the rest of the operation,'' said one senior Nato official.
``These people have been at war a long time and no-one wants to be the first to
pull back.''
A spokesman for the departing UN mission gave a final briefing for journalists.
``We who have survived the war are handing over to the peacemakers,'' Alexander
Ivanko said.
``Hopefully we will now see the final chapter in this tragic war and the start
of a new era in Bosnia.''
The UN, criticised for its operation in Bosnia, will take away from Bosnia
little thanks from a people bitter at its failures and forgetful of its
achievements.
Today, however, the organisation defended the performance of its staff there
and pledged to continue to work in the civilian sector.
``For more than three years, United Nations personnel in Bosnia worked to
contain the conflict and lighten the burden of suffering civilians,'' said a
spokesman for Secretary-General Boutros Boutros-Ghali.
``They were not sent there to stop the war, yet were asked to shoulder the
blame for the lack of peace.
``They brought humanitarian relief to millions, while agonising over the deaths
that they could not prevent.''
UN troops teamed up with the UN refugee agency to deliver hundreds of thousands
of tons of humanitarian supplies that kept Bosnians alive despite the raging
war around them, the statement added.
``In the process, 110 peacekeepers died, over 800 were wounded, hundreds were
taken hostage, some more than once,'' it said.
``They did their job; they did it well. This should not be forgotten.''-Reuter.
</TEXT>
