<HEADLINE>Health boost</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<FLAG>news digest</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974798923</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
HEALTH workshops aimed at reducing stress among Aberdeen District Council staff
have proved a success. A three-day series of the health and well-being
workshops were held in October at the administrative buildings in Kittybrewster
and St Nicholas House and were attended by 493 employees, about one sixth of
the workforce.
Robbery bid
A JUVENILE was arrested after an attempted robbery at the sub-post office in
the village of Kirkgunzeon, near Dalbeattie, Dumfriesshire, yesterday. Police
said the sub-postmistress was unhurt and no weapon was involved.
Drugs case
POLICE raided a flat and seized 11 cannabis plants being grown in the loft,
Aberdeen Sheriff Court heard yesterday. University student Scott Fraser, 22, of
Westholm Avenue, Aberdeen, Stephen Kay, 21, of Elmfield Avenue, Aberdeen, and
Neil Forbes, 21, of Monreith Road, Newlands, Glasgow, admitted growing the
plants earlier this year. Sheriff David Kelbie deferred sentence until January
12.
Festive haul
THIEVES have stolen 10 Christmas food hampers worth #2000 after breaking into a
refrigerated van parked in the Spittal area of Berwick.
Poison charge
A MAN has been charged with poisoning three cats in the village of Greenlaw,
Berwickshire, over a two-week period earlier this year. Mr Ian Archibald, 48,
of Blackadder Crescent, Greenlaw, is to appear at Duns Sheriff Court next month.
</TEXT>
