<HEADLINE>Couple jailed for attack on pensioner</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE McKAIN Law Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974798924</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A COUPLE who took part in a sadistic attack on a 79-year-old pensioner were
each jailed for eight years yesterday.
Mr Charles Wells suffered a fractured cheekbone as he was repeatedly punched in
the face. He was also forced to drink as a bottle of rum was thrust into his
mouth.
Temporary judge Alexander Wilkinson QC told Gail Hope and Earl Young at the
High Court in Edinburgh: ``You brought into reality what must be the nightmare
of any elderly person living on his or her own.......Such people must be
protected.''
Hope, of Ferry Road, Edinburgh, was found guilty unanimously of an assault on
Mr Wells in his Edinburgh home on August 20 this year during which he was
robbed of #20.
Young, of West Montgomery Place, Edinburgh, admitted assault and robbery.
The court heard that Mr Wells, a retired widower, used to go to a public house
for an hour every day to enjoy a pint of beer and read his newspaper.
He struck up an acquaintance with Hope and agreed to put her up for the night
after she phoned to say her boyfriend had put her out.
This happened on several occasions and he usually gave her a meal, a drink, and
cigarettes. Eventually he got fed up and on August 20 told her not to come back.
That afternoon, Young, whom he had never met, appeared at his door and claimed
that water was leaking from his kitchen into the flat below.
But when Mr Wells let him in, Young said: ``I am going to give you a going
over.'' Young then opened the door for Hope.
Hope got a bottle of rum from the kitchen and Young held the old man's wrists
while Hope tried to pour the drink down his throat.
Mr Wells said his lips were cut and bruised by the bottle. ``She kept pouring
the rum. Some was going into my mouth but most on my shirt and the chair until
the bottle was finished.''
Young punched him between 10 and 20 times on the face and chest. Mr Wells
added: ``He took his time. There were 10 to 15 seconds between punches, maybe
more.''
At one point Hope hit him over the back with a standard lamp.
Mr Wells told the court that his right cheekbone was fractured and he needed
stitches for a gash over his left eye.
</TEXT>
