<HEADLINE>Presents of mind</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Ann Shaw</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974798925</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Ann Shaw offers psychological advice on the gift of giving
IF YOU are knee-deep in wrapping paper or too exhausted with trekking around
shops, known as the ritual sacrifice of time by psychologists, you may still be
looking for some last-minute ideas for presents.
Remember that successful present giving depends less on the value of the gift
than on your ability to analyse accurately the personalities of your relatives
and friends. Yes - psychologists have been working away at this rich vein and
have recognised three distinct types.
The key is to tune into their needs. Knowing what drives a person is the most
effective way to understand likes and dislikes. The three motivations
identified are: affiliation, achievement, and power.
Those in the affiliation group want to please and make friends. They look at
the method of presentation more than the gift itself. With them it is the
thought that counts. Scented soap, genuine beeswax candles, books of handmade
paper or homemade cookies will all be appreciated.
In the achievement slot they are highly competitive, work hard, like flattery,
and are confident, active and determined. They see gifts as trophies - tokens
of the high esteem in which they believe they are held. Value certainly counts
with them. You're safe with any new fad or designer-labelled gift, desk toys,
car mascots, monogrammed pen or pencil or tickets to the hottest show in town.
The power people are driven by money - they are influential and leaders. They
prefer to give rather than to receive. Despite their success and wealth they do
like to receive gifts, provided they are appropriate, and useful. Look out for
army knives, credit-card holders, state-of-the-art desk or travel alarm clocks.
All this and much more is explained in Just What I've Always Wanted by Susannah
Constantine and Pia Marocco (Quadrille Publishing, #12.99). It makes a superb
gift in itself.
Once you realise what makes your family and friends tick present-giving is no
longer a lottery; you can buy and wrap with confidence.
Shirley Conran offers the best bit of advice: ``So that I'm never caught short
of a gift when I haven't time to shop (a chronic condition of the working
mother) I keep a permanent gift drawer for little gifts that I buy when I see
them; also in this drawer is a gift-wrapping box in which are scissors, a
Sellotape dispenser, white tissue and cream, narrow real satin baby ribbon; you
might try this with a more daring colour scheme.''
Remember some of the nicest gifts cost nothing. Conran says one of the most
thoughtful gifts she ever received was from her future mother-in-law who gave
her for Christmas a collection of photographs of her bridegroom as a little boy.
This brings me on to the subject of hand-made gifts. There is something extra
special about receiving a present that's been made, especially if it is edible.
For, despite the commercialisation of Christmas, an increasing number of people
do take pride in creating simple, thoughtful gifts. Not only is it cheaper but
it avoids High Street hassles.
Where do you start? Look no further than Mrs Beeton's Hand-Made Gifts (Ward
Lock, #15.99). Her book captures the real joy of giving. Here you will find
gifts for every occasion from Christmas to Mother's Day and wedding
anniversaries.
For those who like the challenge of making their own Christmas decorations, I
recommend Myra Davidson's excellent Christmas Crafts (Cassell, #10.99). It's a
bit late for this year, though, unless you are very nifty with a pair of
scissors and a sewing kit - but the book itself makes a good gift for anyone
keen on the crafts.
</TEXT>
