<DATE>951220</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Secret document on conditions at the Royal Edinburgh lists more than 50 criticisms MP calls for inquiry at hospital</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By ROB ROBERTSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974798926</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE full extent of the concerns of an independent health watchdog about
conditions at a Scottish psychiatric hospital became apparent last night in a
secret six-page document studied closely by The Herald.
More than 50 points of criticism are contained in the minute of a three-hour
meeting between officials of the Scottish Health Advisory Service and managers
at the Royal Edinburgh Hospital.
Last night, local Labour MP Nigel Griffiths wrote to Scottish Secretary Michael
Forsyth, asking him to launch an inquiry. Mr Griffiths is to meet patients'
representatives in the next few weeks.
A seven-strong team from the SHAS, an independent body funded by the Scottish
Office, spent five days investigating conditions at the hospital between
October 9 and 13. The document spells out major concerns over the hospital,
which has a staff of 630 and an annual budget of about #21m.
Among the points raised were:
q Concerns that patients were being discharged too quickly. Current discharge
procedures raised the risk of a breakdown of care when patients go into the
community.
q There was a strong case to reduce the bed numbers to at most 20 per ward,
maybe 15.
q They detected a sense of lack of involvement from the meeting the inquiry
team had with junior medical staff, which was rearranged because no-one turned
up for the first one.
q The practice of ``pinching'' nurses from one ward to staff another was
described as bad news and the nursing staff needed clear professional
leadership.
Fears were raised that there were too few nurses dealing with too many patients
in overcrowded wards. In some cases, patients felt unsafe and the agencies
involved at the hospital were not working as well together as they could.
Consultant staff said they felt left out of the strategic planning process and
the business plan and thought there was a lack of faith that things were being
fought for explicitly and loudly.
The standard of cleaning was described as ``abysmal'' and there were worries
that, if things such as catering problems arose at the hospital, the management
organisation would not be able to deal with them.
Last night, Dr Donald Rankin, director of the Scottish Health Advisory Service,
condemned the leaking of the document, which he insisted was not an SHAS report
but minutes of preliminary discussions between SHAS officials and the trust.
``This document has not come from anyone within this organisation. I deplore
the leaking of what is a confidential document before the final report has been
agreed and its contents made known to the trust and the health board.''
Dr Rankin said SHAS had never been afraid of criticising hospitals but its work
depended on maintaining confidentiality until it had drawn up its final report.
``We are working on a draft and will publish the report by the end of
January,'' he added.
The document does list 15 ``good features'' at the hospital, which included
educational work, various projects, and the positive attitude of clinical and
social work staff.
Mr Jim Kiddie, support worker with the Royal Edinburgh's patients, said
patients and their families had raised concerns over the staff levels and
conditions at the hospital at a number of meetings.
Mr Griffiths, MP for Edinburgh South, said he had visited the hospital in
February and raised his concerns on a number of issues with management. ``It
saddens me to see that, months later, the same problems are remarked on by the
inquiry team. Action must be taken at the hospital to improve conditions in the
light of this document,'' he said.
A spokeswoman for the Royal Edinburgh said last night she could not comment on
any matters at present because the hospital had not seen any report.
Patients demeaned ...............12
</TEXT>
