<HEADLINE>Gold rush on  Death Railway</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>From ANDREW CHANT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974798927</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Bangkok, Tuesday
TREASURE hunters relying on a mystic monk and an 83-year-old nun are hunting
for a #250m hoard of gold they believe Japanese troops buried during the Second
World War.
The nun was the wife of a Japanese Imperial soldier during the construction of
the Death Railway, where thousands of Allied prisoners-of-war died building a
link between Thailand and Burma.
The site is near the famed Bridge on the River Kwai, 20 miles east of the
Burmese border.
The nun's claims to know the whereabouts of a train full of hidden Japanese war
treasure were taken seriously last week after a government excavating team
found a train line buried 6yd underground. The track led to a cave which
appeared to have been blocked with boulders and cement. On Saturday, the team
sealed off the area and posted army guards after finding three Second World War
train carriages buried under the rubble.
Deputy Education Minister Chaovarin Latthasaksiri said: ``I believe gold bars
might be buried there. Only the mad would have dug so deep to hide three
coaches loaded with stones.''
Today, an earth mover turned up only dirt and limestone. However, the Minister
vowed to continue the search.
The hunt was triggered by Thai businessman Tom Meesiri, who found a section of
the underground railway track after hiring a Buddhist monk to divine the
location of the hoard.
</TEXT>
