<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951220-000079</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951220-000079</DOCID>
<DATE>951220</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Russian premier stands firm against Communists</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>From TIMOTHY HERITAGE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974798928</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Moscow, Tuesday
RUSSIA'S triumphant communists today thundered towards seizing one-third of the
seats in the lower house of parliament, but Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin
rejected their calls for big policy switches.
``Changes, shifts, sackings - nothing of the sort will happen,'' Chernomyrdin
insisted.
``Personnel changes have routinely taken place and will take place in future
but they have nothing to do with this election.''
The Kremlin said that Chernomyrdin and Yeltsin had discussed personnel issues
at the Barvikha sanatorium outside Moscow where the president is recovering
from a mild heart attack, but no details were given.
``What is essential for us is stability and above all economic stability,''
said Chernomyrdin.
Rubbing salt in the wounds suffered by President Boris Yeltsin and the Russian
reformers, Communist Party candidates took 49 of the 195 single-seat
constituencies declared by mid-afternoon.
The communists also led Sunday's election to the State Duma with 21.5% of the
votes on a separate list which counts support for parties rather than
individuals.
Nationalists extremist led by the fiery Vladimir Zhirinovsky were second on
10.8% and Chernomyrdin's Our Home is Russia party was third on 9.7% support.
Communist Party leader Gennady Zyuganov told a news conference: ``In all
probability we will have about 30% of the votes in the party list, and a little
bit more than that in single-seat constituencies.''
According to Interfax, government experts believe the communists are likely to
end up with around 150 out of the parliament's 450 seats.
They said Zhirinovsky's Liberal Democratic Party would win 49 seats from the
party list section and one constituency seat.
Our Home is Russia would win 43 party list seats in addition to at least 10
constituency seats, while the fourth-placed Yabloko party would get 37 list
seats and 12 constituency seats.
Many of the 225 constituency seats have been won by independents whose
allegiance is likely to be clear only when the Duma meets.
Zyuganov said his party would seek allies in parliament to strengthen its hand
and demanded shifts in economic policy.
However the Duma has little strength under a constitution which puts most power
in the hands of the president and Chernomyrdin at once ruled out any change of
direction after talks with Yeltsin.
``What is essential for us is stability and above all economic stability,''
Chernomyrdin said in a speech to the Federation Council, the upper house of
parliament.
The West has reacted calmly to the communists' success and financial markets
have been unruffled because they regard a presidential poll next June as more
important.
In Brussels, new Nato Secretary General Javier Solana vowed to expand the
Alliance eastwards to take in former Warsaw Pact countries, but said Nato must
co-operate with Moscow.
Zyuganov has warned Nato against expanding and said today the Baltic states of
Estonia, Latvia, and Lithuania should not rush into new alliances.
Grigory Yavlinsky, whose liberal Yabloko party is fourth in the party list
section with 7.7% support, warned reformist groups must unite to fight the
communists in the presidential race.
Results were coming in much more slowly than expected. Some international
observers, who gave the vote a clean bill of health overall, said they were
concerned about the delays but election officials ruled out the possibility of
foul play.-Reuter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951220-000080</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951220-000080</DOCID>
<DATE>951220</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Bruised Santa hangs up sack</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974798929</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Canberra, Tuesday
A BATTERED Australian Santa Claus has said he will no longer be coming to the
boisterous outback town of Bourke after he was attacked by a group of children.
Santa and an assistant elf fled to the police station for help and had to
continue their mission handing out sweets from a police wagon with a police
escort, Santa told reporters today.
``They were kicking me in the groin, pinching, punching in the kidneys, and
trying to grab the sweets and remove my disguise,'' said local businessman John
Holmes.
The attack on the 14st Holmes by 30 children aged eight to 13 occurred after a
carol-singing concert. ``I wouldn't have liked to be out in the open for
another five minutes,'' said Holmes.
It was the third time in three years that a Santa has come under attack in
Bourke. In 1993, a different Santa was dragged from his boat on the Darling
River and partly stripped.
Last year, children at a youth centre threw bottles at Holmes during his Santa
appearance. After the latest attack, he says he will not be donning the red
suit and white beard again.
STOCKHOLM: A Swedish forest owner has found a way to get even with Christmas
tree thieves - by pouring sewage on the branches. It makes a foul smell when
the tree is taken inside and the frozen sewage thaws.-Reuter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951220-000081</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951220-000081</DOCID>
<DATE>951220</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Former Slimmer of Year tells of weight gain `fine'</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974798930</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A FORMER Young Slimmer of the Year told a court yesterday how she signed a
contract agreeing to pay a ``fine'' of #10,000 a week for every pound she went
over 10!s stones.
``I thought it was a good incentive to lose weight,'' Michele Deakin told
Liverpool Crown Court. It's a lot of money. But they didn't want me turning up
at promotions advertising the (diet) product weighing 20 stones again.''
She was giving evidence as a prosecution witness in the trial of Australian
Peter Foster, 32, former fiance of model Samatha Fox.
Mr Foster, of Hadley Wood, Barnet, north London, denies conspiring to supply
slimming granules under the name Deakin Diet, contrary to trading standard
rules.
Miss Deakin, 27, mother of four-year-old twin girls, was named Young Slimmer of
1988 by a magazine.
The court heard she was contacted by Mr Foster and persuaded to endorse his
diet product which consisted of guar gum, which swells up in the stomach and
makes people feel full.
However, she had never used it. Her weight loss from 22 stones to 10 stones was
entirely due to her own efforts.
In return, Miss Deakin, then 19, was to receive #1000 a week as long as she
stayed slim, plus royalties from the product. Yesterday, Miss Deakin said she
received only about #2000.
The jury heard that Miss Deakin appeared at a Liverpool court in April 1990
when she pleaded guilty to the same charge Mr Foster now faces.
She received a sentence of six months' imprisonment suspended for two years.
The trial continues.
</TEXT>
