<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951220-000083</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951220-000083</DOCID>
<DATE>951220</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Ordeal over for kidnapped travel tycoon</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974798932</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Zurich, Tuesday
MILLIONAIRE Geo Mantegazza, one of Switzerland's richest men, was freed
tonight, a day after he was kidnapped.
He appeared in satisfactory health after his ordeal, said police.
Mantegazza, 67, was abducted from his office in the town of     Paradiso in the
Italian-speaking canton of Ticino yesterday.
Mantegazza is co-owner of the Swiss travel group Globus-Gateway Tours, which
includes the Cosmos holidays group and Monarch airline. His brother, Sergio,
runs the group from London. He also has several property firms.
A police statement announcing the businessman's release gave no further details
and did not indicate whether he had been freed by his kidnappers or by a police
operation.
However Alex Pedrazzini, president of Ticino canton, hinted in a radio
interview that no arrests had been made, saying a hunt was on for the
kidnappers.
Police commander Franco Ballabio had earlier kept a virtual blackout on details
of the kidnapping. ``A person's life is at stake,'' he said.
Police were earlier reported to have contacted Interpol about the kidnapping.
Italian police also helped in the case.
Swiss newspapers had speculated that Mantegazza had been taken over the border
into Italy.
There were unconfirmed reports that his wife had received threatening phone
calls, claiming that he would be killed if she informed police.
One Swiss newspaper said the family had received a ransom demand.
Such kidnappings are rare in Switzerland. Many rich and famous people choose to
live in the Alpine nation precisely because they feel assured of safety and
discretion.
Mantegazza lives in the lakeside southern city of Lugano with his second wife
and a four-year-old son.
The Mantegazza brothers were ranked among the 200 richest Swiss this month,
with estimated joint holdings of #1001m to #1700m. Monarch is one of Europe's
biggest privately-owned charter airlines.
The brothers also own luxury properties in Ticino and England.-Reuter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951220-000084</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951220-000084</DOCID>
<DATE>951220</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Whistle-blowing is rejected</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974798933</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A PLAN by health Ministers to make ``whistle-blowing'' on their colleagues a
contractual responsibility for doctors has been rejected by Greater Glasgow
Health Board.
The board has told the Scottish Health Department that it would be fraught with
difficulties.
Dr Harry Burns, director of public health, told the board meeting yesterday
that the plan would create a climate of fear and suspicion, and could be used
as a stick with which to beat doctors. Its main implication was that doctors
could be disciplined formally for failure or apparent failure to report
inadequate performance on the part of a colleague.
``We have a considerable amount of experience in the identification of
variations in the standard of clinical practice - that is one reason why we
have clinical audit.
``It is a subtle and complex matter. In many instances, apparent poor
performance is due to a combination of factors outwith the control of the
clinician and to put individual doctors in a position in which they could be
disciplined for failure to respond to evidence of poor clinical performance
which may be difficult to interpret is, in our view, unreasonable.''
Dr Burns acknowledged that there had been instances where clinical negligence
had been so gross that colluding in a cover-up would have amounted to
professional misconduct. However, the new legislation covering the General
Medical Council empowered it to deal with such cases.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951220-000085</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951220-000085</DOCID>
<DATE>951220</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Chance of white Christmas leaves bookmakers chilled</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By KEITH SINCLAIR</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974798934</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BING Crosby's celebrated dream of a white Christmas could come true in
Scotland's cities this year, according to weather forecasters.
They say sub-zero temperatures are expected to arrive from the Arctic today and
remain until after Christmas Day, increasing the likelihood of a blanket of
snow falling in Glasgow, Edinburgh, and Aberdeen on Monday.
A white Christmas is, however, more likely in Aberdeen and Edinburgh than in
Glasgow because eastern parts of the country will suffer most from freezing air
coming from the North Pole.
The weather forecast meant bookmakers suffered another bout of the jitters
yesterday. William Hill is offering evens - down from 3-1 - on snow falling in
Glasgow, Edinburgh, London, Birmingham, and Nottingham on Christmas Day.
Heather Reid, a weather forecaster at Glasgow Weather Centre, said yesterday:
``It's possible that snow will fall in Glasgow and Edinburgh on Christmas Day.
``But I think Edinburgh stands a better chance than Glasgow because most of the
wintry weather will be on the east side of Scotland.''
She added: ``It's even more likely in Aberdeen.''
The odds on bets for a white Christmas have been sliding back in recent days.
William Hill spokesman, Mr Graham Sharpe, said shops were already facing a
six-figure payout if flakes fall on Monday.
Figures show that the last white Christmas in Glasgow was in 1980. The last
time snow fell on Christmas Day in Edinburgh was in 1962. Snow fell last on
Christmas Day in Aberdeen in 1993.
Snow flurries are forecast for the east and possibly in parts of the west today.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951220-000086</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951220-000086</DOCID>
<DATE>951220</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Two killed in road accident</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974798935</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A YOUNG father and a friend died when they were run over as they tried to cross
the A90 Aberdeen-Dundee road.
Mr Michael Smeaton, 26, and his neighbour, Mr David Bruce, 56, both of
Broomfield Caravan Park, Montrose, died on Monday evening near Laurencekirk,
where a contra-flow system is in operation.
Mr Smeaton had been visiting Fourdoun, where his two daughters live with his
former partner.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951220-000087</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951220-000087</DOCID>
<DATE>951220</DATE>
<HEADLINE>The Herald car winner</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>by Chris Starrs</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974798936</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
By CHRIS STARRS
HERALD reader Patricia Bain got an early Christmas gift yesterday, a #16,000
sports car.
Mrs Bain received a new MGF - the first MG model to be built since 1980 - as
the winner of a competition run by The Herald, Rover MG, and Scottish MG
dealers.
Her husband Norman put his wife's name on the entry form, which was the first
correct one drawn from more than 18,000.
Mrs Bain, 41, an adult education tutor, of First Avenue, Netherlee, Glasgow
said: ``The MGF is a beautiful car, I just can't believe it's mine. I thought
someone was playing a joke on me at first.
``I've been driving for 20 years and I always fancied a sports car but I would
never have been able to buy one.''
Only 16,000 MGFs will be produced each year at the company's factory in
Longbridge, Birmingham.
The prize was presented at Shields Rover on St Andrews Road, Glasgow, where
owner Joe O'Donnell said the competition had provided a tremendous boost for
the car.
The competition question was ``What do the letters `MG' stand for?'' - Morris
Garages.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951220-000088</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951220-000088</DOCID>
<DATE>951220</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Man dies in Oban firen</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<FLAG>NEWS DIGEST</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974798937</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AN elderly man died last night after fire broke out in his flat at Cawdor
Terrace, Albany Street, Oban. Police were contacting relatives before releasing
his name.
Two other residents of the block, brothers Neil and Angus Campbell, and three
police officers who attended the scene, Constables Darryl Burnside, Alisdair
Barlow, and Derek Crooks, were treated for smoke inhalation at the Lorn and
Islands District General Hospital.
Climbers rescued
TWO climbers were rescued from one of the country's most treacherous ridges
last night by A Sea King helicopter from RAF Lossiemouth. Police in Inverness
said the men had been stranded on 3000ft Aonach Eagach. They were reported to
be safe and well.
Jobs threatened
HIGHLAND Council workers face an uncertain Christmas after it was announced a
further 180 jobs could be axed. The move follows a reduction of 65 white-collar
posts in the run-up to April's launch of the new authority.
Keep it clean
MOTORISTS face on-the-spot #20 fines in a police crackdown on roadway ``grime
crime'' - where number plates on cars, vans, and lorries are obscured by dirt.
A senior police officer at Lanarkshire's traffic department said fines would be
imposed under the Road Vehicles (Conditions and Use) Regulations, 1986.
Sellafield jobs
UP to 1000 jobs are to be created by a new #360m plant for treating nuclear
waste at Sellafield in Cumbria. The plant is to open in 2002.
Suicide pact
TWO schoolgirls made a suicide pact before one threw herself under a train and
the other threatened to jump off a bridge, police said today. One of the
15-year-olds dived under the wheels of a train as it approached Southampton
Central Station last night. She slipped between the tracks and the train passed
over her, leaving her unscathed. Her friend was spotted earlier in the day
threatening to jump off a bridge in Southampton.
Theft charge
A MAN charged with stealing about #853,000 from the Salvation Army over a
four-month period in 1992 was granted bail when he appeared before Bow Street
magistrates in London yesterday. Mr Stuart Christopher Ford, 44, unemployed,
formerly of Audley Road, Stetchford, Birmingham, was remanded on bail until
February 13 on condition that he surrender his passport and reside at an
address in Halifax, West Yorkshire.
Bedside vigil
ACTRESS Una Stubbs has pulled out of a play after her son collapsed with a
suspected brain haemorrhage. The 58-year-old star, who made her name as Alf
Garnett's daughter Rita in Till Death Us Do Part, travelled 200 miles to the
bedside of musician son Christian, 24, from the West Yorkshire Playhouse in
Leeds where she was starring in Peter Pan. A spokeswoman said Christian
successfully had undergone an operation to remove the clot at a London hospital
after he collapsed last week.
Christmas joy
FOREST Enterprise has stepped in to make sure an injured Portuguese worker has
a happy Christmas with his family. Manuel Da Fonceca Ribeiro suffered a spinal
injury in a fall while working for a contractor in Castle Douglas Forest in
Kirkcudbrightshire. He was taken to Dumfries Infirmary and it looked as if he
would not be able to get home for the festive season as his boss had returned
to the Continent. Yesterday, forestry bosses arranged to pay for Manuel's
flight home.
</TEXT>
