<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951220-000089</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951220-000089</DOCID>
<DATE>951220</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Grandchild plea ends woman's terrifying ordeal</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE McKAIN Law Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974798938</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A MASKED intruder who subjected a 56-year-old postmistress to a terrifying
ordeal after breaking into her home was ordered to be detained for six years
yesterday.
Mrs Christina Paterson's nightmare ended only after she told Sean Padden of her
fears she might never see her newly-born grand-daughter.
Padden, 20, who had been drinking and taking cannabis, admitted striking Mrs
Paterson repeatedly on the head with an air pistol to her injury on May 6 this
year after breaking into her home in Perth.
Mr James Campbell, advocate-depute, told the High Court in Edinburgh that Mrs
Paterson had fallen asleep in the living room but woke up to be confronted by a
figure armed with a gun and wearing a balaclava.
The man shouted at her and tied her thumbs together.
When she tried to run into the kitchen she was struck several times on the head
with the gun. Mrs Paterson told the intruder she feared she would never see her
newly-born grand-child and he calmed down, said he would not hurt her, and
left. Mrs Paterson told police she might know her attacker. She had known
Padden since he was a child and he lived just along the road.
Padden, of Murray Crescent, Perth, admitted the attack to police and said he
had climbed through an open window because he wanted to get in out of the cold.
Mr Brian McConnachie, for Padden, said his client accepted it must have been an
extremely terrifying ordeal for his victim and was genuinely remorseful.
Mr McConnachie said Padden had fallen out with his mother and step-father and
had been told to leave the family home. He had the air pistol because he
intended spending the night in nearby woods and wanted to scare off anything or
anyone that came near.
He had been drinking and smoking cannabis and when he saw the open window at
Mrs Paterson's house he climbed in. When she woke, she panicked, which induced
panic in him.
He believed he had struck her three or four times with the gun during a
struggle and was brought to his senses when Mrs Paterson mentioned her
grand-daughter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951220-000090</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951220-000090</DOCID>
<DATE>951220</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Schools face funding cap</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974798939</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SECONDARY schools in Edinburgh are facing the possibility of five-figure cuts
in their budgets next year because of the ``double whammy'' of severe capping
and the cost of local government reorganisation.
The warning came yesterday from Councillor Elizabeth Maginnis, convener of
Lothian region's education committee.
She said: ``It is a very grim situation indeed and makes a mockery of the
Government's predictions that education would be protected under its spending
plans. We are not crying wolf.''
Councillor Maginnis said prospects would have been less severe if the Scottish
Office had applied the more generous capping levels which will take effect in
England and Wales.
The shadow Edinburgh City Council has not had a definitive statement about its
grant-aided expenditure but has predicted a 10% cut across the board to take
account of capping and the cost of reorganisation.
Councillor Maginnis said: ``From discussions with colleagues across Scotland,
the picture is looking as severe as it is for Edinburgh.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951220-000091</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951220-000091</DOCID>
<DATE>951220</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Tribunal told of feud at family-run garden centre</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974798940</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A FAMILY feud ended up before an industrial tribunal following the death of the
senior partner of a garden centre.
Miss Margaret MacDonald, 34, whose father Ronald died of cancer last year,
claimed she was forced out of her job at the garden centre by her father's
brother and her aunt.
She told a Glasgow industrial tribunal how the remaining partner, her uncle, Mr
Allan MacDonald, wanted to sell the entire ground, including the land where her
family home stood so that he could go to live at his house in Spain.
Then he said the nursery business, MacDonald Brothers, at Bogton Nurseries,
Muirend Road, Glasgow, was to continue as a going concern as it would fetch a
better price, Miss MacDonald claimed.
Miss MacDonald, of Glasgow Road, Stewarton, told the tribunal that she, her
mother Constance, her brothers Angus and Ian, her cousin David, and her Aunt
Patricia all worked at the nursery or garden centre.
Miss MacDonald told the tribunal of the strained relationship between her and
her aunt. ``It wasn't a normal relationship. I was tolerated, she was
tolerated. But it was a successful business and we didn't allow anything to get
in its way.''
After her father's death, Miss MacDonald claimed her Aunt Patricia began
interfering in the running of the shop at the garden centre, she was
countermanding instructions and staff began to leave.
She claimed she was left short-staffed at Easter, one of the busiest weekends
of the year and over May and June, the hottest and busiest summers she could
remember.
She had to give up her only day off and had to work weekends when her aunt went
on holidays and she was expected to cancel prior engagements.
``It was horrific and I complained to my uncle. Staff didn't know who to take
instructions from. Before my father's death, they took instructions from me but
now I was just an assistant like them.
``They started talking back to me. Pressure was such that I couldn't cope.''
Miss MacDonald said the incidents leading to her departure were a culmination
of events to get rid of her: ``I was a thorn in the flesh. They wouldn't have
to pay me redundancy and they got me out of the way.
``It got to the stage there was no other way out. I wanted to be there to see
what I had worked for, what I had slaved for, being sold.
``How would you feel when, the day after, someone changed the locks? I was
still living there and that is what happened. Next day, my cousin walked up and
took my job. Maybe he was only helping out, I don't know.''
Miss MacDonald said she told her uncle that circumstances were beyond her
control and the only way she could cope was to resign.
``I wanted him to turn round and say, `Margaret, what's wrong?' He wasn't
giving me any support.'' She agreed she was given a pay rise earlier this year.
The hearing continues in February.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951220-000092</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951220-000092</DOCID>
<DATE>951220</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Mr Happy wasn't thinking straight</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By CAMERON SIMPSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974798941</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IT was a sad day when Mr Happy - the only successful slogan and logo Glasgow
has ever had - was killed off.
However, according to new research by psychologists, the council leaders who
presided over his untimely demise may have been right. Being happy can stop you
thinking straight, they say.
The Roger Hargreaves character, who sold the city throughout the world in the
1980s with his infectious energy, was left out of the Year of Culture 1990 and
suspended officially in 1991, to be followed by a succession of forgettable
replacements.
Now, Dr Mike Oaksford and a team from Warwick University have concluded that
when it comes to logical deduction, happy people do not perform well. In fact,
the reasoning strategies observed in positive-minded people were similar to
those seen in patients who had suffered damage to the frontal lobes of the
brain.
In a paper presented yesterday at the British Psychological Society's
conference in London, Dr Oaksford and his team found that both positive and
negative mood states impaired reasoning performance.
However, for certain problems specifically set up to test deductive thought
processes, only the subjects in a happy mood performed badly.
Glasgow District Council chiefs did order Mr Happy to be dusted off again last
year to highlight the city's image.
It was all very low key but it could no doubt provide the British Psychological
Society with an agenda for a new conference.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951220-000093</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951220-000093</DOCID>
<DATE>951220</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Where matters sexual are not open to question</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By KEN SMITH</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974798942</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE people of Nairn on the Moray Firth can be a reserved lot. Thus a number of
them were surprised to be asked about their sex lives. In particular whether
they were heterosexual, homosexual or bisexual.
Some no doubt did not know what a bi was but they were pretty sure they had
never had sex with one.
Then there was the question about their ethnic origins, whether they were
black, or even if they were not Highlanders but from elsewhere.
It sounded, perhaps, as if some race group was monitoring whether there were
too many white settlers taking over in the town just north-east of Inverness.
The nosey-parkers however were simply the local housing association, the Albyn
Housing Society, which next month takes over 80 houses in Nairn from Scottish
Homes, the Government housing agency. In order to show that it did not
discriminate against minorities in its housing allocation, it had to ask
tenants some searching questions.
However, the Rev Bill Wallace, of the Church of Scotland's board of social
responsibility, was not happy: ``I cannot see any positive purpose in this. It
is stirring up issues which do not exist in the Highlands.
``There is a real danger that this sort of thing could open up a Pandora's Box
of resentment about outsiders and minorities. Highland communities have always
been open and friendly and we have a traditional reluctance to pigeonhole
people in this way,'' he said.
Albyn, which manages 1300 houses throughout the Highlands, explained that it
had to gather information on sexuality, race, religion, and disability to show
that it did not discriminate.
Senior housing officer David Brookfield said: ``The information we will gather
through this survey is for monitoring our equal opportunities policy and will
be treated in the strictest confidence.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951220-000094</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951220-000094</DOCID>
<DATE>951220</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Stagecoach runs into merger snag Perth-based bus group awarded the first passenger rail franchise</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By IAN McCONNELL and ROY ROGERS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974798943</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WITHIN hours of Perth-based bus group Stagecoach being awarded the first
passenger rail franchise, the Office of Fair Trading raised the possibility of
a monopolies investigation.
Coming from a fellow Government department, the OFT view could be considered an
embarrassment to the Office of Passenger Rail Franchising (Opraf), which would
have been hoping that the letting of the South West Trains franchise to
Stagecoach would go without a hitch.
Labour has also called for the intervention of the Monopolies and Mergers
Commission.
Stagecoach is no stranger to the MMC, which recently accused it of ``predatory
and deplorable'' actions in putting a municipal bus company in Darlington out
of business.
In contrast, Opraf said of Stagecoach: ``They are good value for money, they
have a commitment to running a really good business to the benefit of
passengers, they are in the business for the long term, and they have a dynamic
management team.''
Stagecoach, which already runs buses in South West Trains' territory and plans
to provide dedicated bus feeder services to some rail stations, is set to move
on to the rails early in the New Year.
However, an OFT official said yesterday: ``I would certainly expect us to be
looking at it.
``As far as we are concerned, it is just another merger. We are concerned with
the effects on competition because we have one transport company taking over
another transport company, albeit different forms of transport.''
The OFT would advise Mr Ian Lang, President of the Board of Trade, on whether
or not he should refer Stagecoach's acquisition of South West Trains to the
Monopolies and Mergers Commission.
An MMC official said: ``I am sure all the Government departments will be having
a think about whether we should be looking at it. At the moment, nothing has
happened, so we will have to wait and see.''
Former ScotRail chairman, Mr John Cameron, Stagecoach's rail adviser and a
director of the post-privatisation South West Trains, welcomed the ``real
prospect of providing an integrated service between rail and bus transport''
and believed this would encourage the use of public transport.
Mr Cameron said, because rail privatisation was a ``very regulated'' process,
Stagecoach was committed to certain criteria which he believed would ensure the
company did not run into conflict with the OFT.
Stagecoach, which intends to bid for all of the rail franchises including
ScotRail, plans to upgrade stations in the South West Trains' network and
improve passenger information.
Pay, conditions, and pensions of the 4000 staff would all be protected but
Stagecoach admitted that ``some staff cuts'' might be required although it was
hoped that these could be achieved through voluntary redundancy and early
retirement.
Stagecoach, which is acquiring South West Trains for a nominal sum, will
receive a subsidy of #54.7m in the first year of the franchise. For 1995/96,
the Government earmarked #83.4m of financial support for the train operating
company within the public sector.
In current prices, Stagecoach's subsidy will gradually decline to #40.3m in
2002/03, averaging #49m over the seven-year life of the franchise.
Stagecoach will provide guarantees of #42m in respect of its franchise
obligations, including a #21m performance bond.
South West Trains operates suburban and mainline services out of London's
Waterloo to more than 200 stations, principally in south-west London, Surrey,
Hampshire, and Dorset. The biggest of the 25 franchises being sold off in terms
of passenger revenues, it employs nearly 4000 people, runs more than 1000
trains and carries nearly 100 million passengers each year.
Although Stagecoach is pledged to run improved services on about half the
current subsidy, Labour transport spokesman Brian Wilson claimed the company
was only obliged contractually to provide 86% of the current timetable in light
of the minimum passenger service requirements specified by Opraf.
Calling for a monopolies inquiry, Mr Wilson said: ``Usually, the OFT are
running round the country trying to catch up with Stagecoach. On this occasion,
they have the opportunity to pre-empt developments.''
Opraf, aware that South West Trains is a busy commuter network covering an area
where railways have ``considerable monopoly power'', said a wide range of fares
would be regulated.
However, only 47% of South West Trains' passenger revenue will be subject to
fares regulation.
Stagecoach chairman Brian Souter said he was bidding for all available
franchises and was particulary keen to concentrate on other London commuter
services where be believed a largely captive market was getting a raw deal.
``You have to take out a bank loan to get on to a train down here,'' he said on
leaving the official launch ceremony of the first privatised franchise staged
at the QE2 Conference centre in Westminster.
Despite the likelihood of the bulk of Stagecoach operations being sited in the
London area, the company had no intention of quitting where skilled staff were
available and the quality of life in Perth was superior.
Transport Secretary Sir George Young said: ``This is the most important
announcement for passengers since the privatisation process began. People will
be able to see for themselves the quality of service being offered by those in
the franchise bidding process.''
Mr Jimmy Knapp, general secretary of the RMT rail union, issued an early
warning to Stagecoach against redundancies, stressing that he could not see to
run more services, or even run the existing services, and cut jobs at the same
time.
Franchising contracts covering Great Western Trains out of London Paddington
and LTS (London, Tilbury, and Southend) are imminent and could be finalised
today and the second tranche of contracts, including the East Coast Main Line,
are due to be let early next year.
The pressure group Save Our Railways yesterday conceded defeat over the first
batch of franchises and ended, at least temporarily, its High Court action.
Shares in the Perth-based company yesterday leapt 11p to 293p.
</TEXT>
