<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951220-000095</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951220-000095</DOCID>
<DATE>951220</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Much more to see than a mere flying circus</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Keith Bruce</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974799034</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Keith Bruce, while hissing at Hook, finds himself enchanted by Scottish
Ballet's Peter Pan production
THIS is the story our parents did not warn us about; instead, they read it to
us as they tucked us up in bed. J.M Barrie's Peter Pan has become more potent
with every passing paranoia of the 90s.
From the weird and incomprehensible world of Michael Jackson and his Neverland
retreat - a phenomenon that makes Presley's Graceland excesses look like a
study in showbusiness mediocrity - to the reality of the Jamie Bulger killing
and media anxiety about loss of innocence in our youngsters, this tale of the
boy who declined to grow up is a parable of our times.
Alongside Robert Louis Stevenson's Treasure Island, it is one of the most
enduring contributions Scotland has made to our twentieth-century
commonplaceness. Children's literature, drilled into us all at an early age,
has the power to do what adult books cannot. The continuing enthusiasm among
the pre-schools for images of pirates can be traced back to those two books.
It stays with us all our life and the notion of piracy as something undoubtedly
illegal but neither evil nor wicked, and worthwhile if only to keep the
bureaucrats at bay, finds a home in each successive technological advance. Home
taping is killing music? That'll be right.
While Stevenson's Jim Hawkins undergoes a lesson in life, Barrie's Peter
presents problems that have had literary analysts reaching for their Freudian
analogies. How quickly we forget what the story meant to us as we grew up.
First there was the phase of flying. Headlong jumps from the first landing that
ended in tears. A lesson in life every bit as profound as Jim-lad's.
Then we begin to wonder about the boy's relationship with Wendy - this usually
dawns alongside the realisation that avoiding growing up is not an option and
girls are not necessarily to be universally despised. Later still, we twig what
Tinkerbell's problem is - a crucial lesson - and that rich tapestry of all our
future dealings with the opposite sex is set in a mixture of marshmallow and
concrete in our hearts. Goethe might have invented the concept of romantic
love, but Barrie simplified the equation.
Self-knowledge will later normally allow us to identify some continuing
Pan-like tendencies, but the memory of that bumpy landing on the lobby floor
will still keep most of us on the right side of fantasy.
All of which makes Scottish Ballet's Peter Pan the show of the Scottish festive
season, the storytelling genius of Stuart Paterson (to be seen in Dundee,
Edinburgh, and Stirling) notwithstanding.
Ignore the dance critics on this one, because they have their own agenda, which
most of the Christmas theatre audience probably care little about. There is
nothing particularly awful about the dancing here. I've seen Scottish Ballet
much worse. This is charming and light and they neither bump into one another
nor get seriously out of time with the music.
If Graham Lustig's choreography is neither disciplined classical ballet nor
exciting modern dance, so what? The narrative drive to the piece is actually
very impressive, particularly in the current revised version.
It was only at the very beginning, before he adapted to the pace of the story -
and impatient for the departure of Mr &amp; Mrs Darling and the entrance of our
hero - that my three-year-old asked: ``When is the Mummy going to go?''
Margaret Woznica's design suits both this narrative directness and the seasonal
nature of the show. No fussiness or ambiguity here. Eddie McGuire's music is
quite simply perfect. Easy to listen to and appreciate but far from dumb, his
use of Scottish traditional music is appropriate to the author's origins and to
the folk-tale spirit of the piece.
I saw the show - for a second time - at a matinee packed with kids. Unbidden,
we hissed Captain Hook and a gesture from Rupert Jowett's Pan had us applauding
Tinkerbell back to consciousness (you'd forgive a girl like that anything). We
loved the cutesy crocodile and believed a boy could fly. That'll do me for an
afternoon.
n.Peter Pan is at Glasgow's Theatre Royal to December 30.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
