<DOCID>GH951220-000096</DOCID>
<DATE>951220</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Private sector beckons Bethel</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Ken Smith</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974799035</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTLAND'S enterprise network is losing one of its leading executives. Archie
Bethel, chief executive of Lanarkshire Development Agency, has announced he is
going back to the private sector, writes KEN SMITH.
He is joining Motherwell Bridge, Scotland's largest private engineering
company, as managing director of its manufacturing division.
His resignation comes only days after Secretary of State Michael Forsyth
announced a 7.5% cut-back in funding for Scottish Enterprise and its satellite
enterprise companies. However, the two events are not connected.
Mr Bethel was the only local enterprise company chief executive recruited from
the private sector when the network was established in 1991, and it was always
anticipated that he would return at some point.
He said yesterday that despite the cut-back he still believed the funding was
available for the major development and job-creation programmes currently
planned.
LDA is Scotland's second largest Government-funded enterprise company and, with
the others, will learn what its budget for next year will be from Scottish
Enterprise's headquarters in January.
Mr Bethel is staying with LDA until the end of March.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951220-000097</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951220-000097</DOCID>
<DATE>951220</DATE>
<HEADLINE>FAO calls for rise in cereal output</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974799036</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE United Nations Food and Agriculture Organisation (FAO) has warned that
world cereal output must rise at least 4% in 1996 to safeguard food security.
A new report by the FAO, the UN ``watchdog'' on food supply, added a warning
that dwindling stocks and high prices may damage some poorer Third World
nations.
``With 1995 crop estimates now much firmer, it is certain that cereal stocks
will be drawn down sharply even to meet the reduced consumption requirements
now expected,'' its latest Food Outlook said.
``This will mean continuing high cereal import costs with possible serious
implications for low-income, food-deficit countries.''
The agency said the world needed bigger harvests in 1996 to ensure food
security. ``To meet only the currently expected below-trend utilisation in
1996-97 and to prevent a further erosion of world cereal stocks, a minimum
increase of 4% will be required,'' it said.
The FAO said its latest forecast for 1995 world cereal output was 1.883 billion
tonnes - eight million tonnes less than it last forecast in September.
Cereal stocks were expected to fall by 47 million tonnes to 226 million tonnes
in 1996-97. ``At this level, the ratio of cereal stocks to trend utilisation in
1996-97, at 14% to 15%, would be well below what the FAO secretariat considers
the minimum necessary to safeguard world food security,'' it said.
The FAO said a draw on stocks was expected despite a likely decrease in global
cereal consumption by some 2% in 1995-96. The decrease was a result of a sharp
drop in animal feed use in developed countries because of high prices.
Its current forecast for 1995 world cereal output would be 64 million tonnes or
3.3% below the revised estimate of production last year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951220-000098</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951220-000098</DOCID>
<DATE>951220</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Larry Fish becomes Royal Bank's highest paid director as Peter Wood sees income slump by #24m Citizens chairman earns #1.5m</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW WILSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974799037</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LARRY Fish has replaced Peter Wood as the most highly paid director of the
Royal Bank of Scotland.
The chairman of the extremely successful Citizens retail banking subsidiary in
New England earned #1,547,000 in the year to September, whereas Mr Wood, who
founded the Direct Line insurance business, saw his total slump from
#24,466,000 to just #486,000.
The previous year he gained #13m from the buy-out of his interests in Direct
Line as well as a #7,064,000 pension fund top-up and a #4m bonus.
The annual report shows that chairman Lord Younger had a comparatively modest
uplift from #226,000 to #242,000, while chief executive Dr George Mathewson,
who still has a three-year contract, was just #8000 better off at #485,000.
It also shows that the board has exercised substantial numbers of share
options. Dr Mathewson was sitting on a profit before tax of #1.44m and
operations director Norman McLuskie realised #727,000.
Unfortunately for them, they sold at 465p rather than waiting until the
takeover fears swept the City. These drove the price up to a peak of 658p last
week, although the shares have retreated rapidly, dropping another 17p to 568p
yesterday.
Last Friday, corporate and institutional director Iain Robertson exercised
options over 80,000 shares or more than half his option holding at 620p for a
#341,000 profit.
Retail banking director Tony Schofield is now the biggest option holder at
275,000 with a striking price of 193p.
The Royal is the first bank to comply fully with the Greenbury Code on
disclosure of directors' remuneration.
Citizens has been a major achievement for Dr Mathewson. When it was acquired in
1988, there was a widespread feeling it would not amount to very much and
certainly not reach his target of contributing 10% of group earnings.
But it has consistently out-performed its peer group and is the only bank in
New England not to have incurred losses in the recession in the early nineties.
Profits in the last five years have leapt from #11m to #107m. In contrast, the
parent had a rocky period in 1991 and 1992, the nadir being when profits from
the on-going businesses fell to #32m before bounding ahead three years later to
last time's total of #602m.
That meant the Royal is the only British bank not to have lost money in the US
- there have been tales of woe from Barclays, HSBC with its Marine Midland
subsidiary, and National Westminster before John Tugman got to grips with
NatWest Bankcorp.
The major reason Midland is now a subsidiary of HSBC is its disastrous purchase
of Crocker National Bank in California which was stuffed full of dud property
and Latin American loans.
The greatest humiliation was that the sale of Crocker's head office prevented
Midland actually falling into the red.
Citizens has concentrated on making acquisitions within 100 miles of its
Providence, Rhode Island, headquarters. That has enabled it to grow its
customer base with less risk than if it had cherry picked takeover
opportunities across the US.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951220-000099</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951220-000099</DOCID>
<DATE>951220</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Armstrong poised to sign on the dotted line</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DEREK DOUGLAS, Chief rugby writer</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>24</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974799038</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
GARY Armstrong expects to sign the contract which will take him to Newcastle
within the next few days.
Lawyers acting for the Scotland scrum half and Sir John Hall's new superclub
have been examining the contract in detail for a fortnight but yesterday
Armstrong said all had now been agreed and there remained only the formality of
an official signing.
Armstrong made his debut for the club during a guest appearance when Newcastle
played Transvaal last month and expects to be involved in the latter part of
the Tynesiders' Courage League II programme early in the new year.
The three-year deal, worth more than #150,000, will see Armstrong form a
half-back partnership with England's Rob Andrew who moved from Wasps and
sacrificed his international career in order to become Newcastle's director of
rugby on five-year contract reputed to be worth #750,000.
Armstrong's fellow Borderer Doddie Weir is also still involved in negotiations
with Newcastle and, along with Dean Ryan, Tony Underwood, and Nick Popplewell,
the new recruits will form the spearhead of Andrew's plan to gain promotion to
the English first division and, ultimately, to play in Europe and realise Sir
John's dream of making Newcastle the biggest rugby club in Europe.
Yesterday, Armstrong, 29, said: ``Everything has now been agreed and although
it will be a wrench to leave Jed-Forest I now just want to get the contract
signed and get down to business in Newcastle.
``It's a huge challenge but it's one that I'm looking forward to. I expect to
hear from Rob Andrew within the next few days and then we can get the signing
over and take it from there,'' he said.
q PROTRACTED negotiations aimed at placing the Scotland international squad
under contract to the SRU are nearing completion and pen will be put to paper
any day now.
The Herald understands that the players stand to earn about #3000 a game this
season, making some #15,000 in total, plus a #5000 retainer and bonuses
depending on where the side finishes in the Five Nations tournament. The
concept of win-bonuses for individual games has, apparently, been kicked into
touch.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951220-000100</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951220-000100</DOCID>
<DATE>951220</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Federal Reserve cuts rates</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By CHRIS STONE City Editor</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974799040</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AMERICAN short-term interest rates have been reduced by a quarter-of-a-point,
for the second time this year, by the US Federal Reserve. It is a move which
should cheer Wall Street which had suffered a 101.5-point fall in the Dow Index
on Monday, its biggest one-day decline in eight years.
Against the background of the continuing impasse over the Federal budget, which
meant that the release of yesterday's expected batch of US economic data has
been delayed, hopes had been fading that the authorities would cut rates
although earlier expectations and market sentiment had been for a small
reduction.
It should also be good news for UK shares which normally take their lead from
Wall Street which had shown some recovery early on yesterday. However, the
problem of the federal budget could continue to act as a dampener. The FTSE-100
Index closed down 19.2 points at 3576.9 but at one stage it had been down over
37 points following Monday's 46.5-point fall, recovering some ground after Wall
Street's steady opening.
The cut in US rates lowered the federal funds rate that commercial banks charge
each for overnight loans by a quarter-percentage point to 5.5%. The Fed left
the discount rate that it charges banks for money unchanged at 5.25%.
``Since the last easing of monetary policy in July, inflation has been somewhat
more favourable than anticipated,'' central bank chairman Alan Greenspan said
in a statement.
``This result, along with an associated moderation in inflation expectations,
warrants a modest easing in monetary conditions,'' he added.
The cut, by the central bank's policy-making Federal Open Market Committee,
followed a string of statistics showing the economy softening after a
surprisingly strong rise in the third quarter.
Some analysts had questioned whether the central bank would cut rates while the
Republican-led Congress and the Clinton administration were still battling over
the budget.
But Fed officials had argued interest rate policy should not be held hostage to
political manoeuvring over the budget and should be free to respond to changes
in the economy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951220-000101</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951220-000101</DOCID>
<DATE>951220</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Glaxo sells stake</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ANDREW WILSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974799041</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
GLAXO Wellcome is selling its half-interest in the Warner Wellcome joint
venture for $1050m (#683m) in line with its strategy of concentrating on
prescription-only drugs, writes ANDREW WILSON.
The venture was agreed in July 1993 to develop and market consumer products
globally which included Warner Lambert, Wellcome - then independent of Glaxo -
and some of the Glaxo over-the-counter medicines, including the Zantac
heartburn product group.
Glaxo Wellcome will continue to supply ``switch products'' or medicines which
are being transferred from prescription to over-the-counter status.
These include Zantac 75, Beconase for hay fever, and Zovirax cold-sore cream.
It is selling the original Wellcome ``sniffs and sneezes'' products such as
Actifed and Sudafed and Calpol.
In the half-year to June, Glaxo Wellcome's share of profits in the joint
venture amounted to #38m including Wellcome's share prior to the #9000m hostile
takeover.
The prospect of finding a large sum to cut its #3500m debt helped reduce an
earlier 27p fall in the share price to just 7p at 878p by the close.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951220-000102</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951220-000102</DOCID>
<DATE>951220</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Two top Scottish business leaders plan to take their expertise on to pastures new Gold moves to Scottish Chambers</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT POWELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974799042</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LEX Gold, the former civil servant who helped give the Confederation of British
Industry (CBI) a stronger profile in Scotland, now plans to do the same for
Scottish Chambers of Commerce.
Mr Gold finished a two-year stint as director of CBI Scotland last month. He
will take up a part-time appointment as director general of Scottish Chambers
on January 3.
``For some time now they have been looking to establish a presence at a
national level . . . it is a big job and I am looking forward to doing it,'' he
said.
Mr Gold said Scottish Chambers, which claims to be the country's biggest
business organisation, should make its voice better heard in policy areas such
as transport, tourism, European affairs, education and training.
But he added that it should remain politically neutral on the thorny issue of
devolution, asking only what the economic consequences of a parliament in
Edinburgh would be.
Mr Gold said Scottish Chambers' 8000 members had a wide range of views on the
constitutional aspects of devolution, but they were united on one thing: ``They
want to see their businesses develop and grow and their primary interest is in
getting the right conditions.''
They were asking themselves: ``What does it mean in terms of the business
community? Is it going to raise costs or is it going to provide
opportunities?'' he said.
``I think there are plans to take that debate on the business issues in
devolution around the regions in Scotland as part of the Chambers' activities.''
Mr Gold said he would start his new job by undertaking a round of consultations
with the organisation's grass roots.
``The first thing I intend to do is to go around and listen to what the
chambers say. I don't come with a package of measures which I intend to impose
upon them,'' he said.
Mr Gold stressed he had not deliberately left CBI Scotland to work for a rival
business organisation.
He said he had only agreed to take on the CBI job for two years after a 33-year
career in the civil service. When he left he had no idea he would be approached
for the Scottish Chambers' post.
This became vacant in July when Charles Winter, the previous director general,
stepped down due to heart trouble. Mr Winter, who had been chief executive of
Royal Bank of Scotland, began the task of giving Scottish Chambers a higher
profile.
Peter Dunn, a Scottish Chambers director from Fife who is a noted enthusiast of
home rule, stepped into the breach temporarily after Mr Winter's departure.
Mr Dunn's interpretation of a recent Scottish Chambers survey of members'
attitudes to devolution ruffled feathers among some firms opposed to any change
in direct rule from Westminster.
The CBI, which has 1500 1member companies in Scotland, welcomed Mr Gold's new
appointment. ``Naturally we are wishing Lex well in his new job,'' said Paul
Walker, the spokesman of CBI Scotland.
Mr Gold said he hoped to continue working closely with the CBI, as well as
other organisations such as Scottish Financial Enterprise and Scottish Council
Development and Industry, to achieve a common stance on key business issues.
He will receive #20,000 a year for spending three days a week at Scottish
Chambers, less than the #30,000 he earned working full-time at CBI Scotland,
but then again, he is not doing it for the money.
``It is the nature of the challenge that attracts me,'' said Mr Gold, who
played football for Rangers and worked briefly as a journalist before starting
his career in the civil service.
He will divide his remaining time between voluntary organisations such as the
Scottish Training Advisory Group (STAG) for disabled people and Apex Scotland,
an organisation that helps ex-offenders.
``I have also had two or three approaches which I am currently considering for
gainful employments. Just watch this space,'' he added.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951220-000103</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951220-000103</DOCID>
<DATE>951220</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Hot Ice, Edinburgh Festival Theatre</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Mark Fisher</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974799043</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE advantage dancing on skates has over a regular sprung floor lies in the
great circular sweeps of the stage, the gyroscopic spirals and the ability to
glide backwards at much speed with effortless grace. The disadvantages are much
the same.
Once you've seen the characters from Alice in Wonderland sweep, spiral, and
glide, there's not much to be said about a troupe of jazz hoofers sweeping,
spiralling and gliding, or an army of Charlie Chaplins, or a gang of futuristic
robots. Hot Ice, choreographed by Phil Winston and directed by Amanda Thompson,
has more to do with rapid and multiple costume changes than it does
attention-grabbing dance.
The numbers that work best tend to involve just one or two skaters who are
allowed time and space to show off their technical skills and impressive
acrobatic ability. These are usually set to the more primal musical pieces
where rhythm is everything, although there's also a nice duet to When I Fall in
Love. More typically, the performance is as humourless as the self-important
soft rock songs that top and tail the show, all broad gestures, bland grins and
po-faced scowls.
Ofpants, the official panto watchdog, was laid up in bed (it's a testing time
of year), which is just as well, given the lack of effort to engage the
under-10s, notwithstanding Alice and an unsophisticated football spoof (Michael
Clark eat your heart out).
Far more diverting are the stunning laser effects (``Lovely to look at,'' says
the theatre's programme and you can't fault it for honesty), but even the
bizarrely diverse range of influences from Gershwin to the formation of the
universe, can't disguise the production's lack of soul.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951220-000104</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951220-000104</DOCID>
<DATE>951220</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Howden group wins record orders</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT POWELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974799044</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
HOWDEN Group is managing to hold its head comfortably above water during a
difficult time for the engineering industry.
Its order book for specialist equipment, ranging from fans and compressors to
pasta-making machines and drilling rigs, rose 26% to a record #243m during the
six months to October 31.
The Renfrew-based group enjoyed particularly strong business in the Far East
and also traded well in Europe and South Africa.
But profit growth was restrained by high manufacturing costs in the US and
Canada and a poor performance in Germany.
The strong mark and low demand for tunnelling equipment from the depressed
construction industry meant its German subsidiary, Wirth, barely broke even,
but this had been expected.
Group operating profits increased 10% to #13.5m as turnover rose 9% to #211.6m
and profit margins were maintained at 6.3%.
But profits before tax grew only 4% to #11m, held back by higher interest
charges as gearing crept up to 47% from 37% at the start of the period.
``It is a pretty good performance in what we know are difficult markets for
engineering companies generally,'' said analyst Richard Andrews at Edinburgh
stockbroker Bell Lawrie White.
But the overall result was ``just a little more depressed than had been
hoped''. Although Howden shares firmed 1p to 68p, Mr Andrews is cutting his
full-year profit forecast to #33.5m from #35.0m.
Howden's corporate services director, Alan Maclachlan, said the explosion of
new orders included a spate of small contracts worth less than #5m in the Far
East.
Howden said its recently established fan businesses in Malaysia and Singapore
had ``performed beyond expectations'' and the construction of its fan and heat
exchanger factory in China was proceeding smoothly. The Chinese factory should
open next summer with ``a reasonable order book''.
Gearing should sink back towards 40% by the end of the financial year, but no
major acquisitions are planned following a spate of purchases around the globe
over the last three years.
Only 20% of Howden's turnover is now generated in the UK. About 30% comes from
North America and 17% from Continental Europe. The remaining 33% comes from
emerging markets in the Far East, Africa and Latin America.
The widespread nature of Howden's business makes the firm confident about its
prospects.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951220-000105</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951220-000105</DOCID>
<DATE>951220</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Melrose hands almost on cup</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>24</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>photograph </GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974799045</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Admiring glances: Melrose captain Bryan Redpath can look but he cannot touch.
The SRU Tennents championship trophy which the Borderers won at the weekend
will be presented at a specially arranged Greenyards ceremony on December 30
when Melrose play Jed-Forest in a regional league game. The Greenyards club had
wanted the trophy to be handed over at a home game when they had a full squad
in operation and December 30 was the first date which fitted the bill.
</TEXT>
