<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951220-000106</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951220-000106</DOCID>
<DATE>951220</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Co-operative says it offers good price and long-term security Scottish Milk upbeat</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROBERT ROSS Farming Editor</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974799046</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTTISH Milk, the farmers' co-operative which succeeded the old Milk Marketing
Board, said yesterday it was heartened by the support it had received during a
series of ``meet the members'' presentations. By the end of this week the
management team will have addressed 15 meetings from Kelso to Kintyre.
Deregulation of the dairy industry has concentrated the minds of producers on
whether their interests are best served by staying with the co-operative or
transferring to one of the increasing band of purchasers seeking direct
supplies.
The Scottish Milk meetings have been attended by 1000 of the 18000 active
members in the co-op.
John Duncan, Scottish Milk chairman, said there was support for the broad
policies being pursued by the company - to maximise efficiency, implement cost
savings wherever possible and offer members enthusiastic leadership.
``We believe farmers have gone home from the meetings feeling confident that
their co-op can deliver the kind of returns they are looking for as milk
producers.''
On the key issue of price comparisons, he advised members to check any offers
from alternative outlets with their area manager. Past experience had shown
that prices quoted by competitors needed to be properly interpreted by each
individual producer, he warned.
At the meetings managing director Jack Pirie pointed out that in the first 12
months of trading Scottish Milk paid members on average 1.5p a litre more than
the old SMMB did. ``In any other commercial sphere that kind of progress would
have made headlines,'' he said.
Milk Marque in England had established the standard litre which had 4.1%
butterfat and 3.35% protein, and for that quality it paid 24.75p a litre, he
added. All comparison stemmed from that figure but not all milk conformed to
the standard litre. Scottish Milk expected to pay about 25.5p a litre for 4.1%
butterfat and 3.3% protein.
``With this to build on, together with our high standards of service to both
customers and members, we are optimistic about our ability to compete in the
market place.''
The most important figure for members' milk prices was income net of costs, he
said. Scottish Milk had been working, with some measure of success, to reduce
costs and was in the middle of discussions with its haulage contractors about
major changes aimed at achieving further significant savings.
A number of industry commentators have, in recent weeks, been emphasising the
importance of a strong co-operative remaining in the dairy sector. That theme
was taken up by John Duncan at the producers' meetings he addressed.
The vast majority of producers wanted to be part of a body owned by them and
managed for their benefit, he said. ``They want an organisation that will seek
to maximise returns to members in the long term, offer them collective strength
in the market place, and secure a wide spread of customers in order to spread
the risk.
``The concept of producers working together with collective strength is right -
but some make the mistake of thinking about Scottish Milk as an alterative
buyer of their milk. Such an attitude is all about the short term. Instead,
producers must think about their security in the long term. Only a strong
Scottish Milk can provide that.''
</TEXT>
