<HEADLINE>Move on salmon price welcomed</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROBERT ROSS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974799047</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Scottish Salmon Growers' Association has welcomed the introduction by the
European Union of a minimum import price for Norwegian salmon.
Phillip Thorn, chairman of the association, said it was the first stage in
addressing the problem of massive over-production in Norway.
Further measures were being discussed with the European Commission, said Mr
Thorn. ``I am disappointed that they have only implemented the minimum price
for whole fish, and have omitted fillets,'' he added.
``However, I am sure the EU processing industry will also be most concerned and
we will be pressing for their inclusion.''
The SSGA would be working for the introduction of more effective medium and
longer-term measures including volume controls on Norwegian exports to the EU,
he said.
Meanwhile, Moray Seafoods, already one of the largest shellfish producers in
Britain, is about to invest #350,000 to increase production and raise
processing standards.
The company, which has 250 employees at its plant in Buckie, has recorded 15%
increases in turnover for the last two financial years and is on target for a
30% rise in sales this year.
Grant Eckersley, Moray Seafoods' managing director, said: ``We have decided to
rebuild our coldwater prawn processing unit again from scratch and provide the
most modern environment with full separation for high care product processing
and packaging operations.''
The company is also installing new machinery which will halve energy costs
while cooking prawns more gently and evenly.
</TEXT>
