<HEADLINE>Enter the score keepers</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Michael Tumelty</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Profile</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974799048</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Michael Tumelty profiles a noteworthy group who ensure our music is well
accounted for
IT IS largely unseen, unheard, and unheralded. The general public is probably
not aware of its existence. Many in the music business will only be dimly aware
of its function or location. But the Scottish Music Information Centre (SMIC)
is a vital component in the engine room of musical Scotland, providing the fuel
for the smooth running of much of the musical life in the country. Literally.
If you attend a concert by the Paragon or Hebrides Ensembles, the Chamber Group
of Scotland, or any of the orchestras which happen to be performing a work by a
Scottish composer, new or old, the probability is the music - score and parts -
being performed was prepared and issued by the Scottish Music Information
Centre.
If you read a book, or an article in a newspaper or specialist magazine which
touches on Scottish music; if you attend a lecture, see a slide show, or hear a
radio talk on the subject; part at least of the information therein is likely
to have originated in, or have been verified by, SMIC.
``We're not a performing or promoting body, not a library, not a museum,'' says
Kirsteen McCue, general manager of the centre. ``We're all of these, and that's
our real strength. We feel that we're a unique organisation in Scotland.''
Unique it certainly is. Tucked away on the top floor of a west end building in
Glasgow owned by the Scottish Council for Educational Technology, the Scottish
Music Information Centre is a vast storage house - a treasure trove - of
Scottish music.
It has a manuscript collection which is priceless, containing around 9000
scores of works by over 300 Scottish composers, dating back to the sixteenth
century and earlier, and a reference facility which can provide you with every
scrap of biographical or professional information you might require about any
aspect of Scottish musical life.
It holds a unique collection of around 4000 recordings of Scottish music, many
archival, many from broadcasts given by the BBC, and many privately-made,
non-broadcast recordings which are the sole record of works that received only
one performance.
Now, in a continuing extension of its more public face - SMIC has been
associated with a number of projects over the years, from a festival of
Icelandic music to the large-scale Scotland's Music exhibition - the
information centre is undertaking its first commercial venture with the
publication of the Scottish Music Handbook.
An invaluable reference tool for anyone involved in any aspect of the business,
from education to performance,  the handbook, launched recently by
percussionist Evelyn Glennie, should instantly find a place in every public
library and school, college or university music department in the country. (See
Handbook review on this page.)
The production of the book would have been inconceivable only a few years ago,
and is a reflection of the recent dramatic change in status and function of the
information centre.
Founded in the sixties as the Scottish Music Archive by Professor Fred Rimmer
of Glasgow University's music department, the centre was originally sited on
university premises and had a specific function: to build up a national
resource of musical materials.
``Most of our composers don't have a publisher,'' says McCue, touching on one
of the most controversial issues in Scottish musical affairs. ``Therefore their
music is not copyright, and is not automatically kept in one of the main
deposit libraries in Britain.''
HE adds: ``If it wasn't for the fact that Fred Rimmer set up the archive to
pull all of that material together, it would be lost, scattered, with
composers, in people's houses...... not accessible.''
In the mid-eighties, the function of the archive was broadened. It became an
information centre, part of an international network, and its scope was
extended to include dissemination as well as storage - its monthly newsheet,
Music Current, is an invaluable guide to contemporary music event in Scotland
and abroad.
The Scottish Arts Council, stipulating the development of the information side
of the business, came in as the main funder and, in 1992, trebled its grant to
the organisation to #61,500, which covers the rent of the building and the
salaries of the staff, now increased to three full-time and one part-time.
``The SAC grant is our oxygen,'' says McCue.
Additional finance to cover the running costs of the operation is provided by
facilities and services offered by SMIC, by trusts and foundations, and by
Glasgow city council.
Production of the Scottish Music Handbook - which has taken just over a year -
was met by rapid development of SMIC's in-house computerised database, with
special finance and extra staff. While the need for a handbook was first
pinpointed and suggested some years ago by Matthew Rooke, music director of the
SAC, the volume of inquiries received by SMIC - over 1600 last year - itself
dictated such a development.
Next priority for Kirsteen McCue is space. ``We have centuries of stuff here in
boxes, and we are absolutely squeezed for space. And we also need
environmentally controlled space; the manuscript collection includes autograph
material which needs to be stored in acid-free boxes, and in conditions which
are not too dry, not too damp.
``It's needed not just to make it accessible, but for future generations.
Before the eighteenth century, all this material was never gathered in one
place. Now it's vitally important to grasp the opportunity to preserve it.''
</TEXT>
