<HEADLINE>Top boxer turns to basketball</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>24</PAGE>
<FLAG>sports digest</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974799050</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BRITISH basketball officials say it's no hoax - IBF super-middleweight champion
Roy Jones, Jr, is set to quit boxing and pursue a basketball career in England
with Budweiser League outfit London Towers.
League and club officials said yesterday that Jones plans to retire after his
title defence against Merqui Sosa on January 12 and move to England for a trial
with the Towers.
``It's extremely serious,'' said Basketball League spokesman Rob Webb. ``This
is real. We've been in regular contact with his agent.''
There was speculation that Jones' move could be related to his efforts to line
up a lucrative unification bout against Britain's WBC super-middleweight
champion Nigel Benn - but the London club believe instead that the boxer is
using them as a stepping stone towards a basketball career at a higher level.
Snooker
A PROPOSAL to pay board members of the World Professional Billiards and Snooker
Association failed to gain the necessary two-thirds majority at the annual
meeting of the game's governing body in Bristol yesterday.
Ian Doyle, manager of world champion Stephen Hendry and carrying proxy votes
for nine other players, argued the WPBSA should concentrate on putting a more
extended executive structure in place - complete with chief executive - rather
than attempt to run board business on a day-to-day basis.
Squash
MARTIN Heath's success in the recent Scottish championship could mark the end
of his self-imposed exile from the Scottish team.
Disagreement arose at last season's European championships, and the 22-year-old
from Oban refused to play at the world event in Egypt last month, but the world
No.30 could return for the European championships in May.
``Hopefully the situation will soon be sorted out,'' he said. ``It would be
good to get back in the team because Scotland should be a match for anyone if
they are at full strength.''
With world No.8 Peter Nicol also missing from the world championship side,
Scotland finished just fifteenth.
Swimming
DUNFERMLINE High School pupil Bryan Morgan, who set two new British junior
records for backstroke at the weekend, will travel with the Scottish youth
squad to Denmark in January. Morgan, 15, of Dunfermline Carnegie ASC, knocked
0.38sec off the 50m backstroke record with a time of 27.32sec and beat the old
100m backstroke record of 58.11 with 57.94.
He will now compete in backstroke events at the multi-nation tournament in
Copenhagen next month.
Curling
THE Stakis Masters tournament was launched yesterday with an announcement of
its biggest prize fund yet and news of its highest ever level of participation
by foreign teams, including for the first time, an entry from Canada.
The Perth event, which will take place over the first weekend of January, is
now in its third year and already, with almost #8000 available for the top
teams, it is recognised as the premier event in Scotland.
The competition has been given extra spice by the British Curling Association's
decision that taking part is mandatory for any team with hopes of representing
Britain at the 1998 Winter Olympics.
Tennis
ALAN Mackin's challenge in the Orange Bowl world 14-and-under championships in
Florida ended in yesterday's second round. The 14-year-old from Paisley who won
through the qualifying competition to earn his place in the 128-player draw,
defeated Canadian John Rodger 6-4, 6-3 before bowing out 6-1, 6-2 to Marius
Gormans of Slovakia.
Michele Mair has returned from the Challenger circuit in Australia to contest
this week's British Women's Tennis Association Christmas tournament at Queen's
Club. The Scottish No.1 opened with a 6-1, 6-0 win over Suffolk junior Susan
Durham yesterday.
JEFF Tarango yesterday apologised to umpire Bruno Rebeuh, and to tennis in
general, for his infamous outburst at Wimbledon that led to a fine of almost
#30,000 and a ban from next year's tournament. The American stormed off court,
refusing to play on, in protest at the umpires' decisions during a singles
match against Alexander Mronz.
On appeal to the Grand Slam committee, Tarango's fine was reduced to #18,000,
which equals the prize money he would have otherwise received. He will still
not be allowed to play in next year's Wimbledon but the additional
one-tournament suspension was suspended for three years. The American's
six-month battle with the sport's establishment now seems to be over.
Boxing
SHINJI Takehara, of Japan, won the WBA middleweight title in Tokyo last night
when he outpointed defending champion Jorge Castro, of Argentina.
Sports awards
BRITISH intermediate heptathlon champion Jacky Tindal (Fife AC) is promoted
alongside British international Mel Neef in the latest list of awards from the
Scottish Sports Aid Foundation. The 17-year-old Buckhaven High School pupil
receives a #1000 Robertson Trust bursary, as does the 25-year-old City of
Glasgow star.
Walker Cup golfer Gordon Sherry (Kilmarnock) has also had a #1000 cash boost
from the Bank of Scotland's `Elite' Awards scheme, as has swimmer Graeme Smith
(Dunfermline). Awards:
Robertson Trust: Archery - C Trenaman (Helensburgh). Athletics - J Tindal
(Buckhaven), M Neef (Mid Calder). Cycling - C Maclean (Grantown-on-Spey), E Guy
(Edinburgh). Golf - R Beames (Irvine). Rowing - L Potter (Edinburgh). Shooting
- N Davies (Penicuik). Skiing - R Green (Falkirk). Bank of Scotland Award: Golf
- G Sherry (Kilmarnock), G Smith (Dunfermline). Kelso Racecourse Award:
Athletics: M Combe (Jedburgh).
American football
SAN Francisco 49ers blew a 21-point lead but rallied in time to defeat
Minnesota Vikings 37-30, setting themselves up to play all of their NFL
post-season matches at Candlestick Park. The 49ers must now win their final
game next weekend to secure the home-field advantage.
Receiver Jerry Rice caught 14 passes for a team-record 289 yards and three
touchdowns as the 49ers secured a first-round bye in the play-offs.
San Francisco's win also propelled the NFC Central Detroit Lions into the
play-offs, much to the relief of their head coach Wayne Fontes, who had been
threatened with the sack if his team had failed.
Athletics
KILBARCHAN Xmas Four-Mile Road Race - 1, G Fairley 21min 27sec; 2, J Snodgrass
22-43; 3, M McGinley 23-52. Veteran - D Mewse 24-05. Super Veteran: J McMillan
24-20. Junior: P Dailly 24-39. Women: 1, H Townsend 28-10; 2, Geddes 29-02; 3,
M Menzies 29-26. Veteran: E McMillan 31-15. Handicap winner: J McMillan.
Greyhound results
SHAWFIELD results: First race - Wish A Pick (4) 3-1; Zinovia (5) 6-4 #7.46.
Second - Silver Treasure (3) 5-2 jt fav; Labour Victory (1) 4-1 #12.32. Third -
Void. Fourth - Loyal Boy (1) 3-1; Aubane Arrow (2) 3-1 #11.78. Fifth -
Peterswells Greg (5) 3-1 tpl jt fav; Ballybrack Tina (1) 3-1 #11.78. Sixth -
Tartan Lassie (3) 9-4 fav; Nicolas Nap (5) 4-1 #11.07. Seventh - Husky Lady (4)
9-4 fav; Crow Pony (2) 5-2 #7.82. Eighth - Alans Hope (3) 5-1; Blair Adam (1)
5-2; #17.01. Ninth - Brigside Moate (4) 4-1; Black Silk (2) 6-4; #9.83.
