<HEADLINE>Sella calls it a day</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>24</PAGE>
<FLAG>sports digest</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974799051</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
RUGBY
PHILIPPE Sella, who holds a world record of 111 caps in a top-level career
spanning more than 15 years, has announced his retirement from the
international scene.
The 33-year-old Frenchman earned his last cap on June 22 in Pretoria when
France defeated England in the World Cup third-place play-off. ``It's time for
me to concentrate on life outside rugby,'' said Sella, who runs a clothing
business. He scored 36 tries for France and was also one of the toughest
defenders in the team.
Sella enjoyed the best moments of his career in the 1987 World Cup where France
lost to New Zealand in the final after an fine win over Australia in the semis.
He has said that he intends to develop his company in England and might join an
English club next season, although he denied reports linking him with
Harlequins, Leicester, and Saracens.
ner: J McMillan.
