<DATE>951220</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Vote of no confidence already under discussion SRU must act to quell a rebellion in the clubs</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Brian Meek</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>24</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974799052</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THERE is definitely a whiff of rebellion in the air. You can smell it in
committee rooms up and down the land, club men with hundreds of years of unpaid
service behind them, railing and ranting at the organisation which is running,
or ruining as some would have it, the game they love. Frankly, at the moment,
in the nostrils of their own members, the SRU stinks.
It is not one issue, not just the argument about who should represent Scotland
in Europe next season, though that is an important cause celebre. Nor is it
just club officials who are upset.
The whole of the North and Midlands districts are up in arms having been forced
to play their championship match against the Scottish Exiles on Sunday, a quite
ludicrous decision given the weakness of the home side. My understanding is
that the majority of the SRU committee, the 18 men who make up the sport's most
powerful elite, were originally in favour of granting a postponement.
That did not suit some people so a telephone poll took place in which committee
members were urged to change their mind. This is no way to run a whelk stall,
never mind a multi-million pound organisation.
Nor are the top players resigned to continuing to reside and play in Scotland.
Money talks. If they are offered large sums to go South most of them will take
it. To predict that the Scotland team of two years hence will be made up
entirely of exiles is by no means fanciful.
It is therefore quite astonishing to hear leading SRU figures describe the
actions of such as Sir John Hall, the millionaire backer of Newcastle, as
``going on an ego trip''. They had better pray that there are Scottish
businessmen who are willing to sign up for the same cruise.
There has been much talk about the clubs calling an extraordinary general
meeting to challenge the decision that Districts - still to be formed or even
named - will be our European representatives. That may indeed happen.
But I am beginning to believe, from conversations that I have had with senior
club officials, that the special meeting may well be called to propose a vote
of no confidence in the committee itself.
``We are not just concerned about the European competition,'' a Stirling County
office-bearer told me on Saturday. ``There is a lot more we want to know.
``The growing number of staff at Murrayfield is another worry, the financial
position of the union - which appears to have deteriorated rapidly - is
something else we want to ask about, plus the whole question of league
reconstruction.
``This is a big club with big ideas and we are not content to be fed a diet of
scraps from the Murrayfield table.''
You could hear these comments echoed at Meggetland and Melrose.
A motion of no confidence is a rare but not unique occurrence in rugby. The
entire Welsh Rugby Union hierarchy was swept away just a few years ago.
I would not like to see that happen in Scotland because there are a lot of
decent, hard-working people on the SRU committee who have given sterling
service to the game. Dr Ian Todd, the current president, is one of life's
gentlemen. It is not his fault that the sport has been thrown into turmoil by
what seems increasingly, to me, a cowardly decision of the International Board
simply to declare the game open.
Charlie Ritchie is a grand chap to have at your side in a crisis and he will be
needed.
Because I believe the SRU must act to save itself and to stop the game from
descending into a civil war, the union should call an extraordinary general
meeting. They should not wait to be pushed into a corner.
The visionaries on the committee, the likes of Duncan Paterson and Allan Hosie
who have been arguing for a change in procedure for some years, should be used
to spell out how the union sees the future. Let Jim Telfer explain his thinking
face to face with club members.
What should clubs be doing about contracts? And could the director of rugby, or
anybody else, tell us how the Exiles are to be fitted into the new set-up.
Iain Laughland, the finance convener, should speak openly about the deficit and
about the remedies he intends to apply. Chief executive Bill Hogg might be
given his say, too; no-one has worked longer or harder in the union's interest.
Let's put all the cards on the table. The days of the old committee issuing
edicts on tablets of stone have gone; ``but the clubs are the SRU'' was always
the cry though hardly the reality. Now that might be an accurate assessment.
Kenny Milne, the retiring Heriot's and Scotland hooker, made a sensible
suggestion to me on Saturday. ``If it is to be Districts in Europe, then why
not pay the clubs for the release of every single player.
``That way, the more successful sides will at least receive some monetary
reward for their efforts.'' The union might do well to listen more to the wiser
players.
All is by no means black in Scottish rugby. We have just concluded one of the
most exciting first division championships. There are bigger crowds at club
matches than ever before; the public want to get behind the international side.
What is needed now is men of vision and courage to come forward and to speak
their mind. The alternative is just a mess.
A motion of no confidence is a rare but not unique occurrence in rugby. The
entire Welsh Rugby Union hierarchy was swept away just a few years ago
