<DATE>951220</DATE>
<HEADLINE>The Stone Roses, Barrowland, Glasgow</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>David Belcher</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974799053</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WHO was the geezer last night roaring one of the Roses' more plangent
masterpieces of adolescent yearning, Waterfall, while wearing an orange acrylic
Jimmy-wig - so-called because the tam-o'-shanter which comes handily
pre-attached to it is intended to invoke Russ Abbot's archetypal drunken Scot,
Mr C U Jimmy? Who? Who?
A clue. Last night he sang in a costermonger's hectoring tones, having forsaken
the fey uncertainty of his original vocal style. Correct. It's Ian Brown, the
latest graduate from the Shaun Ryder Memorial School of Flat Mancunian
Atonality.
Granted, Ian only wore the Jimmy-wig briefly, someone in the stage-front throng
having gifted it to him. The wayward singing lasted throughout, although oddly
not during acoustic versions of Your Star Will Shine and Tightrope.
Why the change? Why does Ian Brown gaze out above the crowd's heads with a
simian look that's either sublimely sure or supremely indifferent? The Stone
Roses: we've waited for them since the summer of 1990, and were they as good
last night as they used to be? Were they any good at all? If they leave it for
another five-and-a-half years, will everyone have bogged off home? I honestly
don't know.
I do know that these days the Stone Roses are just a question of music, rather
than cultural definition and belief, so I can say wow, that John Squire! From
his guitar he extrudes deft metallic runs; aquaeous swathes; muscular chimes;
delicate shimmers, and funky, chunky bits.
``You soon got tired,'' Ian Brown observed as the crowd's dancing flagged at
one point. It began again, but as to why . . .
</TEXT>
