<DATE>951220</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Tall Tales For Cold, Dark Nights, Tron Theatre, Glasgow</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Keith Bruce</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974799054</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
COMMUNICADO Theatre Company has provided the Tron - and thereafter Edinburgh's
Traverse - with a perfect Christmas show. Only it is not a Christmas show.
Sure, seasonal references have been inserted into this inspired piece of
story-telling, presented with the sort of easy theatricality that is Gerry
Mulgrew's company at its best. But basically it is the same show that premiered
at the Scottish International Children's Festival in Edinburgh in the early
summer.
It worked well then, and it works equally well now. The difference is in the
receptiveness - and size - of the audience. This is a show that is simply an
entertaining piece of theatre, but it seems that shows that work on such a
direct level are either for Christmas or for kids. Something wrong in the
equation there, perhaps.
Still, let's spot the panto elements. The occasional burst of music, chiefly
rendered by Jane MacFarlane (fiddle and cello), and Mulgrew himself. The puppet
sequences - one scene hypnotically rendered on a set the size of a dinner
plate, and a totally superfluous dance sequence (cf panto) with a mannequin
demonstrating Irish dancing, for example. Transformation scenes and quick
changes, they're all here.
What about the themes in these three Scots tales (from the collections of
Duncan Williamson)? Fairy tales as good as Grimm or Hans Christian Andersen.
Come to that, The Taen-Awa, which forms the whole of the second half, is a nice
pagan obverse of the Nativity.
The six-strong company - Donna Bainbridge, Peter Grimes, Conleth Hill, Anne
Lacey, MacFarlane, and Mulgrew - is excellent, conjuring up characters with
nothing and everything. They are a true ensemble - and no-one's making any fuss
about it.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
