<DOCID>GH951220-000115</DOCID>
<DATE>951220</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Trust gets grazing study grant</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974799055</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE National Trust for Scotland has been awarded a #116,000 grant by the
European Union as part of a #230,000 project to study grazing in the Scottish
Highlands.
Overgrazing by sheep and deer has long been blamed by conservationists for
causing widespread damage to the Scottish uplands.
The two-year study will be undertaken by the National Trust in collaboration
with the Scottish Wildlife Trust and Scottish Natural Heritage together with
the Insititute of Terrestrial Ecology in Banchory and the Macaulay Land
Research Institute in Aberdeen.
To work out what grazing level is needed to conserve the Scottish uplands the
project team will look at four sites in detail - Ben Lawers, Glencoe, Torridon
and the Lendalfoot Hills.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951220-000116</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951220-000116</DOCID>
<DATE>951220</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Burns' target is a defender</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Ian Paul</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>26</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974799056</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
By IAN PAUL
CELTIC are on the verge of bringing another Dutch player to Parkhead to join
Pierre van Hooydonk, the striker who joined them last January for #1.2m. Van
Hooydonk is with Burns in his home town, Breda, where the pair are expected to
watch Roda's international defender, Johan de Kock, who has been the subject of
recent Parkhead scrutiny, in action this afternoon against the striker's former
side.
De Kock was the man who was called on to Anfield last week to replace Denis
Bergkamp when the Dutch manager, Guus Hiddink, decided that the national side
needed more aerial strength to cope with Tony Cascarino and John Aldridge in
the second half of their European Championship play-off with the Republic of
Ireland. Celtic had him watched that night.
Burns has been in Holland for a couple of days and, although other suggested
targets have been Denis de Nooyer of Sparta Rotterdam and Luc Nilis of PSV
Eindhoven, my understanding is that the man they are after is De Kock who,
although 31, has impressed Hiddink since he took over as national coach and is
now a certainty to be included in the squad for the European Championship
finals.
The fact that the Belgian, Nilis, is highly paid and very content with
Eindhoven, to where he can commute comfortably from home across the Border,
would seem to rule him out and, as Sparta Rotterdam, the club for whom de
Nooyer plays, have no game today, it is odds-on that Burns will be taking in
the match involving Hooydonk's former team.
For a man with five caps De Kock, astonishingly, is a part-timer who combines
his football with his day job as a civil engineer, but the word is that he
would be enthusiastic about a move to Celtic. In fact, the move had seemed a
possibility at the start of the season when van Hooydonk recommended the tall,
powerful defender. Nothing came of that early interest but there seems no doubt
that Roda would be willing to trade with Celtic, as their star turn's contract
runs out at the end of the season when, in the new Bosman era, he would be free
to move without any fee being involved.
Roda price him at 4m gilders which is about #1.6m, a fee Celtic would
accommodate if the player fits their requirements.
Although the club is relatively well off in his department, Burns has said
consistently that he is in the market for quality players when they are
available and is also committed to drumming up competition throughout the side.
The success of van Hooydonk, who is the leading scorer in the country, and the
all-round professionalism of Dutch players as a whole have impressed Burns and
chief scout David Hay, both of whom are fans of the Ajax youth system which the
management at Parkhead is trying to imitate in the long term.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951220-000117</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951220-000117</DOCID>
<DATE>951220</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Boards act on Cadbury</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Chris Stone</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974799057</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MOST companies have reviewed the structure and operation of their boards
because of the Cadbury Code, according to a new survey, writes CHRIS STONE.
The CBI/Touche Ross study of corporate governance shows that 81% of companies
have taken action on the     issue.
The findings also show that 89% of companies want the Cadbury Code to remain
confined to principles, and 85% believe compliance with it has been
straightforward. A total of 71% believe their institutional shareholders are
concerned to ensure they comply with the code.
The survey was sent to the chairman or chief executive of 347 companies in the
last quarter and received a 45% response.
Among the other findings, 90% of respondents believe Cadbury has had no
positive effect on their financial performance; 61% feel compliance has not
added significantly to audit costs and the workload of senior executives, and
54% feel only larger listed companies should be required to comply with all of
it.
Some 67% think it should be modified for smaller listed companies and almost
75% said companies should simply be required to disclose the extent of their
compliance, although more than a quarter of firms believe compliance should be
required with each section of the code.
Commenting on the results, CBI president Sir Bryan Nicholson said: ``The CBI
was a sponsor of the original       Cadbury Committee and is a sponsor of the
newly-created successor body, to be chaired by Sir Ronald Hampel.
``High standards of corporate governance promote confidence in the investing
community and the public at large in the companies that practise them.
``A clear set of guiding principles for boards and directors, and disclosure of
how businesses are following them, are sensible ways of encouraging these
aims.''
However, the survey found though, 85% of respondents felt that the new
committee should not attempt any major change in the Cadbury Code until
companies have had more experience of the existing requirements.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951220-000118</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951220-000118</DOCID>
<DATE>951220</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Coal suspended</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Christopher Sims</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974799058</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SHARES of Coal Investments, which is the largest investor in Mining (Scotland),
operator of Longannet mine and nine open-cast sites, were suspended yesterday
pending clarification of its financial position, writes CHRISTOPHER SIMS.
Mining (Scotland), which employs some 900 people at Longannet, stressed the
news did not directly affect it.
David Brewer, its finance and operations director, said: ``We note this
situation with interest and are not happy to see one of our major shareholders
in any financial difficulty but it has no direct and immediate implications for
us.''
He pointed out Coal Investments was only one shareholder in the company. Others
include Waverley Resources and Murray Johnstone, as well as the workforce.
The company has the finance it requires fully in place, with spending in the
current year at Longannet between #15m and #20m to raise output to two million
tonnes a year, and it expects to make a profit in its first trading period for
the 15 months to next March.
Formed in 1993 to take over some British Coal pits, Coal Investments has
invested heavily in opening the Markham Main pit in South Yorkshire and
Silverdale colliery in Staffordshire among others. But they have taken longer
to bring into production than expected, extending the company's initial
loss-making period.
Its shares have fallen heavily this year on fears it will require refinancing.
Coal Investments said the immediate reason for the share suspension was the
refusal of planning permission for a coal face at Hem Heath colliery,
Stoke-on-Trent. It has been reviewing its financial position since the
beginning of December.
Its longer term future is under-pinned by lengthy supply contracts with the
power generation industry, notably a five-year contract with National Power to
supply 2,800,000 tonnes a year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951220-000119</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951220-000119</DOCID>
<DATE>951220</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Gloom may not be all bad</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<FLAG>Business Comment</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974799059</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TEXTILE shares have been under-performing the market for some months, but the
general gloom was deepened yesterday by a miserable trading update from
Courtaulds Textiles, which was echoed by Coats Viyella.
The latter's shares managed to stay almost level at 169p but Courtaulds'
slumped 24p to 373p, and even mighty Marks &amp; Spencer slipped 8p to 431p on the
implications for its sales figures.
It is hardly surprising the industry is having a hard time given what it has
had to cope with. The weather was until recently all wrong, with an
exceptionally long hot summer followed by a mild and dry autumn. The result was
depressed demand for woollies and other outerwear. This was disappointing
because in the first seven months of the year, Courtaulds experienced good
trading. However, the second half is the more important.
Lack of demand hit margins which were already under pressure from higher raw
material prices, with cotton and wool, for example, showing big rises.
Household textiles have been a difficult area all year, partly because of the
poor housing market, with fewer people moving and replacing curtains, bed linen
and the like.
While clothing sales in the UK have returned to more normal levels in November
and December, in the US Courtaulds has been hit by destocking in the face of
weaker than expected demand. To cap it all, the strikes in France have affected
business there. The US and France account for more than a quarter of group
sales.
As a result, chief executive Noel Jervis warned that pre-exceptional pre-tax
profits would be down on 1994's #47.3m. This is in spite of a 16% advance in
operating profits on continuing operations in the first half. But the final
dividend will be held.
In Coats' case, demand and raw material problems have been partly offset by a
strong showing from the thread business, particularly in Europe and Brazil. But
it still sees 1995 profits as being below market expectations and also slightly
less than in 1994.
The trading statements could mark the nadir of the textile sector and further
share weakness could provide a buying opportunity.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951220-000120</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951220-000120</DOCID>
<DATE>951220</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Rationalisation only way for football to survive  Major partnership with minor strikes right chord</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Fergus McCann</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>25</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>arena</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974799060</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTTISH football needs to rationalise in order to survive. It is competitive
and, when the quality is high, a great attraction. So provided it can achieve
this and maintain it, it can be a success in Scotland. It is the national game
that every child wants to play well. It has no serious competition from other
spectator sports except an occasional golf or rugby event. And supporters care
passionately about their clubs.
The problem is that most parties want too much without giving a lot in return.
The media and the fans they influence want:
l A successful national team competing at the top level.
l Club success in Europe.
l The clubs to buy million-pound players.
l A massive youth coaching and training system producing star players and
costing millions of pounds.
l Entertaining football.
l Top quality stadia.
l Low admission prices.
The trouble is, with an economy and population the size of Scotland, we can't
have it all.
Meantime, players want six-figure contracts and nearly 40 supposedly
professional clubs who control the game. They want ``someone'' to keep them
alive. For several years that ``someone'' has mostly been the Celtic and
Rangers supporter, supplemented by some sponsor and television money shared
around.
On an average Saturday, the supporters of two of the 40 clubs pay out about
two-thirds of all the gate money. So the balance is definitely wrong. It is
clear that there are too many clubs, not enough customers - and just as clear
not enough quality players can be produced, or even attracted from elsewhere.
So how can we improve things? Not by making a so-called ``top'' division of 16
clubs. This just brings more mediocrity, and short-changes the customer. Yes,
the subsidy from Celtic and Rangers will increase, and be shared by more, but
weakening the two big clubs will not bring strength or quality.
Perhaps we can use our resources better. Here are some ideas.
To begin with, the Bosman decision, where the best players will move to the
most financially-successful clubs, means that we need a league that is
financially viable. It will have to be a small league. Eventually, we should
have no more than 10 fully professional clubs in a Major League, with
re-election of the weakest member required every two years - not relegation.
These clubs should enter partnerships with 10 Minor League clubs in other
towns, and 10 semi-professional youth ``farm'' clubs as well.
Just as important, the clubs who want to participate at the professional level
should be obliged to do what Aberdeen and Celtic have done, namely raise
capital and make their operations self-sufficient, not dependent.
Each club in the professional league should have internal capital of at least
#1.5m, invested by its owners, ideally to include its supporters or even its
local council. It should provide 15,000 covered seats or more, and be able to
sponsor a second-tier and youth network.
Some claim that the clubs play too many games. The answer is to extend the
season into summer, with a winter break - providing better conditions for
spectators, fewer injuries, and better pitches.
How can we finance the best training centres, football camps, youth coaching?
The Scottish Football Association has the money. Instead of developing Hampden
Park (already a less than ideal stadium with many seats at ground level 50
yards behind the goal line), using the clubs' and taxpayers' money, resources
should go to development of the quality of the game. Glasgow will soon have two
major stadia with a total of more than 100,000 quality seats. It needs a
national football stadium as much as it needs a national supermarket.
The recent talk of a 16-club ``top'' division, put forward by a group of
``takers'' does no service to the future of professional football in Scotland.
Aside from ignoring obligations to sponsors and television contracts, it
ignores the paying customer in favour of survival and self-interest.
 Fergus McCann, 1995.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951220-000121</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951220-000121</DOCID>
<DATE>951220</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Three plus two adds up to confusion</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By MURRAY RITCHIE European Editor</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>25</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974799061</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
EUROPEAN football's so-called three-plus-two rule which restricts the number of
foreign players in a side is outlawed with immediate and direct effect, the
European Commission insisted yesterday.
But the European Union of Football Associations (UEFA) immediately countered
saying that they held a different interpretation of the law and would be doing
nothing to change it.
Meanwhile, European soccer and other team sports have been left in confusion
about the rules.
Social Affairs commissioner Padraig Flynn told a committee of Euro-MPs in
Brussels that he was surprised at the reaction of UEFA to the EU's Court of
Justice ruling against the restriction of foreign players.
The court ruled last week in favour of Belgian soccer professional Jean-Marc
Bosman in a case which appeared to scrap the rule limiting the number of
foreign players which a side can field in a European game.
It did so because it said the present system conflicted with the free movement
of labour in Europe.
The ruling also seeks to end the transfer system in professional team sports on
which many small soccer clubs depend for survival.
UEFA had said on their first reaction to the court's decision that in their
view the three-plus-two rule might remain valid for European level competition.
``This interpretation seems to me to be clearly contrary to the court's
ruling,'' Flynn said.
He told Euro-MPs: ``The court's ruling was clear. The restrictions on the
number of EU players that clubs can play - the so-called three-plus-two rule -
are outlawed.''
Later, he issued a formal statement quoting from the court's ruling in which it
was made clear that ``Article 48 of the EEC treaty precludes the application of
rules laid down by sporting associations under which, in matches in
competitions which they organise, football clubs may field only a limited
number of professional players who are nationals of other member states.''
The court also said that nationality restrictions could be accepted only for
matches between national teams on grounds which are of sporting interest.
Flynn said: ``It is clear to me that from now on nationality restrictions are
illegal in European-level club competitions. I expect those affected to take
the necessary steps to change their rules to comply with the court's ruling. In
any event, all those affected should be aware that this ruling has immediate
and direct effect.''
But Alasdair Bell, the Scottish lawyer who           represents UEFA in
Brussels, said the ruling was not as clear as Flynn was making out and that its
wording required clarification.
``For the moment there is no next step,'' he said, ``there is just
disagreement. We have read this judgment one way and the commission has read it
another way. We are not going to do anything.''
Bell thought it likely that a challenge would be made again in the courts so
that clarification could be sought.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951220-000122</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951220-000122</DOCID>
<DATE>951220</DATE>
<HEADLINE>'Shire on goal spree</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>25</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974799062</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
East Stirlingshire 5,
Albion Rovers 1
THE home side improved their league fortunes with this win at Firs Park last
night. 'Shire struck after eight minutes when a pass from Hunter released
Lamont, who slotted the ball home.
Three minutes before the interval, Rovers' Gallacher put the ball past his own
keeper, and the match was finished as a contest just seven minutes into the
second half when Hunter supplied Dwyer with a chance which he finished from 10
yards.
Four minutes later Lee's cross was headed home by Dwyer, and then the striker
completed his hat trick with a fine shot from the edge of the six-yard box.
With six minutes remaining Rovers claimed a consolation goal through Willock.
</TEXT>
