<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951220-000123</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951220-000123</DOCID>
<DATE>951220</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Hammer of Scots looks forward - and back FOOTBALL LEGEND JOHNNY HAYNES HOPES THAT THE WEMBLEY ENCOUNTER WILL BE THE FIRST OF MANY</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By RAY HEPBURN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>25</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974799063</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
JOHNNY Haynes last night drooled over the prospect of Scotland meeting England
again next summer, just as the ``Hammer of the Scots'' relished the fixture
more than 30 years ago.
There was a disturbing confidence in his belief that the Wembley match in June
will go the same way as many of the home internationals he starred in, during
the late 50s and early 60s.
The man remembered by most Scots fans as the individual wholly responsible for
our blackest day, the 9-3 Wembley defeat in 1961, is now settled in business in
Edinburgh. The fact that, on that black day, he scored twice and laid on most
of the others lends some credence to the legend that has built up around him
since.
A mild-mannered Londoner, Haynes has made the most difficult of transitions,
from a man feared by a whole nation of football followers to one of its most
popular incomers. That makes the realisation that the former Fulham inside left
was one of the few world-class players produced by the United Kingdom just a
bit more palatable to take.
When he relaxes this afternoon in Harry's Bar in the West End of the capital,
enjoying Christmas lunch with a host of recently found Scottish friends, he has
still not decided whether to join the trek to Wembley next summer.
``I may sit tight and watch the game on television, although as the day draws
closer the appeal of the occasion will no doubt grow,'' Haynes reflected.
``It's amazing that it took a quirk of the draw on Sunday to resurrect a
fixture that the professionals wanted to play but the authorities were much
less keen about.
``The fact that it will be in a competitive tournament will surely add that
touch of spice and hopefully we will see the match become a regular in the
calendar again.
``In my time it was the highlight of the football season, whether it be at
Wembley or in front of that huge, noisy crowd at Hampden Park.
``Everyone made great stress of the will there was within the whole Scottish
nation to win but there was a deep determination among other players to come
out on top as well.
``They were superb matches, played with great players, although I seem to
remember that your goalkeepers weren't all that great - and you'll get no names
from me!''
It was almost certainly in the series against the Auld Enemy that the jibes
from the south at Scottish keepers were born, and much of the damage was
inflicted by schemer Haynes.
Aberdeen's Freddie Martin lost seven goals in 1955, Frank Haffey's career all
but ended with a concession of nine in '61, and Stewart Kennedy never recovered
from a 5-1 mauling in 1975.
``I still get stick from my pals up here about the old games, but you Scots
have this great talent for only remembering the good days,'' added Britain's
first #100-a-week player.
``There were so many good players around when I played, like Jimmy Greaves and
Jimmy Baxter, and it made the quality of the matches virtually assured.
``But there will be good players at Wembley next summer, when the fact that
it's a European Championship tie will give the game an exciting edge.
``I remember playing for England schoolboys in 1950, when the full team beat
Scotland 1-0 at Hampden in what was used as a qualifying tie for the World Cup
finals - sorry to bring up yet another victory. So it is some time since the
fixture has had such a meaningful tag.
``There are so few football matches nowadays that really grabs the imagination
of the public, that it's a shame that this, one of the greatest games, should
have been lost for six years.''
Whether at Wembley in the flesh, or from his Fountainbridge home, Haynes will
relive the past on June 15. Sadly, none of us will ever supersede his memory of
the match, from that hellish April day 34 years ago.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951220-000124</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951220-000124</DOCID>
<DATE>951220</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Cheap deal</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<FLAG>Business Comment</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974799064</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
DEAR, oh dear. National Westminster Bank has sold its NatWest Bancorp for a
total of $3260m (#2100m) compared with the $4000m rumoured in September when
chairman Lord Alexander said it was up for sale.
That caused a certain amount of bemusement in banking parlours. Nothing seems
more calculated to damage morale among staff, who in the US are much more
mobile than their UK counterparts and would want to take pre-emptive action
before the cost-cutting programme that normally means 20% redundancies imposed
by the new owner.
At the time several names were in the frame but not that of yesterday's buyer.
That is Boston-based Fleet Financial Corporation, which is actually getting
Bancorp slightly more cheaply than the headline figure.
It is paying the equivalent of #1700m in cash, but Fleet can reduce that by
offering #310m of its own stock. Also there is a final consideration of about
#370m spread over a maximum of eight years. So NatWest will not have quite so
many of the readies as first appears.
It has been clear for several weeks it would not get its hoped for price even
if other US banks have been changing hands at well over twice book value.
Something around two-and-a-half times would have been reassuring but this looks
like being about one-and-a-half.
NatWest shares jumped 19!sp to 649p on relief that the deal had finally been
completed and that it may buy back 100 million shares, which would lap up #650m
and increase earnings per share.
It is now talking about making acquisitions in fund management and life
assurance, but that seems somewhat late in the day.
Cruel it may be, but all the other UK High Street banks have clear strategies.
That of NatWest remains a mystery.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951220-000125</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951220-000125</DOCID>
<DATE>951220</DATE>
<HEADLINE>OECD sees UK rates stable</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<FLAG>business digest</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974799065</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SHORT-TERM British interest rates will remain unchanged as the economy grows
modestly above trend over the next two years, the Organisation for Economic
Co-operation and Development (OECD) said yesterday.
In its latest economic outlook, written before the Budget, the Paris-based
think-tank forecast the British economy would grow on average by 2.5% in 1996
and 1997, slightly down on its estimate for 1995 of 2.7%. These forecasts fall
short of Chancellor Kenneth Clarke's estimates of 2.75% growth this year and 3%
growth next.
``No further rise in interest rates is assumed over the next two years,'' the
OECD report said, as the impact of fiscal restraint becomes progressively less
important in 1996.
Slazenger sold
INDUSTRIAL conglomerate BTR has decided to sell one of the world's best-known
sports businesses for more than #300m. Dunlop Slazenger, with an annual
turnover of #275m, is being bought by venture capital group Cinven. BTR said it
aimed to complete the sale by early next year.
Trust disappoints
MURRAY Smaller Markets Trust significantly under-performed the World and
All-Share indices during the six months to end-November. The Murray
Johnstone-managed trust, which is invested in smaller markets around the globe,
achieved a total return on net assets of only 4.3%. During the six months, the
respective total returns on the World and All-Share indices were 11.4% and
11.7%. The #284m fund's interim dividend was raised by 2.6% to 1.60p.
Hess go-ahead
AMERADA Hess has been given Government consent to develop the Telford field in
the North Sea. The field has estimated reserves of 48 million barrels of oil
and 74 billion cubic feet of gas. Three production wells and three water
injection wells will be drilled next year and the first oil is expected in
1997. Crude output from the Telford field 100 miles north-east of Aberdeen is
expected to reach 30,000 barrels a day.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951220-000126</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951220-000126</DOCID>
<DATE>951220</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Rangers concede the road to goal was 'Well blocked Points dropped as Fir Park drought continues</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Jim Traynor Chief Sports Writer</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>26</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974799066</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE gap between Rangers and Celtic at the top of the premier division stands at
two points. The pursuit of the championship grows ever more intriguing.
Rangers went into Lanarkshire last night hoping to take from Fir Park three
points to keep Celtic at arm's length, but the Ibrox side can feel the breath
of their traditional rivals hot on the back of their neck. Motherwell proved
much more resilient than most of the 10,197 audience could have imagined,
especially when they lost another yet another key player before the kick-off.
Dougie Arnott had to be sent home on Monday morning because he was feeling the
effects of flu. Andy Roddie started the match, but it was really only in the
second half that he became any kind of menace.
The same was true of Alex Burns, but once these two started to use their main
attributes, their pace, they troubled Rangers' defence and the game became
vibrant and exciting. Chances were created and both keepers had to rely on the
structure of their goals to prevent goals. It should also be said that Andy
Goram and Scott Howie played well.
Rangers' manager Walter Smith, who always seems to look calm while others
around him are succumbing to their anxieties, felt from the kick-off the match
wore the look of a no-scoring draw. When he watched Gordon Durie's header hit
the crossbar and then Howie turn a net-bound shot by Durie over the top, his
instincts were confirmed.
However, he wasn't too disappointed with his team's performance given the
unavailabilities with which he still must contend - Ally McCoist and Stuart
McCall were added to the casualty list while Oleg Salenko and Paul Gascoigne
were the most notable absentees because of suspensions - although he pointed
out: ``I think it shows that we are not able to play as a unit because of those
who are missing.''
Motherwell also have serious injury concerns - they have been without key
players like Chris McCart and Tommy Coyne, in particular - but they have
persevered with their passing game and there were times last night when they
looked slick and dangerous.
Nevertheless, at this stage last season they were 18 goals better off, and when
Goram made a marvellous save from Paul Lambert early in the first half,
Motherwell manager Alex McLeish must have felt that the break in front of goal
was not going to come along, and similarly when a Burns shot, which was
deflected by Alan McLaren, hit the base of a post in the second half.
Still, McLeish had reason to feel positive. Brian Martin returned after injury
and played remarkably well in defence, although he also was able to push
forward in support of those ahead of him. But he hobbled off 12 minutes from
the end suffering from a hamstring strain.
Billy Davies also failed to finish the game because of injury and his place was
taken by Jamie Dolan with fewer than 10 minutes left. Dolan is regarded as one
of the most influential players in Motherwell's side, but he was dropped last
night perhaps as a reminder that more is expected of him.
The same could apply to Alexei Mikhailichenko, who started the game, but he
under-produced. It is must be one of the great regrets of recent times in the
premier division that he should still be unable to be consistently influential
because he does possess such sublime skills.
Motherwell's performance, as McLeish said, made a mockery of their position at
the bottom of the division, although the point taken last night meant they
moved into second-bottom place on goal difference. ``Time for a cartwheel,''
said McLeish, who refuses to become too downhearted.
``I'd be more upset if were not creating chances, but I think you can see where
our problem lies. However, I tell the players that a couple of results could
lift them clear because it is very tight in this division.''
McLeish was especially pleased with the contribution of Greig Denham, who was
making only his sixth appearance in the first team this season. The 19-year-old
showed a cool touch at the back and made some timely interventions.
``Yes, he does have the credentials,'' said McLeish. ``He looked as though he
had been at the heart of the defence all his life. He has the kind of mentality
which is essential at this level.'' The manager added that he continues to seek
a player to help ease Motherwell's problems, but pointed out: ``It isn't that
I've been inactive. It's just that I want to be sure the next player is the
right one.''
Teams
MOTHERWELL - Howie, May, McKinnon, Krivokapic, Martin, Denham, Lambert,
McSkimming, Burns, Roddie, Davies. Substitutes - Dolan, Essandoh, Ritchie.
RANGERS - Goram, McLaren, Gough, Petric, Robertson, Mikhailichenko, Ferguson,
Miller, McInnes, Durie, Laudrup. Substitutes - Durrant, Murray, McGinty.
</TEXT>
