<DOCID>GH951220-000127</DOCID>
<DATE>951220</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Raith are given a #2.3m kick-off</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>25</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974799067</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
PREMIER division newcomers Raith Rovers yesterday were given permission to
kick-off a #2.3m redevelopment of their Stark's Park ground at Kirkcaldy.
Following approval by Kirkcaldy district's development committee, the ground
will be transformed into an all-seater stadium, increasing capacity by around
1000, taking the total to 10,400.
Two new stands, each seating 3400 fans, will be built at each end of the
ground, while the existing railway stand will be extended to hold an additional
590.
Access to the ground will be provided underneath the stands, which will remove
congestion currently blighting Pratt Street on match days.
New floodlighting, snack facilities and entry for disabled supporters are
planned, while the pitch itself will be moved 2.5 metres south and have its
famous slope removed.
Work on the ambitious scheme is scheduled to start after the game against
Rangers on March 30 and be completed in time for the start of the 1996/97
season - the deadline laid down in the Taylor Report.
q DUNDEE manager Jim Duffy last night fined himself after having been booked in
a reserve match at Dens Park.
The player-manager was yellow carded for complaining about a penalty decision
which went against his team in Monday's clash with Livingston.
Duffy spoke up after a tackle by recent signing Barry Smith was penalised by
the match referee, even though a linesman signalled a corner when the ball went
out of play.
The Dens Park manager said: ``I felt it was a good tackle from Barry, but I am
fining myself for being booked, because I know by this stage in my career that
nothing I can say is going to make a referee change his mind over a decision.''
Duffy was able to recall that this is only the second time in his long playing
career that he has picked up a yellow card for dissent.
q.SOUTHAMPTON'S Paul McDonald last night asked Scottish managers to kickstart
his career. The 27-year-old former Hamilton winger has been on the transfer
list since Dave Merrington took over at The Dell in the summer.
A move to Burnley has already fallen through and #50,000-rated McDonald said:
``It has been bitterly disappointing since Merrington took over, and I would
jump at a move back to Scotland.
q.HIGHLAND League Clach have signed former Caley Thistle player Mike Andrew,
who was one of five given free transfers by Fort William to save money.
The 36-year-old will make his debut against his former club on Saturday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
