<DATE>951220</DATE>
<HEADLINE>MP in bid for more tickets</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By IAN PAUL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>25</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974799068</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AS THE English FA yesterday confirmed that each of Scotland's ties in the
European Championships already has been officially declared a sell-out, the
controversy over the allocation for the England-Scotland meeting on June 15 is
showed no sign of easing.
The argument has now been taken up by Scottish Labour's spokesman on sport,
John McAllion MP, who has called for a rethink on the allocation, suggesting
that there could be ``serious trouble'' as a result of the way the tickets are
to be distributed.
His intervention comes at the same time as the FA indicated that it might be
able to provide at best an extra 2000 tickets on top of the regulation 7000 set
aside for visiting fans.
McAllion has written to the English and Scottish Sport Ministers, Iain Sproat
and Raymond Robertson, urging them to raise the matter with the football
authorities. ``I find it unacceptable that Scottish fans will receive only 7000
out of a total of 76,000 tickets for this match.'' he said. ``There will be
enormous interest in the game, with up to 30,000 Scots wanting to travel to
Wembley to see it. Unless there is a rethink there could be a number of
flashpoints which could lead to serious trouble.'' He has made these points to
the ministers:
l.Since ticket touts are already boasting of exploiting the fans from Scotland
by charging up to #1000 a ticket, this could lead to serious trouble outside
the stadium;
l.Since touts will sell tickets to anyone prepared to pay their price, for any
part of the ground, there is a real danger of Scottish and English fans mixing
in the same part of the ground, with potentially explosive implications for
order at the game.
l.Police strategies for keeping rival fans separated, which is common practice
these days, will be rendered null and void.
``For all those reasons, it would be disastrous for the tournament organisers
to treat this game as just another tie. It is not. It is a special tie which
will be played in exceptional circumstances and should be treated accordingly
by the authorities.''
The avalanche of ticket applications has meant that the FA has closed the book
on the Wembley match and the games with Holland and Switzerland at Villa Park,
Birmingham.
Meanwhile in Glasgow, the SFA Travel Club organiser, Marjory Nimmo, continues
to be inundated with requests to join the only official organisation which can
supply tickets in Scotland.
q.MARTIN O'Neill yesterday confirmed his decision to resign as manager of first
division Norwich. O'Neill quit the Carrow Road club on Sunday but had been
understood to be having second thoughts.
q.HAMILTON are offering specially discounted tickets for the second half of the
season costing #50 for adults and #28 for senior citizens and juveniles. They
are for all the home games until May.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
