<HEADLINE>First Choice digs in for winter</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER SIMS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974799069</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FIRST Choice Holidays reckons it has done all it can to raise profits next year
and now it is all down to the fickle customer.
January is the vital month, when a quarter of all summer holidays are booked.
Only when February arrives will the industry know what the 1996 season holds.
First Choice has lopped off 1,500,000 holidays from capacity, to 1993 levels of
8,500,000. This will mean much better margins compared with discount-hit 1995,
if demand does not fall further. However early bookings are down by a quarter.
It has raised brochure prices by 9%, in line with competitors. Bookings have
been for higher margin packages so yield is up 17%.
It believes a #17m increase in advertising this year has lifted early bookings
2% to 12.9%. It is also well ahead in the 1995-96 winter season.
The group's airline, Air 2000, has reduced its summer capacity by 4% to
2,800,000 seats.
The usual first-half trading loss is coming down, last year running at #24m,
and chief executive Francis Baron is aiming to eliminate it over a number of
years.
The purchase of the minority holding in the Canadian operation will help. It
contributed 80% more profits at #7.9m in the year to October.
Through 126 redundancies and a requirement for 200 fewer summer staff, some #3m
a year has been removed from costs. Travel agents' commission has been cut to
about 10%.
First Choice confirmed its earlier indication of profits of #1.3m against
#16.3m for 1994-95 and maintained dividends of 3.85p. Net cash stands at #101m.
The shares were unchanged at 64p.
</TEXT>
