<HEADLINE>Starring role for Astra</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Ross Finlay</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974799070</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Starring role for Astra
ALTHOUGH the number of variants which made it Vauxhall's biggest model range
has been trimmed, there are still more than 40 catalogued types of Astra. The
body styles alone include three-door and five-door hatchbacks, a four-door
saloon, a convertible and a five-door estate.
The Astra offers a bewildering choice of engines. It is not just a matter of
1.4, 1.6, 1.8 and two-litre petrol engines, plus a diesel and a turbo diesel.
You would have to be a University Challenge contender to remember all the
sub-divisions like 1.4 Hi-Torq and 1.6 E-drive. The point is that there are
engines for all purposes, from the ultra frugal to the sporty 16-valve.
All the Astras have been improved by the styling changes introduced earlier
this year. I think that, of the whole considerable Vauxhall range, the Astra is
the car which best suits the ``family'' V-grille front-end. And the estate
version is one of the most attractive looking load carriers in its class, far
more neatly styled overall than the car which is its most obvious rival.
During 1995 the CDX was introduced as the top-line Astra estate. It comes as a
1.7-litre turbo diesel at #15,065, or with a choice of petrol engines, the
1.6-litre at #15,345 or the two-litre at #16,645, which puts it into the upper
part of the Vectra price range. The two-litre CDX estate has a very full
specification. Electronically monitored anti-lock braking is standard, and so
are twin airbags, air conditioning, alloy wheels, a CD player and an alarm
system which includes a sensor to set it off if a window is broken.
An Ecotec 16-valve engine with a 136bhp output gives the two-litre CDX good
reserves of power without too great a thirst. I drove the test car on a scamper
to Spain and Portugal. On motorways and dual carriageways it cruised very
easily at just under 3000rpm, relaxed but not especially quiet.
Less interested, during that mile-eating run, in acceleration than in fuel
economy, I noted that the Astra managed about 43mpg on its best cruising
tankful, compared with 37mpg on stretches which involved the inevitable dash
for a ferry.
Vauxhall has given it gas-filled shock absorbers and altered front suspension
settings, but it still seems more like a long-distance cruiser than a car for
scampering round the lanes. And this is another Vauxhall in which you are
better treating the gearbox smoothly, timing the changes properly, than just
shoving the lever unthinkingly about.
There are not many two-litre Astras around. The extra engine capacity, and the
extra power which comes with it, make the two-litre CDX an easier long-distance
cruiser and generally much brisker.
You can feel the Opel design influence in the front seats, which are harder
than some UK owners prefer. Certainly, I began to shuffle in mine much earlier
than I do in a base-model Astra Merit.
As a working estate, though, the CDX scores well. The concertina-type security
blind covers a large and well-shaped load area. It swallowed cases, bags and
boxes in some profusion, and kept them all well out of sight.
Two-up and with a well-laden rear compartment, the Astra maintained its ride
quality, and when required it would tackle winding roads with verve. One it
romped up happened to be a European speed hill climb championship course.
But, despite the extra performance compared with other models, this is a
practical rather than a semi-sporting estate. Vauxhall's preference for secure
understeer is obvious, and that makes sense, because a car which may be called
upon to carry considerable loads needs to handle safely at any weight up to its
recommended maximum.
</TEXT>
