<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951220-000131</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951220-000131</DOCID>
<DATE>951220</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Wise move</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<FLAG>Business Comment</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>974799071</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE six ``wise men'' who advise the Chancellor should in future be referred to
as the six wise persons following Mr Clarke's decision, announced yesterday, to
include two leading women economists in the panel of independent economic
advisers.
It is a move which will be much appreciated by those who feel, rightly, that
women are still grossly under-represented in many fields. There may be nothing
like the same number of women economists as men, but to treat the panel as a
solely male preserve would be an anachronism in this day and age.
Whether it actually plays any significant role in Treasury planning is beside
the point, though the views and opinions of outside commentators and
forecasters were always studied even before the panel (then with seven members)
was established by Norman Lamont in January 1993 to help restore credibility
after our ignominous exit from the ERM.
New member Kate Barker is the chief economic adviser at the Confederation of
British Industry, while Bridget Rosewell is a co-founder of Business
Strategies, an economics and business consultancy which also undertakes
research with the CBI, specialising on the regions.
Their respective jobs give them an ear to the ground on British industry and
should make them particularly hard headed and realistic when putting forward
their views. Some economists tend to live in ivory towers, though these days it
is common practice at the Treasury itself to second them to companies so they
can get a better feel of the subject, a form of work experience almost.
</TEXT>
