<HEADLINE>Jury finds case against AA man is not proven</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974799072</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A JURY found the case against an AA patrolman charged with causing the death of
a young Ayrshire woman by driving his van dangerously not proven yesterday.
Ms Alison Dunn, 20, of Arran Place, Ardrossan, died after the car in which she
was a passenger was involved in a head-on collision with Mr Bernard Coyle's van
on the A737 Johnstone by-pass.
Mr Coyle, 58, of Campsie Road, Slaemuir, Port Glasgow, who was an AA patrolman
at the time, denied causing her death by dangerous driving.
The jury at Paisley Sheriff Court returned a not proven verdict by majority.
As he left the court, Mr Coyle said he was ``greatly relieved'' his ordeal was
over.
Ms Dunn's father Ronald, of Springvale Street, Saltcoats, said he had to accept
the jury's decision and added: ``Whatever the result, it wouldn't have brought
our daughter back.''
During the trial, the court heard claims from lorry driver John McLelland, 29,
of Kirknowe Cottages, Howwood, Renfrewshire, that he had been driving his
articulated lorry east on the by-pass when Mr Coyle's van suddenly appeared
directly behind him.
He said he saw the van appear close to the rear of his trailer in his offside
wing mirror and it ``caused him some alarm''.
He said the van had pulled out as if to overtake his 40ft truck and there was
an almost instantaneous impact with the car, driven by Mr Andrew Allan, 24, of
Ardrossan Road, West Kilbride.
In a statement to police, he said he thought the van driver must have suffered
a heart attack or stroke, causing him to lose control of the vehicle.
However, Mr Coyle denied that he had driven on the wrong side of the road in
the seconds leading up to the collision and said he had no recollection of
driving behind Mr McLelland's heavy goods lorry or that he had tried to
overtake any traffic.
He claimed he had seen Mr Allan's car coming towards him on the wrong side of
the road and had tried to take evasive action by swerving to the right on to
the other carriageway, but could not avoid a collision.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
