<DOCNO>GH951220-000133</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951220-000133</DOCID>
<DATE>951220</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Second man shot in Belfast</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974799073</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ANOTHER man was shot dead last night in Belfast in what appears to be a purge
against suspected drug dealers.
Chris Johnston, 38, who was gunned down at a street corner in the Lower Ormeau
Road area, was the second murder victim in 24 hours and the fifth since the
campaign started last April.
Earlier Francis Collins, 4O, a father of five, was shot dead in front of his
wife at their chip shop in the republican New Lodge Road area. Although no
organisation claimed responsibility for that attack, police blamed the IRA.
Mr Johnston had been on bail on drugs charges and was returning to his home in
Cooke Street when he was ambushed. Gunmen had taken over a nearby house and
opened fired as he got out of his car.
Three men have been shot dead within a fortnight. All were alleged drugs
dealers.
As Northern Ireland Secretary Sir Patrick Mayhew prepares to meet Irish Foreign
Minister Dick Spring in Dublin today, these killings are bound to leave the two
Governments uneasy on future prospects for the peace process.
</TEXT>
