<HEADLINE>Friends buy Church centre</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER REEKIE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974799075</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CARBERRY Tower, the Christian residential conference centre near Musselburgh,
is to continue in that capacity although it is being sold by the Church of
Scotland.
The Kirk has sold the house and estate to the Friends of Carberry for #747,000.
Negotiations have been in progress with the friends' organisation since the
General Assembly of the Kirk agreed last May that its board of parish education
should sell Carberry at full commercial value.
Carberry Tower dates back to 1480 and stands in 35 acres of parkland. It was
gifted to the Church of Scotland in 1961 by the Elphinstone family.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951220-000136</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951220-000136</DOCID>
<DATE>951220</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Fraser now looks out in the coldl</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>22</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974799076</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IT COULD be the end of the road for three England quick bowlers, at least for
the time being, with the news that Angus Fraser has been left out of the side
for England's final practice match before the fourth Test, which starts in Port
Elizabeth on Boxing Day.
Fraser joins Devon Malcolm and Darren Gough, two other fast bowlers who were
expected to play a big part in South Africa, on the sidelines. All three were
omitted from the drawn third Test; and they now can expect the same fate when
battle resumes on Boxing Day.
Batsman Jason Gallian steps into the side to play South Africa's equivalent of
Combined Universities in Pietermaritzburg today, less than 24 hours after
having arrived from Pakistan, while Dominic Cork has been rested, making way
for Mike Watkinson.
The pace bowling spots are again occupied by Peter Martin and Mark Ilott, with
manager Ray Illingworth stating: ``We will probably pick our Test team from
these 11 players, plus Cork. We won't make any final decision until we've seen
the Port Elizabeth wicket. But Peter and Mark did well enough in Durban.''
Gough is injured, while Malcolm's speed is an advantage  only when pitches are
quicker than those England are likely to find during the rest of this Test tour.
Fraser is reliable on any surface. However, it appears the 30-year-old
Middlesex seamer is being left behind by younger players.
Gallian seems certain to face South Africa on Tuesday having flown in from A
tour duty to replace the injured John Crawley. ``I feel a bit wobbly, but I'm
looking forward to playing,'' said Gallian.
q JOHN Emburey is set to step into the breach for England today when the
43-year-old spinner will be named as twelfth man when England A face Pakistan A
in the third and final one-day clash at Sheikhupura Stadium.
His inclusion will complete a busy tour for Emburey who, as team manager, has
conducted the usual duties of organising and monitoring the players, and has
even been seen motivating lethagic Pakistani groundsmen and acting as an
emergency scorer in the second one-day contest.
AUSTRALIA yesterday beat West Indies in the World Series, limited-overs
competition. The Aussies won the match by 24 runs despite an improved
performance by the tourists in cold and blustery conditions at the Melbourne
Cricket Ground.
In reply to Australia's 249 for six from their 50 overs, West Indies subsided
to 225 all out in 49.1 overs and are still searching for their first win in the
triangular competition which also features Sri Lanka.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951220-000137</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951220-000137</DOCID>
<DATE>951220</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Power switch for watchdog on electricity</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By ELIZABETH BUIE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974799077</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE current chairman of the Edinburgh Sick Children's NHS Trust, Mr Graeme
Millar, has been named as the new chairman of the Southern Scotland Electricity
Consumers' Committee (SSECC), which covers the ScottishPower area.
He will take over next month from Professor Tom Carberry, who has held the post
for six years.
Yesterday, Mr Millar pledged to use his appointment to persuade ScottishPower
and all the other suppliers ``to address consumers' needs that would normally
come from a privatised competitive market''.
He said he saw the SSECC as sitting midway between the regulator Offer and
ScottishPower and other suppliers, acting as a source of information and advice
to both sectors.
Mr Carberry, who is retiring, said he had seen a marked improvement in consumer
services offered by ScottishPower since 1990/91.
He added that consumers would continue to benefit between now and 1998.
However, the SSECC was concerned that consumers had not benefited ``anything
like the same extent as the shareholders and the senior executives of the
companies''.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951220-000138</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951220-000138</DOCID>
<DATE>951220</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Peer admits to #4.5m car fraud. Aristocrat faces jail over burglary deception</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974799078</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LORD Brocket yesterday pleaded guilty to his part in a #4.5m classic car fraud.
The 43-year-old friend of the Prince of Wales, looking strained and worried,
announced his plea from the dock at Luton Crown Court.
He was told by Judge Daniel Rodwell QC that he could expect to go to prison
when the case was dealt with early next year.
The judge said he was ordering pre-sentence reports and warned the stately home
owner: ``I want to make it clear that by ordering a pre-sentence report it
doesn't mean you are going to receive anything other than a custodial
sentence.''
The length of the prison sentence could well be determined by what was said in
the reports, the judge said.
``I don't want you to be under any misapprehension whatsoever. Do you
understand?''
Brocket replied: ``Yes, your honour.''
The polo-playing aristocrat was charged under his name Charles Ronald Nall-Cain.
In the dock with him was 40-year-old mechanic Stephen Gwyther, of Cromer Hyde
Lane, Welwyn Garden City, Hertfordshire, American classic-car salesman Richard
Furtado, 41, of Bluebells, Welwyn Garden City, and financial consultant Michael
Campbell-Bowling, 59, of Cambria Street, Fulham, west London.
All four men were charged with conspiracy to defraud, alleging that between May
17 1989 and September 1 last year, they conspired together and with a fifth
man, Mr Mark Caswell, to defraud such persons as could be induced to part with
money.
Brocket and Gwyther pleaded guilty to the charge but Furtado and
Campbell-Bowling denied the offence.
Mr Peter Stage, for the prosecution, asked Judge Rodwell for 14 days so that a
decision could be reached on whether it was in the public interest to proceed
with a trial against Furtado and Campbell-Bowling.
Desmond De Silva QC, for Brocket, asked the judge to renew his client's bail,
saying he wanted to sort out ``matters of deep family concern so that he might
be allowed to attend to his affairs''.
Judge Rodwell adjourned the case for 28 days and all four men were granted bail.
The case arose from a burglary which Brocket claimed had happened in May 1991.
He said four valuable classic cars had been stolen from a showroom in a
converted stable block on the Brocket Hall Estate at Lemsford, Hertfordshire.
The cars, said to be worth millions, were a 1952 Ferrari 340 America, a 1955
Ferrari Europe, a Ferrari 195 Sport, and a 1960 Maserati Tipo Bird Cage.
At the time, Brocket claimed the thieves had carried out a ``professional job''
by removing the alarm system.
In fact, no burglary had taken place.
In February this year, the lord, along with four other men, was arrested and
accused of attempting to deceive insurance companies - the charge which he
admitted yesterday.
Mr Steven Barker, Lord Brocket's solicitor, said: ``He has pleaded guilty and
that is as a result of a decision he made some considerable time ago and he has
had to live with that decision for some time.''
The solicitor said there were matrimonial proceedings pending which would be
heard in the High Court next month. Mr Barker added: ``He fully accepts the
consequences of his action. He is prepared to go to prison but he is far more
concerned with the welfare of his children.''
The solicitor added that the hearing in the High Court would involve ``family
and residential orders being made''.
He asked the press and media to exercise care and caution in reporting personal
matters concerning Lord Brocket.
</TEXT>
