<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951220-000140</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951220-000140</DOCID>
<DATE>951220</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Monty is the top man</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>RAYMOND JACOBS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>22</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974799080</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
GOLF
THE #100 fine imposed on Colin Montgomerie for audibly swearing during the
Johnnie Walker world championship in Jamaica last week proved to be no
impediment to his being selected for the same sponsor's award as the European
Player of the Year. Towards the end of a frustrating season, during which he
had been second three times and in the first 10 on six other occasions,
Montgomerie in late August and early September ended a 12-month victory drought
by winning the German Open and Lancome Trophy.
That breakthrough occurred shortly after his sudden-death play-off loss to
Australia's Steve Elkington in the US PGA championship, one of the world's four
majors which have so far eluded him. Of that ambition Montgomerie said:
``Realistically, I suppose, I've got 32 more attempts, four a year until I'm 40
- after which I'm unlikely to get better.''
Montgomerie then made his contribution to Europe's unexpected Ryder Cup triumph
over the USA with two points out of five, one of which came in the singles,
where he had a 2 and 1 victory over the Masters champion, Ben Crenshaw.
A month later at St Andrews, Montgomerie's wins in the first four rounds helped
to take Scotland into the final of the Dunhill Cup for the third time, and
although he lost to Zimbabwe's Nick Price, Sam Torrance and Andrew Coltart had
already won to gain Scotland's first victory in the event.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951220-000141</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951220-000141</DOCID>
<DATE>951220</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Tomba is in trouble</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>22</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974799081</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SKIING
IT was a day of mixed emotions for Alberto Tomba yesterday, with success in a
World Cup slalom in Italy coming before the threat of the sack from the
Carabinieri.
Tomba celebrated his twenty-ninth birthday with victory on the piste at Madonna
Di Campiglio after Jure Kosir, quickest after the first leg, crashed.
``You can imagine what this win means,'' said Tomba, who has been under police
investigation after a photographer, who had sold nude photographs of him to a
magazine, complained the Italian had thrown a heavy glass trophy at him after a
World Cup race on Sunday.
Tomba was only third after the 59-gate first leg, but then pulled out all the
stops and flew down the piste on the second run to clock a combined time of
1min. 34.62sec. for his first victory of the season, with France's Yves Dimier
second. Overall World Cup leader Lasse Kjus, of Norway, finished third but was
later disqualified for straddling a gate, third place going to Italy's Konrad
Ladstaetter.
However, Tomba's joy was cut short with the news that he could be sacked from
the para-military Carabinieri police after the incident with the photographer.
The police have stated that their inquiry would ``examine the disciplinary
position'' of Tomba, who holds the rank of sergeant.
The freelance photographer suffered a cut hand after Tomba appeared to throw a
magnum of spumante and then a heavy glass trophy at him during a prize-giving
ceremony on Sunday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951220-000142</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951220-000142</DOCID>
<DATE>951220</DATE>
<HEADLINE>United are hit hard</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JOSEPH DILLON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>22</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974799082</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
HOCKEY
THE West district have suspended United WS for two-and-a-half years following
an incident at the Scotstoun complex last month when a female member of staff
was verbally assaulted by the United WS team and had to be escorted from the
pitch by Irvine, the opposition.
The woman had gone on to the field to terminate the game after the time for the
let had expired, and now the district have suspended the club for bringing the
game into disrepute.
As United WS had been warned in March as to theirconduct, they have also been
banned for the remainder of the season as their discipline has been showing no
improvement.
The severity of the suspension has surprised the club. Parvez Malik, the
secretary, said: ``Emotions are running high among some of our members for they
are horrified at the length of the suspension. We have contacted our solicitors
and will be appealing.''
No matter the outcome, the future of the club is in the balance. The captain of
the mainly Asian side, Khalil Malik, has suggested: ``Once this case is over we
will not play again,'' while president of the West district, Stuart Stephen,
said: ``We regret having to take this decision, but with United WS having
received written warnings, we have been left with no alternative.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951220-000143</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951220-000143</DOCID>
<DATE>951220</DATE>
<HEADLINE>American budget problems hit visas</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER REEKIE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974799083</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ROUTINE issuing of visas by American authorities in the United Kingdom was
suspended yesterday because of the renewed row between Congress and President
Bill Clinton over the federal budget.
The consulate generals in Edinburgh and Belfast, and the American Embassy in
London all stopped dealing with visas for non-immigrants and immigrants for the
duration of the US Government shutdown.
Routine services for American citizens were also suspended but the authorities
said UK citizens who were travelling to the US for business or pleasure for up
to 90 days did not need visas.
A spokeswoman at the London Embassy said the suspension had no connection with
the possibility of the American Consulate General in Edinburgh being closed.
Earlier this year, the Edinburgh consulate was threatened with closure, with
other consulates, as the US State Department sought economies.
Lothian region and Edinburgh councillors campaigned for it to stay open and
enlisted the support of two former presidents, Jimmy Carter and George Bush.
On October 27, a spokesman at the US Embassy said Congress had decided to defer
a decision on the Edinburgh consulate until a foreign affairs budget was
presented at a future date. A number of other consulates were being closed. Dr
William Crowe, the US Ambassador to Britain, indicated in a lecture in
Edinburgh that he was not optimistic about the consulate in Edinburgh
continuing.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951220-000144</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951220-000144</DOCID>
<DATE>951220</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Getting in key</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>MICHAEL TUMELTY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Book Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974799112</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
NO TWO ways about it. Whatever your role in the music business - performer,
student, educator, promoter, writer, broadcaster, librarian - the new Scottish
Music Handbook is an indispensible tool of the trade. But it will be of
interest, too, to the vast public which attends musical events throughout the
country, or anyone who wants to find the range of general or specific musical
activities in their region.
If you want to join a choir, book a ceilidh band, learn an instrument, buy an
instrument or get a broken one fixed, apply for a grant or make a recording,
book a hall or commission a composer, there is information in this handbook
which will take you where you want to go.
Well-organised in layout, the handbook embraces organisations, education, young
people's music, sources of funding, suppliers and services, clubs and
promoters, and so on.
By far the largest section is given to artists, who are categorised by genre -
classical, country music, early music, folk and traditional, jazz, light music,
music from other cultures, rock.'n'.pop, and community. Within these categories
there are further subdivisions according to type. So, in folk and traditional
music, for example, you can trace, alphabetically, lists of agents, bagpipers,
fiddlers, mandolin players, Uillean pipers, and more.
The statistics alone give an astonishing account of the volume, density, and
geographical spread of music activity in Scotland. I counted 73 choirs, nine
opera companies, 11 chamber orchestras, 22 symphony orchestras, 50 separate
sources of funding, and 125 composers and arrangers.
The sections are packed with information: across the entries on choirs, for
example, you can learn where they're based, their historical background, the
type of music they perform, their regular rehearsal and concert dates, and
contact numbers.
Each section of the book is prefaced by an essay. These are by a range of
contributors and are of varying quality, from the informative to the
self-serving and superficial.
These notwithstanding, the handbook is an immediately useful goldmine of
information and contacts. Copies can be obtained from most good bookshops or
directly from the Scottish Music Information Centre, 1 Bowmont Gardens, Glasgow
G12 9LR. (Tel 0141 334 6393) Price #12.99.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
