<HEADLINE>Swiss kick out Hodgson</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>26</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974799113</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SWITZERLAND, in the same group as Scotland in next year's European
Championships in England, surprised the football world last night by sacking
their English-born manager, Roy Hodgson.
Hodgson, who coached the Swiss to their first World Cup finals in 30 years last
year, was recently appointed manager of Italian Serie A side Inter-Milan, and
had intended to stayed on as part-time manager of Switzerland, making it clear
he wanted to lead the country to their first European finals in June.
However, the Swiss football federation yesterday named Portugal's Artur Jorge
as national coach. Jorge will commence his duties on January 1 on a contract
that runs through to the end of the 1998 World Cup finals in France.
Jorge, 49, has an impressive pedigree in European league football, but he may
face an uphill struggle in winning over Swiss players and public. He was
previously coach of Benfica, but left in September on amiable terms after 15
months of mediocre results. Before that, he had a successful three-season stint
as coach at Paris St Germain. Under Jorge's guidance, they won the French title
in 1993-94.
Scotland manager Craig Brown, whose side face Switzerland at Villa Park on June
18 in Euro '96, said: ``I've got to be pleased with this news because I am
fully aware of Roy Hodgson's abilities as a coach,'' said Brown. ``He is a
personal friend and a great coach, so I can't be too disappointed that
Switzerland will be under new management. But I can't say much more because I
don't know much about Artur Jorge.''
